<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Cancels US Symphony Concerts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China canceled two concerts by the Boston  
Symphony Orchestra in Beijing, saying the ``barbarous'' NATO 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia ruined the atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	The orchestra planned four performances in Japan and two  
performances in China to celebrate Seiji Ozawa's 25th anniversary 
as music director. Ozawa is Japanese and was born in northeastern 
China when the area was occupied by Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	After a performance today in Osaka, Japan, the orchestra had  
been scheduled to perform in Beijing on Wednesday and Thursday. 
Premier Zhu Rongji and President Jiang Zemin were scheduled to 
attend the concert Thursday in the Great Hall of the People. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're terribly disappointed,'' Boston Symphony Orchestra  
spokeswoman Caroline Smedvig said in Japan. ``We'd planned this for 
a very long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Demonstrators hurled rocks and debris today into the U.S.  
Embassy in China, trapping American diplomats inside their compound 
in a third day of protests against the bombing, which U.S. 
officials said was accidental. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese media reported three people were killed when NATO  
missiles struck the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on Saturday. More 
than 20 were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The China Performing Arts Agency, the government promoter, said  
in a letter addressed to Ozawa and dated Sunday that the NATO 
bombing made the concerts impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	The orchestra provided a copy of the letter to The Associated  
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``This barbarous atrocity of NATO has evoked the utmost  
indignation of the Chinese government and people,'' said the letter 
signed by Zhang Yu, general director of China Performing Arts 
Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency ``has decided to postpone hosting the tour,'' the  
letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smedvig said the orchestra would return to the United States  
on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
