<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Washington has no plans to support drug  
crop substitution programs in rebel-controlled areas of Colombia, 
the deputy U.S. drug czar said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia's largest guerrilla group is proposing such a project.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's important that the alternative development is carried out  
in an area that is under government control,'' Thomas Umberg told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. support for a project to wean Colombian peasants off the  
cultivation of coca, the raw material of cocaine, in a 
Switzerland-sized demilitarized zone depends upon the return of 
government troops, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Andres Pastrana cleared the southern region of troops  
six months ago to facilitate peace talks with the country's most 
powerful rebel group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, 
or FARC. Last week, government and rebel negotiators agreed on an 
agenda and Pastrana has extended the troop pullout for an undefined 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LA REALIDAD, Mexico (AP) -- Southern Mexico's Zapatista rebels  
ended a jungle meeting with more than 2,000 supporters Monday after 
asking them to take part in other social struggles. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of the Zapatista National Liberation Army urged  
organizers of their national referendum, held in March, to organize 
as supporters of student, worker and farmer struggles ``beyond 
recognition of Indian rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea apparently is to build links to other Mexican protest  
movements. But the meeting ended without a firm statement on the 
results of the referendum. 
</P>
<P>
	Zapatista supporters say 3 million people across Mexico cast  
ballots in the unofficial referendum, 95 percent of them expressing 
support for Zapatista positions. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a move to build support for the movement, whose rebellion  
against the government has been stalled by a cease-fire since two 
weeks after it started on Jan. 1, 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace talks have been stalled since 1996 over a dispute with the  
government over how to enact constitutional reforms guaranteeing 
Indian rights in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela has accepted a proposal by  
Colombia's largest rebel group to take part in that nation's peace 
talks, Venezuela's foreign minister said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia announced Sunday that  
it wants to form an international commission to help advance talks 
aimed at ending Colombia's three-decade civil war. Representatives 
from Venezuela, Mexico, Spain and Costa Rica would make up the 
commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel said President  
Hugo Chavez would name Venezuela's representatives this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela hosted two meetings earlier this year between  
Colombian government officials and leaders of the country's 
second-largest rebel group, the National Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- There are reasons to blame the  
pro-Iranian Islamic Jihad for the 1992 Israeli Embassy bombing, 
Argentina's high court said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from the Supreme Court of Justice said the court  
believes the attack ``was organized and carried out by the 
terrorist group Islamic Jihad,'' the local news agency Diarios y 
Noticias reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel has long contended that Iranian groups were behind that  
attack and a 1994 bombing of a Jewish cultural center that killed 
95 people. Iran has repeatedly denied involvement. No suspects have 
been detained. 
</P>
<P>
	The court statement also said its evidence pointed to an  
explosion originating outside the embassy, and not within the 
embassy as some earlier reports suggested. The attack killed 29 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) -- Officials evacuated three small  
villages near the base of the Volcano of Fire Monday in 
west-central Mexico after it blasted out ash and glowing rock. 
</P>
<P>
	The crater, one of three at the Colima Volcano complex, has been  
intermittently active over recent months, sometimes shoving out 
slow-moving lava as well as ash and rock. 
</P>
<P>
	Jalisco state officials said they had evacuated 160 people from  
the villages of Juan Barragan, Los Machos and El Acostadero after 
the eruption. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuelan authorities said Monday  
they will ask Colombia to protect truck drivers who are waging a 
strike along the border and paralyzing commerce between the 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Drivers in the Venezuelan state Tachira charge that Colombian  
drivers are taking away their business and that operating in 
Colombia is too dangerous because of leftist rebels and other armed 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is elemental that Venezuelan drivers be given protection.  
They should enjoy the same protection that Colombian drivers get in 
Venezuela,'' said Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck drivers say regulations implemented by the Andean  
Community trade block have allowed Colombian drivers to monopolize 
transport between the two countries. The Colombians pick up food 
and goods in Colombia and then transport them throughout Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	The Venezuelan drivers want the opportunity to pick up goods  
themselves in Cucuta, a city on the Colombian side of the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
