<HEADLINE> 6,000 Baby Cribs Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government announced the recall of more  
than 6,000 ``Next Generation Pisces Cribs'' on Monday. Slats on the 
headboards and footboards could come loose, raising the danger that 
an infant could become trapped and hurt or killed, the Consumer 
Product Safety Commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries have been reported, although the company, Generation  
2 Worldwide, a Dothan, Ala., manufacturer, has received 12 reports 
of loose slats. 
</P>
<P>
	The cribs involved in the recall are model number 67-8100. They  
were manufactured between March 4, 1997, and March 10, 1998. The 
model number and date of manufacture can be found on a sticker at 
the bottom of the headboard. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is offering free replacement endboards, instructions  
and tools to make the cribs safe. Generation 2 Worldwide has 
received 12 reports of slats on these cribs coming loose. No 
injuries have been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers should immediately stop using the cribs until they  
have been repaired. To order the repair kit or for more 
information, call Generation 2 Worldwide at (800) 736-1140, 
extension 224, between 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. EDT Monday through Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
