<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Criticizes Large Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	McLean, Va. (AP) -- Calling the launch of a national campaign  
against violence at the White House Monday an ``extraordinary 
gathering,'' Hillary Rodham Clinton said Monday that schools today 
have gotten so big that students can get lost in the system. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way that children can be made to feel special and  
valued, that they can be given the attention and support they need, 
and especially if they are vulnerable or susceptible to the culture 
and therefore more likely to be prone toward aggression that 
anybody will ever notice,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said that to her, one of the saddest comments after  
the Littleton, Colo., massacre was made by the principal of 
Columbine High School, who said he never heard about the ``trench 
coat mafia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Well how could he? Those were just a small group of kids in a  
very large institution,'' Mrs. Clinton said in a speech at The 
Madeira School, a private girls' high school in suburban 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now most of our schools are no longer communities, and  
too many kids are passing through them anonymously. ... So we are 
going to have to change the way we think about, how we build and 
construct and organize our schools,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said she was ``proud'' of the discussion on youth  
violence Monday at the White House. She said that as the bombing of 
a federal building in Oklahoma City ``took the sting out of so much 
of the irresponsible anti-government rhetoric, after Littleton, it 
is very hard to cartoon one another. ... Because the truth is that 
we do have some hard questions to ask ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady quoted one of the gun manufacturers at the  
meeting who said he ``would support some of the president's 
proposals for sensible gun control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He said 'you know, we are parents too, we think people do have  
to exercise responsibility, but we can do more to make it easier 
for parents to keep guns safely away from children,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Mrs. Clinton said, gun control activist Sarah Brady  
said she was ``honored to be in a room with the gun manufacturers, 
because for the first time people were not hurling invectives at 
one another but trying to decide what is it we can do to make it 
easier to make sure that guns have safety locks, for example.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also said that the television networks and other media  
companies that attended ``are finally facing up to the fact that 
they cannot escape their share of the responsibility for this 
culture in which we live.'' This shows, she said, ``some cracks in 
the walls of deniability, and that in itself is a big step 
forward.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
