<HEADLINE> Amy Fisher Released From Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBION, N.Y. (AP) -- Amy Fisher walked out of prison Monday after  
serving nearly seven years for shooting her lover's wife in the 
head in a case that once dominated tabloid headlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher, known as the ``Long Island Lolita'' in tabloid  
headlines and television movies, wore sunglasses, kept her head 
bowed and did not answer questions as she walked past reporters and 
photographers outside the Albion Correctional Facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Accompanied by her mother and attorney Bruce Barket, Ms. Fisher  
got into a van and later boarded a charter flight from Rochester to 
Farmingdale, Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's obviously extremely happy and thankful to the people who  
brought this about,'' Barket said, including shooting victim Mary 
Jo Buttafuoco, who helped win an early release for Ms. Fisher. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've all placed a significant amount of trust in her and  
she's not going to let them down,'' Barket said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barket said Ms. Fisher would be living in the New York City area  
and would work in a fashion-industry job. She will be on parole 
until 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher's story sparked a fountain of stories at the time of  
the shooting. She was portrayed as a scheming, spurned, teen-age 
temptress who seduced Mrs. Buttafuoco's husband and brazenly 
blasted the rival for his love on the Buttafuoco front doorstep. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher pleaded guilty in 1992 to assault for shooting Mrs.  
Buttafuoco and was sentenced to five-to-15 years in prison. Ms. 
Fisher, now 24, was a 17-year-old high school senior when the 
shooting happened. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge agreed last month to a shorter prison sentence for Ms.  
Fisher, making her eligible for release if the state Parole Board 
agreed. The board voted 2-1 last week to grant her release. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Buttafuoco, 37 when she was shot, survived and forgave Ms.  
Fisher in court last month. The two had corresponded for several 
months and Mrs. Buttafuoco helped get Ms. Fisher's sentenced 
reduced. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Fisher had been having an affair with Joey Buttafuoco, the  
38-year-old owner of an auto body shop. He pleaded guilty to 
statutory rape and served six months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In a $220 million lawsuit that was dropped in February, Ms.  
Fisher claimed she was raped by five corrections officers at 
Albion. U.S. District Judge Richard Arcara wrote that the lawsuit 
``reads more like a cheap dime store novel or a script for a 
tabloid television show than a pleading in a federal lawsuit.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
