<HEADLINE> Yugoslavians Play on Despite War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's volleyball and soccer teams are trying to find ways  
to play despite war in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	The world volleyball federation ruled Monday the country can  
play abroad, but it cannot hold international competitions while 
there is fighting in Kosovo or other parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``In principle, Yugoslavia is not suspended,'' federation  
president Ruben Acosta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday in Luxembourg, the European Volleyball Confederation  
had suspended Yugoslavia from competition until June 15 because of 
safety concerns for athletes, officials and spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	Acosta said his group will send coaches, nets and more than 500  
volleyballs to Kosovo refugee camps in Albania and Macedonia next 
month to teach youngsters the sport. He said three coaches will 
remain in each area for a month. 
</P>
<P>
	European soccer's governing body said Yugoslavia is eligible for  
the European 2000 Championship but cannot play games at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia will resume qualifying play June 5 in Dublin against  
Ireland. Yugoslavia's game June 9 against Malta will be played at a 
neutral site. The Yugoslav soccer federation has until Wednesday to 
suggest a place. 
</P>
<P>
	A UEFA committee handling the rescheduling of Euro 2000 games  
involving Balkan countries plans to review developments in the 
war-torn area on May 25-26 during a meeting in Barcelona, Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
