<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 10:26:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Service Targets Web Credit Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Web merchants stung by credit-card fraud are  
getting help in identifying potentially risky transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	HNC Software Inc. of San Diego, which tracks activity in more  
than 260 million credit card accounts, is unveiling a service to 
combat the growing problem of credit card fraud on the Internet, 
The Wall Street Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	HNC will assign a ``score'' to each transaction that indicates  
the probability for fraud. Internet merchants will then set 
thresholds for their systems to accept or reject a transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the service called eFalcon, Web merchants help HNC  
build a profile of the credit card user, by providing information 
about what products were ordered over the Internet and what Web 
pages the user viewed on the merchant's Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know what transactions you've made. We have a profile of  
you and what you look like and what your charging pattern is,'' 
Allen Jost, HNC's vice president of business development, told the 
newspaper. ``We have more transaction data than anybody in the 
world and we use them to build rich profiles on each client.'' 
</P>
<P>
	HNC said the information is kept confidential and not used for  
cross-marketing purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	By adding Web transactions, HNC increases its database to  
improve the accuracy of its predictions. HNC plans to collect a fee 
of a ``few pennies'' for each transaction, the newspaper said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 16:13:33 </DATE_TIME>
