<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buckeyes Lose Sanderson, Radojevic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Two players expected to be mainstays for  
Ohio State next season -- sophomore forward Jon Sanderson and 
7-foot-3 junior college recruit Aleksandar Radojevic -- will not be 
with the Buckeyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Jim O'Brien and athletic director Andy Geiger issued a  
statement late Monday afternoon that Sanderson, who started every 
regular season game last year, has decided to transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	Radojevic, a native of Montenegro who played last season at  
Barton County (Kan.) Community College, was ruled ineligible by the 
NCAA for playing four games and a total of 19 minutes for a 
Yugoslavian professional team. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio State, which lost to eventual national champion Connecticut  
in the Final Four, returns its top two scorers, Michael Redd and 
Scoonie Penn. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanderson, a 6-7 native of Lexington, averaged 5.4 points and  
3.4 rebounds last season as the Buckeyes went to the Final Four. He 
was replaced in the starting lineup by freshman guard Brian Brown 
in the NCAA tournament, however, with O'Brien citing matchup 
advantages by going with a smaller lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	``My family and I have made a decision that it would be in my  
best interest to leave Ohio State and pursue my basketball career 
and education elsewhere,'' he said in the statement. ``I will 
forever be thankful for the privilege of being a Buckeye.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanderson said he had not decided where he will transfer.  
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien said, ``We wish Jon nothing but success.''  
</P>
<P>
	Radojevic was considered one of the top junior college centers  
in the nation. He helped Barton County to the junior college 
national championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA ruled he cannot play for any member institution.  
Radojevic, who had considered going to the NBA prior to signing 
with Ohio State, will probably make himself available for the NBA 
draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``Alek signed a professional contract with a club team in  
Yugoslavia,'' Geiger said. ``Ohio State and the NCAA learned of his 
situation and Ohio State appealed to the NCAA for reinstatement. 
Ohio State recommended a 10-game penalty because Radojevic received 
$13,000 in compensation. We are disappointed with the NCAA's 
decision.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
