<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flynt Obscenity Trial Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Potential jurors at Larry Flynt's obscenity  
trial were warned Monday that they may have to watch as much as 40 
hours of sexually explicit videos and were asked whether they could 
frankly discuss the material with strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynt, 56, the publisher of Hustler magazine, sat quietly at the  
defense table with his eyes closed as jury selection began. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his brother, Jimmy, 52, are charged with pandering  
obscenity, disseminating material harmful to a juvenile, conspiracy 
and engaging in a pattern of corrupt activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges stem from the alleged sale of an explicit video to a  
14-year-old boy at the Hustler Magazine &AMP; Gifts store, which Jimmy 
Flynt manages. Each brother could get 24 years in prison and 
$65,000 in fines. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynt said his attorneys hadn't decided whether he would  
testify. The trial is expected to last four or five weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Patrick Dinkelacker readily dismissed 18 prospective  
jurors, including the mother of the county prosecutor, who said 
they might face a personal or financial hardship by serving on the 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Dinkelacker gave the remaining 47 jury candidates detailed  
questionnaires that warned about the explicit nature of the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynt said he hoped for a jury of ``people with an open mind and  
who really believe in their individual rights and civil liberties, 
and that they have the right to view and read whatever they want 
to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1977, Flynt was convicted of pandering obscenity for selling  
Hustler magazine. He served six days of a 7- to 25-year sentence 
and was released pending appeal, and the conviction was overturned 
in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
