<HEADLINE> S.F. Chronicle To Evaluate Holdings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Chronicle Publishing Co. said Monday it has  
hired an investment firm to evaluate its holdings, which include 
the San Francisco Chronicle newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chronicle and its rival, the San Francisco Examiner, have  
long been the subject of rumors that have one paper buying out the 
other or the two papers merging. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release, Chronicle Publishing said it hired Donaldson  
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette of New York to review and evaluate the company's 
financial, business and strategic plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither the company's board nor its shareholders have made any  
decisions pertaining to potential future actions,'' Chief Executive 
Officer John B. Sias said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sias did not return telephone calls from The Associated Press.  
</P>
<P>
	Chronicle Publishing is privately held. It owns the Chronicle,  
the Bloomington Pantagraph in Illinois and the Worcester Telegram &AMP; 
Gazette in Massachusetts. It owns television stations KRON in San 
Francisco; KAKE in Wichita, Kan.; and WOWT in Omaha, Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	Its holdings also include a Web site and two book publishing  
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The morning Chronicle and the afternoon Examiner are published  
under a joint operating agreement in which they share business 
operations but have separate and competing editorial departments. 
The papers split profits under the agreement, which expires in 
2005. 
</P>
<P>
	Hearst Corp. owns the Examiner.  


</P>
</TEXT>
