<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Campaigns in New Hampshire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEDFORD, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. John McCain's outspoken backing of the  
NATO bombing campaign in Kosovo has won him increasing support 
among New Hampshire Republicans. But as they get a closer look, GOP 
voters may find they disagree with the presidential candidate on an 
array of other issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking his party, the Arizona Republican supports more gun  
control, campaign finance reform -- including a ban on corporate 
contributions -- and greater regulation of health maintenance 
organizations. He also bashes the big tobacco companies, who have 
returned the favor by portraying him in television ads as an 
advocate of higher taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, 62, told a group of businesspeople Monday that unlimited  
``soft money'' contributions by businesses to political parties 
give corporations an undue influence over legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer is comprehensive finance reform, including a ban on  
both labor union and corporate donations to candidates, he told 
about 140 people at a ``Politics and Eggs'' breakfast sponsored by 
the New Hampshire Business and Industry Association, the New 
England Council and several major corporations. . 
</P>
<P>
	``I would support no campaign finance reform that did not  
require that every union member give their permission before the 
union spends money on politics,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the good news. The bad news is I would also require  
that every stockholder give their permission'' before businesses 
could make political contributions, said McCain, cosponsor of a 
campaign finance bill that died in the Senate last year. 
</P>
<P>
	On tobacco, McCain said his position has ``gotten me a lot of  
name recognition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it is his support for the bombing campaign against  
Yugoslavia and push for tougher action, including the use of ground 
forces if necessary, that has put him in the public eye recently. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's background as a Navy fighter pilot and prisoner during  
the Vietnam War gives him more credibility on Kosovo than the other 
candidates, said Kedar Gupta, a GT Equipment Technologies executive 
and Democrat who attended the breakfast. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a straightforward guy -- he's paid his dues,'' Gupta said.  
``John McCain is the one person ... who understands fighting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A recent poll done by the University of New Hampshire for CNN  
and WMUR-TV found 14 percent of likely Republican voters would 
support McCain if the election were held now. That put McCain in a 
statistical dead heat for second place with Elizabeth Dole, who 
drew 16 percent. The same poll found 37 percent favored Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush, while the other candidates got 7 percent or less. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Smith, director of the UNH Survey Center, said Monday  
that McCain's gains in the polls came mostly from voters who think 
the United States should send ground forces into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sen. McCain has managed to distinguish himself by his support  
of the military campaign in Kosovo,'' Smith said. However, McCain 
has an uphill battle to gain the name recognition that helps Bush 
and Dole, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other question is whether McCain will be able to expand his  
base of support, or whether his popularity will decline when the 
Kosovo crisis wanes, said Bruce Berke, a Statehouse lobbyist and 
supporter of U.S. Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, polls show the public backs the NATO bombing campaign in  
Kosovo. If that support should disappear, the effect on McCain's 
campaign remains to be seen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kosovo has enabled him to be front and center on an issue that  
is front and center with this nation,'' Berke said. ``I think once 
you do get beyond Kosovo, a lot of the decisions he is taking and 
has taken are difficult issues for success in Republican 
primaries.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
