<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Continues To Slide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gold futures continued their sharp descent Monday on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange amid fears world governments, which 
control about 25 percent of world supply, will begin a selling 
frenzy in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, cocoa futures tumbled.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell 1.9 percent as market participants continued to react  
nervously to the United Kingdom's announcement last week that some 
415 metric tons from its 715 metric-ton stockpile will be sold off 
in coming years as the government moves into better-yielding bond 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain's decision caused a measure of calm because officials  
made an announcement before taking action, but investors are 
worried other governments will begin dumping their reserves without 
notice in a bid to make the biggest profits before others join in. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1990, central banks in the Netherlands, Austria, Belgium,  
Argentina and Australia have sold some of their holdings -- all 
without prior warning. There are fears now that other European 
countries and the new European central bank will do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for June delivery fell $5.30 to $278.40 an ounce. Gold  
posted a 20-year low last August of $271.60 an ounce and could test 
that mark in coming days, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures fell sharply on the Board of Trade of the City of  
New York, caught in a tug-of-war between expectations for ample 
supplies and heavy buying at recent lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivory Coast, which accounts for about 40 percent of the world's  
cocoa supply, is expected to have a bumper midyear harvest after 
final numbers are tallied, pressuring prices already sensitive to 
ample world supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Port arrivals are coming during the traditional off-season for  
buying cocoa, used in making candy. But some manufacturers have 
taken the opportunity to buy when prices tumble, helping buoy a 
fundamentally weak market. 
</P>
<P>
	July cocoa finished down $30 to $973 a ton after falling as low  
earlier as $950 a ton. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans gained on the Chicago Board of Trade as  
investors covered positions ahead of the late-afternoon release of 
farmer planting progress reports, which were expected to show 
continued behind-average fieldwork as a result of recent rains. 
</P>
<P>
	In a surprise, however, the U.S. Agriculture Department figures  
show several days of clear skies allowed farmers to catch up on 
their planting. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said 55 percent of intended corn acreage was  
planted by last week, up from the 52 percent average and only 3 
percent below levels at the same time a year ago. And 12 percent of 
soybeans were planted, up 1 percent from the five-year average, but 
down 2 percent from year-ago levels that produced a record crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices for corn in particular also gained amid forecasts  
for rain in parts of the Midwest later this week, which could 
further delay plantings as the window of opportunity rapidly 
closes. That could mean fewer acres planted to corn this year, a 
prospect that would help reduce supplies just as world demand is 
expected to show some improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	July corn rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.21 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose  
1 1/2 cents to $4.79 a bushel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
