<HEADLINE> Machine Tool Production Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Spending on machine tools in March rose 44  
percent from the previous month, but declined 48 percent from the 
year-ago March, according to a study by two industry groups 
released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies spent an estimated $479 million for machine tools in  
March, the Association for Manufacturing Technology and the 
American Machine Tool Distributors' Association said in a joint 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	That easily surpassed the revised estimate of $333 million spent  
in February but fell short of the estimated $914 million spent in 
March 1998, the groups said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first three months of 1999, spending totaled $1.2  
billion, down 45 percent from the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the pickup in March orders over February is positive, it  
closes a quarter still significantly off last year's pace,'' said 
Don F. Carlson, AMT president. ``It does not signal a turnaround in 
the machine tool market. Expectations remain that the second half 
of the year will yield stronger results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts consider demand for machine tools a reliable indicator  
of the strength of the manufacturing sector and the overall 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics are compiled from figures submitted by companies  
participating in the U.S. Machine Tool Consumption report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
