<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'The Mummy' Wraps Up No. 1 Spot / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Mummy'' took advantage of a pre-''Star  
Wars'' box office drought to wrap up this year's biggest opening 
weekend with $44.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The cat-burglar caper ``Entrapment'' slipped to second with  
$12.2 million and cyberspace adventure ``The Matrix'' was third 
with $6 million, estimates showed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	With lukewarm reviews, many expected ``The Mummy'' -- a special  
effects-filled story of an ancient Egyptian priest who returns from 
the dead -- to do mediocre business before dropping out of sight 
when the ``Star Wars'' prequel opens May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, it probably did three times as much business as  
people were expecting,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, a Reel Source Inc. 
movie analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other films have been just hanging around the box office, but  
this had that kind of 'Raiders of the Lost Ark' appeal,'' he said. 
``When you finally get a release like this, everybody goes wild.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With most studios giving a wide berth to the opening of ``Star  
Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' Universal Pictures' daring 
move to open ``The Mummy'' just 12 days earlier may pay off if 
word-of-mouth is favorable. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Mummy'' -- which also had the best non-summer opening ever  
-- was an impressive showing for star Brendan Fraser and easily beat 
his previous high opening of $16.5 million for ``George of the 
Jungle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The first five days of 'Star Wars' will be sold out, so 'The  
Mummy' may actually benefit by being the only alternative,'' 
Bucksbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also opening in wide release this weekend was the high school  
student government satire ``Election,'' starring Reese Witherspoon 
as a compulsive do-gooder and Matthew Broderick as a frumpy civics 
teacher. 
</P>
<P>
	The film opened in only a handful of theaters three weeks ago  
and rode a wave of positive reviews to fifth place this weekend 
with $3.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Analyze This'' crossed the $100 million mark this week,  
earning $1.8 million for seventh place. It has grossed a total of 
$100.9 million in 10 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Weekend ticket sales were 12.2 percent higher than the same  
weekend last year, when ``Deep Impact'' debuted as ``City of 
Angels'' and ``Titanic'' began to slip. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated grosses for Friday through Sunday at North American  
theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Inc., with final figures 
to be released today: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``The Mummy,'' $44.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Entrapment,'' $12.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The Matrix,'' $6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Life,'' $3.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``Election,'' $3.3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Never Been Kissed,'' $3 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Analyze This,'' $1.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' $1.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Cookie's Fortune,'' $900,000.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``Shakespeare in Love,'' $765,000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
