<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators Adopting Bank Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At the urging of Senate Banking Committee head  
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, federal regulators are taking action to help 
keep politics out of bank examinations. 
</P>
<P>
	The four major bank-regulatory agencies are adopting or making  
more formal existing policies barring bank examiners from 
discussing politics with bankers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm issued a statement Monday saying the agencies' actions  
will ensure that bank inspections ``are free from political issues 
or considerations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The examination process can be trying enough for a banker  
without injecting the poison of political pressure,'' Gramm said. 
``These new policies should help prevent abuses by making sure that 
both (government) examiners and bankers are aware that exams should 
be above board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm is a fierce critic of the 1977 Community Reinvestment Act,  
which requires banks to make loans to the poor and minorities in 
the areas in which they operate. As Congress drafts sweeping 
legislation to overhaul the financial services laws, Gramm has 
tried to keep the government's community-lending ratings for banks 
from becoming a standard for allowing them to merge with other 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	His action has put him at odds with the Clinton administration,  
which has threatened to veto a financial services bill passed by 
the Senate last week on grounds it would hurt the community lending 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm said the agencies took the action in response to his  
having recently criticized the Office of the Comptroller of the 
Currency, part of the Treasury Department, for allowing its 
examiners to solicit positive ``political'' statements from bankers 
about the community lending law. 
</P>
<P>
	After the comptroller's office issued a formal directive to its  
employees prohibiting political communications, Gramm said, the 
other three agencies told him they planned to follow suit. They are 
the Federal Reserve Board, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and 
the Office of Thrift Supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Tanoue, the FDIC chairwoman, told Gramm in a letter last  
week that the agency had a long-standing unwritten, informal policy 
of ``carefully avoiding any form of political communications by 
examiners'' with banks or their affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDIC has had no problems in this area for more than 60  
years, Ms. Tanoue said. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to Gramm's request last month, the agency made the  
policy formal and distributed it to employees, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, the Federal Reserve recently formalized its  
75-year-old policy of avoiding any form of political communications 
with banks, a spokesman for the central bank said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	William Fulwider, a thrift office spokesman, said the agency  
planned to issue such guidelines to employees within the next few 
weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:55:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed Looking Into Partnerships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. Monday confirmed that  
it has been holding periodic talks with European aerospace 
companies, including Airbus Industrie, to explore possible 
partnerships. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the past couple of years we've had talks with Airbus,  
that's nothing new,'' said Jerry Langheim, a Lockheed Martin 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Times reported Sunday that executives from Airbus  
Industrie and Lockheed Martin have been talking about an alliance, 
including the possibility of a Lockheed partnership in Airbus' 
proposed superjet, the A-3XX. Another scenario had Lockheed joining 
in a military transport plane Airbus has been planning. 
</P>
<P>
	Langheim said Lockheed does not intend to make any  
announcements, nor does it intend to invest in Airbus. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued Monday, Lockheed Martin said senior  
managers talk periodically with counterparts from European 
aerospace companies ``about the possibilities of working together 
on programs of mutual interest, such as new military airlifters or 
as a subcontractor for components of Airbus commercial airliners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said an alliance could be beneficial to both sides.  
</P>
<P>
	``Airbus really needs more partnerships if it's going to develop  
new product,'' said Richard Aboulafia, director of aviation at Teal 
Group Corp. ``Lockheed needs to grow its aeronautical sector if 
it's to grow as well.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:31:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Morgan Group Recommended in A's Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- A group headed by Hall of Famer Joe  
Morgan and former Oakland Athletics executive Andy Dolich received 
a recommendation from city and county leaders Monday in their bid 
to buy the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-1 vote rejected commissioner Bud Selig's suggestion that  
bids from two groups be forwarded to major league owners. 
</P>
<P>
	The other group is led by San Mateo lawyer Michael Lazarus and  
includes former pitcher Steve Stone, now a broadcaster for the 
Chicago Cubs; and Bob Watson, a former A's coach and a former 
general manager of the Houston Astros and New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just decided the community doesn't want to do it,'' Alameda  
County Supervisor Gail Steele said of Selig's idea. ``I might have 
played the chess game differently but everybody involved wanted to 
play it that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Morgan group is backed by Bob Piccinini, chairman of  
Modesto-based Save Mart Foods, who provided the $12 million 
deposit. The other group is backed by Arizona banker Lyle Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendation was made by the Oakland Alameda County  
Coliseum Authority, which consists of two supervisors and two 
councilmen. Final approval of the purchaser rests with major league 
owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the City Council cast an advisory vote recommending the  
Morgan-Dolich group. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement worked out in October with current team  
owners Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann, the authority had until 
Tuesday to forward recommendations to the baseball on who should 
buy the A's for about $120 million. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement with Schott and Hofmann, the Athletics  
agreed to stay in Oakland through the 2001 season, with a right to 
extend their lease on a year-to-year basis through 2004. When 
Schott and Hofmann bought the A's for $85 million in 1995, they 
signed a nine-year lease at the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	The new owners of the A's will be required to keep the team in  
Oakland through at least 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
