<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Times for St. Louis Closer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A sure sign the closer is in trouble is if he's  
warming up in the second inning and pitching in blowouts. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the situation Juan Acevedo of the St. Louis Cardinals  
found himself in Saturday night. There was absolutely nothing on 
the line when he entered a 7-0 game in the sixth inning and worked 
two low-key scoreless innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has humbled me,'' Acevedo said. ``Not that I wasn't  
humble before, but this really has humbled me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acevedo was Mr. Automatic the second half of last season when  
the Cardinals converted the former starter and he responded with 15 
saves in 16 opportunities. As Mark McGwire put the finishing 
touches on his record 70-homer season, Acevedo didn't allow a run 
in his final 16 outings. 
</P>
<P>
	Lately he's been automatic trouble. Allowing seven earned runs  
in 3 2-3 innings in four outings led to his middle-inning stint 
Saturday. In that span he had two blown saves, a loss and a victory 
he didn't deserve. 
</P>
<P>
	He's seeing the flip side of the life of a closer and learning  
to deal with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``A reporter kept asking me in spring training how I was going  
to be able to bounce back from something like this, and I laughed 
at him,'' Acevedo said. ``I really never thought this would happen 
to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Tony La Russa hoped it wouldn't, but knew a setback  
probably was inevitable because of the pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those are the toughest three outs in baseball,'' La Russa  
said. ``You know what they did for eight innings. You watch the 
game and you know how much the club invested in it, and it's all on 
your shoulders. I mean, it's a hellacious job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After one of those miserable performances, Acevedo worked out  
his frustrations by rearranging the furniture in his apartment. 
After spoiling seven shutout innings by Darren Oliver Friday night, 
allowing the Pittsburgh Pirates to score two runs and tie the 
score, he got a pep talk from his brother on the telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Acevedo's biggest problem is a lack of confidence in his slider  
and curveball. His reluctance to throw the offspeed stuff has made 
him predictable. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you lose the feel for the breaking ball because the role  
you're playing is so critical, anyone would have the tendency not 
to want to get hurt with it,'' pitching coach Dave Duncan said. 
``So you avoid using it. He's pretty much been fastball, fastball, 
fastball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hence, the remedial work. For at least the next few days, the  
Cardinals likely will try Ricky Bottalico and Scott Radinsky in the 
closer role as Acevedo works out his problems. Among the 
adjustments are a new grip for the curve and slider. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go back out there, that's the only way you get over  
it,'' Acevedo said. ``I would understand if they want to go to 
Ricky or Rad more often now in the ninth, but I'm not worried about 
that. I just want to get my stuff back together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Acevedo believes one of his problems is he's in perfect health.  
Last year he battled elbow woes, frequenting an acupuncturist for 
relief, but his stuff hasn't been the same since the pain went 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel great and I think that's part of the problem,'' Acevedo  
said. ``Last year I always had that achy elbow or forearm and I was 
in one of those zones that was unbelievable. Somehow, I've got to 
get back to that zone.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:32:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Loyal Son Who Wants To Be President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- As the loyal son, George W. Bush was aboard  
for the unhappy ride when his father lost the White House in 1992 -- 
a rough year but an instructive one, he recalls now. 
</P>
<P>
	There's less stress, he says, in running himself. Although he is  
just beginning his active presidential campaign, he is leading the 
polls as an undeclared candidate for the 2000 Republican 
nomination. The tense times are coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a big difference between being the loyal son who went  
to the wall for his dad, as opposed to being the person who's 
looking to lead,'' the Texas governor said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Publicly, the political relationship between the George Bush who  
was president and the George Bush who would like to be is more than 
circumspect. They seldom appear together. When they did, briefly, 
two weeks ago at coincidental events in Dallas, there were 
photographs, no questions. 
</P>
<P>
	The former president has made one fund-raising appearance for  
his son, in Phoenix, invitation-only, remarks unrecorded. When he 
spoke at a Republican National Committee fund-raising dinner in 
Washington on April 28, he didn't mention Gov. Bush. ``I believe it 
is essential that we put a Republican in the White House,'' he 
said. ``We have good people who are running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Obviously, he is for the one with his name. ``He says that if  
you choose to go for it, I'll be with you, son,'' Bush said in an 
ABC interview Monday. ``And as importantly, my mother has said if 
you go for it, I'll be with you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Should George W. make it in 2000, the Bushs would be the only  
father-son presidents since John Adams, the second, and John Quincy 
Adams, the sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Bush is readying his campaign with his own team. There may  
be back channel contacts for advice from veterans who served in his 
father's administration, but publicly, only one is a top Bush 
advisor. 
</P>
<P>
	Condoleeza Rice, provost at Stanford University, served at the  
National Security Council for President Bush. She is on Gov. Bush's 
exploratory campaign committee, and advises him on foreign policy 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Name recognition was a major plus for Bush when he upset a  
Democrat to win election as governor of Texas in 1994. The asset is 
indelible, and he has his own record in office, plus a landslide 
re-election in 1998, to run on now. His sensitivity about claiming 
an inheritance from his father's presidency shows when a questioner 
mentions the Bush-Colin Powell doctrine that framed the use of U.S. 
troops in the Persian Gulf War. Answering, Bush gently amends that 
to make it the Powell doctrine. 
</P>
<P>
	A question about the contrast between the uptight Bush of the  
1992 campaign and the seemingly more relaxed Bush of this one 
brings a moment of reflection on then and now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw my Dad losing,'' Bush said. ``It was a very difficult  
time. And it's hard for me to share what it means for me to see 
somebody who's given me the greatest gift of all, which is 
unconditional love, going down the tubes. And it hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And can he really be more relaxed about his own fortunes?  
</P>
<P>
	``I am. I am. This is a different level of intensity ...  
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety-two was a rough year. It was a difficult year.''  
</P>
<P>
	It is said in a softened voice, but with a trace of bitterness  
at ``people who should have been his allies and his strong 
supporters'' but turned away when they saw the president's 
prospects slumping. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I learned a lot about Washington and loyalty,'' Bush  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``... I've just got a better appreciation of what to expect.  
Some people will be for me because they think I'd be a good 
president, a good man. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people will be for me because they think it's in their  
best interests -- and I've learned to discern the difference,'' Bush 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that will make for a more honest candidate.'' He  
catches himself because he isn't supposed to be one yet. 
``Operation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody loves a winner,'' he said. ``You learn the character  
of people when things are not so good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Things are good now, of course. Bush is the GOP leader. The  
polls are promising. There's campaign money in the bank, and more 
coming every day. 
</P>
<P>
	But there will inevitably be difficult times, too. Times to test  
the strength of the early endorsements Bush is reaping. 
</P>
<P>
	And to test the candidate himself.  
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
