<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 15:34:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise, Ending Two-Session Skid / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury prices reversed a two-session skid on  
Monday as investors looked to take advantage of the highest yields 
since last June. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32  
point, or $2.81 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, fell to 5.79 percent from 5.81 percent late 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors scooped up bonds, which now have some of the highest  
yields in nearly a year. But the gains were limited in advance of 
Treasury sales of $15 billion of five-year notes on Tuesday and $12 
billion of 10-year notes Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices were higher Monday in the broader market as well.  
Prices of short-term Treasury securities rose between 1/32 point 
and 3/32 point. Intermediate maturities rose 1/16 point, reported 
Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.59 percent as the  
discount fell 0.01 percentage point from late Friday to 4.47 
percent. Six-month yields were 4.68 percent, as the discount rose 
0.01 percentage point from late Friday to 4.51 percent. One-year 
yields were 4.74 percent as the discount fell by 0.02 percentage 
point from late Friday to 4.52 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, remained unchanged at 4.69 percent from late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds was unchanged at 122 11/16. The average 
yield to maturity slipped to 5.33 percent from 5.37 late Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
