<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Louima Cross-Examined in Cop Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Haitian immigrant who says he was brutalized  
by police in a stationhouse bathroom admitted he lied about some of 
his story Monday but blamed medication, a faulty memory and bad 
advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was under medication,'' Abner Louima said when confronted  
with past comments contradicting his testimony from last week. 
``And my memory, it wasn't clear like it is now, today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The allegation that police sodomized Louima with a broomstick  
shocked the community. Along with this year's police shooting of an 
unarmed African immigrant, it has strained relations between the 
Police Department and the black community. 
</P>
<P>
	During Louima's second day on the stand in the trial of five  
white police officers, defense attorney Marvyn Kornberg suggested 
Louima changed his story to support a lawsuit suit filed on his 
behalf by O.J. Simpson ``Dream Team'' lawyers Johnnie Cochran Jr., 
Barry Scheck and Peter Neufeld. 
</P>
<P>
	``Has your memory gotten better since you retained Mr. Cochran,  
Mr. Scheck and Mr. Neufeld in a $155 million lawsuit?'' Kornberg 
asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, sir,'' Louima replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Kornberg, who represents Officer Justin Volpe, cross-examined  
Louima in a booming voice. The witness sometimes responded with 
long pauses and blank stares. 
</P>
<P>
	Kornberg noted that Louima, while in the hospital in 1997, gave  
a statement to a grand jury saying no other officer held him down 
as Volpe allegedly sodomized him with a broken broomstick. Last 
week, Louima testified that an officer restrained him by grabbing 
the chain of his handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima, 32, had also identified Volpe as the officer who hit him  
in the head with a police radio -- contradicting grand jury 
testimony in which he couldn't identify the attacker. 
</P>
<P>
	The witness insisted his trial testimony was more accurate  
because ``I've had more time to think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Louima left the stand to demonstrate the position  
he was in at the time of the alleged bathroom assault. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't on my knees,'' he said, leaning over. ``My feet was  
down ... Like I was close to down, but I wasn't completely on the 
ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Louima also said he took the advice of some fellow Haitian  
immigrants and lied when he said that an officer had said ``it's 
Giuliani time'' -- a reference to the law-and-order policies of 
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. 
</P>
<P>
	``You lied under oath to the grand jury, didn't you?'' Kornberg  
pressed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yes,'' Louima replied quietly.  
</P>
<P>
	Louima was hospitalized with severe internal injuries after the  
incident, which prompted demonstrations against police brutality. 
In opening statements, Kornberg suggested the injuries may have 
come from homosexual intercourse. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe is among four officers charged with beating Louima because  
they believed -- mistakenly -- he had sucker-punched Volpe in a melee 
outside a Brooklyn nightclub in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe and Officer Charles Schwarz are also charged with the  
bathroom attack. A fifth officer is charged with covering up the 
assault. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
