<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 24.34  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed today after a choppy  
session that saw some profit-taking in blue chips and renewed 
interest in technology shares. The Dow Jones industrial average 
closed down 24.34 at 11,007.25 after fluctuating between positive 
and negative territory throughout the session. On Friday, the Dow 
rose 84.77 to close at 11,031.59, its second record high close for 
the week and its second finish above 11,000. Broader stock 
indicators were mixed today. The Nasdaq composite rose 22.76 to 
2,526.38. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        11007.25  - 24.34
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1733  Declines 1286  Unchgd  526
NYSE Volume:         752,398,550
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online129 3/4  + 11 9/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1340.30  - 4.70
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          787.08  -   .21
Nasdaq Composite Index        2526.38  + 22.76
Gold(final) -    $277.60    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.

</P>
<P>
	Tenn. Jury Sides With Tobacco Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Three of the nation's largest tobacco  
companies were cleared today of liability in the deaths of three 
smokers whose families claimed the companies' cigarettes were 
responsible. All three had lung cancer. The Shelby County Circuit 
Court jury returned its verdict during the fourth day of 
deliberations in the case against Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds 
Tobacco Co. and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. The smokers' 
families claimed the companies knowingly sold a dangerous product 
and tried to cover up the risks. They were seeking more than 
$431,000 for medical bills and unspecified punitive damages. In 
similar cases this year a San Francisco woman with inoperable lung 
cancer was awarded $26.5 million and the family of a Portland, 
Ore., man who died of lung cancer was awarded $81 million. 

</P>
<P>
	EU Urged To Reconsider US Beef Ban  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American leaders made a last-minute attempt  
today to persuade the European Union to end a 10-year ban on 
hormone-treated U.S. beef. The EU faces in four days a deadline to 
end the ban or face U.S. trade retaliation. Thursday is the 
deadline set by the World Trade Organization for the union to lift 
the hormone-treated meat ban. In its ruling a year ago, the WTO 
said the ban is illegal and is not supported by the proper risk 
analysis. The Clinton administration has threatened to impose 100 
percent tariffs on more than $900 million worth of European 
products to retaliate for the ban. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockheed Looking Into Partnerships  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. today confirmed that  
it has been holding periodic talks with European aerospace 
companies, including Airbus Industrie, to explore possible 
partnerships. ``That's nothing new,'' said Jerry Langheim, a 
Lockheed Martin spokesman. The Seattle Times reported yesterday 
that executives from Airbus Industrie and Lockheed Martin have been 
talking about an alliance, including the possibility of a Lockheed 
partnership in Airbus' proposed superjet, the A-3XX. Langheim said 
Lockheed does not intend to make any announcements, nor does it 
intend to invest in Airbus. Lockheed shares were at 42 7/8, down 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Delphi Progressing Before Spinoff  
</P>
<P>
	TROY, Mich. (AP) -- Delphi Automotive Systems Corp., the  
auto-parts manufacturer soon to be independent from General Motors 
Corp., has no more money-losing plants, is getting cooperation from 
its unions to cut costs and is winning more non-GM business, its 
chairman said today. As the world's largest parts-maker, Delphi 
also plans to be a major player in the industry's consolidation 
through an aggressive acquisition drive, J.T. Battenberg III told 
reporters before departing on a worldwide roadshow to raise his 
company's profile among investors. 

</P>
<P>
	NBC, Xoom.com, Snap.com Join Forces  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is joining forces with Web directory service  
Snap.com and Xoom.com, an electronic commerce site, to form a new 
Internet company in an attempt to broaden its online presence. 
Under the deal announced today, the new company, NBC Internet or 
NBCi, will operate under the Snap name online but will include 
content from NBC and the trademark peacock brand. NBC will own 
about half of the new venture and is contributing several of its 
online properties, including NBC.com and Videoseeker.com. NBC is 
also contributing a 10 percent ownership stake in CNBC.com, the 
parent of Snap, to the new venture. Xoom.com shareholders will own 
about a third of the company, and CNET will own about 13 percent. 
NBCi will be a publicly traded company. Stock of NBC's parent 
General Electric was down 1 3/16 at 108. 3/4 today; Xoom.com was up 
6 3/4 at 81 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Comcast Earns $73M on Cable Growth  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Comcast Corp., the third-largest cable  
operator in the country, earned $73.5 million in the latest quarter 
on strong growth in its cable operations. The earnings, which 
worked out to 12 cents per share, were ahead of analyst 
expectations and compared with a loss of $86 million, or 11 cents 
per share, for the first quarter of 1998. Revenues for the quarter 
ending March 31 rose 9.5 percent to $1.37 billion from $1.25 
billion. Growth in Comcast's digital cable and high speed Internet 
access businesses helped boost operating cash flow by 38 percent. 
Comcast shares were at 37 7/8, up 1 3/4 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Banks Plan Loan-Rate Cut  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Leading Japanese banks said today that they will  
lower the long-term prime lending rate, the rate for loans of a 
year or more to the best corporate clients, to a record low 1.9 
percent from 2.3 percent. The long-term prime rate is a benchmark 
for other bank loans. Lower rates on home mortgages and automobile 
and small business loans could follow the cut. The Industrial Bank 
of Japan and The Nippon Credit Bank Ltd. said they would lower the 
rate beginning tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Chevron May Buy Texaco  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chevron Corp. reportedly is discussing buying  
Texaco Inc. for about $42 billion in stock in a deal that would 
unite the nation's third and fourth biggest energy companies. But 
The Wall Street Journal reported today that the companies aren't 
near an agreement and said a combination faces enormous hurdles. 
Large oil companies have been rushing to unite because of falling 
oil prices and the need to cut costs. However, industry analysts 
say a Chevron-Texaco merger would make less sense than other recent 
oil company mergers because both companies have been cutting costs 
on their own and Texaco last year formed a refining partnership 
with Shell Oil, which would present a regulatory stumbling block. 
Chevron shares were at 96 1/8, up 1 3/8. Texaco shares were at 65 7/8, down 
1 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft To Invest $600M in Nextel  
</P>
<P>
	RESTON, Va. (AP) -- Microsoft is investing $600 million in Nextel  
Communications in a deal that will provide Nextel's wireless phone 
customers with e-mail and other basic Internet services through an 
MSN Web portal. The agreement would leave Microsoft with a 4.25 
percent stake in Nextel, whose other major owners include Motorola 
and the McCaw family. The Microsoft deal valued Nextel's shares at 
$36 each, slightly shy of Friday's closing price of 36 3/8. 

</P>
