<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mother Sentenced for Stomping Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) -- A woman who pleaded guilty last year to  
stomping death her stepdaughter 38 years ago was sentenced Monday 
to five years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Rae Morgan, 57, who now lives in Texas, was living in a  
rural Mascoutah farmhouse with her husband in 1961 when his 
4-year-old daughter, Michelle Morgan, died. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors at Scott Air Force Base, where the girl was pronounced  
dead, considered the death child abuse, but civil authorities took 
no action at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	The reopened investigation into Michelle's death began in 1994  
when her brother, George, a Missouri prison inmate, wrote a letter 
seeking clarification of his sister's death certificate. It said 
she died from viral pneumonia. 
</P>
<P>
	George Morgan, who was 8 at the time of the death, said he  
recalled watching his stepmother stomp on the girl's stomach in a 
fit of anger. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Mrs. Morgan told authorities that Michelle had  
fallen off a wood pile while chasing rabbits. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement reached last October, when Mrs. Morgan  
pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter, St. Clair County 
Circuit Judge Jan V. Fiss could have sentenced her to no more than 
eight years in prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
