<DOCNO> APW19990510.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:05:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Speedway Sets Date for Formula One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- For more than 80 years, the only race at the  
Indianapolis Motor Speedway was the 500. Next year, three of the 
world's major racing series will visit, all within a span of four 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway announced Monday that the U.S. Grand Prix is set  
for Sept. 24, 2000, returning Formula One to the United States for 
the first time since 1991. FIA, the sport's international governing 
body, still must approve the date. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Grand Prix joins the IRL's Indy 500 and NASCAR's  
Brickyard 400 at the country's most famous track. The deal for the 
Formula One race was made in December. 
</P>
<P>
	``It re-emphasizes that Indianapolis Motor Speedway is the  
racing capital of the world, both in terms of the quality of the 
events here and the quantity of the crowds that attend and watch 
worldwide,'' speedway spokesman Fred Nation said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said a crowd of about 200,000 is expected for the new race,  
which would make it the third-largest single-day sporting event in 
the world in attendance. The Indy 500, which will be run on May 28 
next year, annually draws up to 400,000 fans; the Brickyard 400, 
expected to be run on Aug. 5, 2000, drew about 320,000 last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction already has begun to accommodate a 13-turn road  
course that uses part of the existing 2 1/2-mile oval and a new 
section that runs through the infield, along with 36 new pitside 
garages with suites atop them. The road course is expected to be 
finished by this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The only current Formula One race in North America is the  
Canadian Grand Prix, held in Montreal in June. The last Formula One 
race in the United States was in Phoenix in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway president Tony George and Bernie Ecclestone, chief  
executive of Formula One Administration, which governs the 
international circuit, have agreed to a multiyear commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway's costs are expected to top $25 million, and  
Formula One will retain all television revenue from the event. 
Tickets go on sale in the fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
