<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fleet, BankBoston Make Appointments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston announced  
Monday key management appointments for the institution resulting 
from Fleet's planned acquisition of BankBoston. 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, Fleet Chairman and CEO Terrence Murray will be  
chairman and chief executive officer of the Fleet Boston 
Corporation, the nation's eighth largest bank with assets of $180 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	BankBoston Chairman and CEO Chad Gifford will be president and  
chief operating officer. He will succeed Murray as CEO on Dec. 31, 
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugene McQuade will remain as chief financial officer and will  
report to Murray. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes less than two months after the March 14  
announcement that Fleet would acquire BankBoston in a deal valued 
at about $16 billion. The deal is expected to close this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointments brought few surprises, said Thomas Theurkauf,  
an analyst with Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods Inc. in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization chart is a clean and sensible one, he said,  
with a good smattering of both Fleet and BankBoston personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think whenever you put a deal together it pays to make these  
decisions sooner rather than later,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The closing of the deal is several months off. This clears the  
air of who's going to be in charge.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
