<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornado Victims Keep the Faith </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. (AP) -- The battered pews were salvaged from  
a ruined church. The muddy blue-and-white tent above the 
parishioners had been donated. 
</P>
<P>
	A bent and scratched sign welcomed an overflow crowd of  
worshippers Sunday who counted their blessings in the shadow of the 
twisted remains of Ridgecrest Baptist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if God took your home, but a tornado did, and God  
will rebuild your life,'' Pastor Tom Duckett said. ``I know that 
the church is the people. A building is just a building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Workers have been using bulldozers and chain saws to remove the  
debris that once was the Ridgecrest sanctuary. ``God One, Tornado 
Zero'' was written on one worker's hard hat. 
</P>
<P>
	Bridge Creek, a town of two churches, a school and 8,000  
scattered residents, doesn't even appear on a map. It was here that 
a tornado touched down May 3, plowed northward and killed at least 
41 statewide. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven of the victims died in the Bridge Creek area.  
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, women in dresses and others in donated jeans and  
T-shirts wore corsages for Mother's Day. ``Mamas, I'm glad you're 
here and your babies are safe,'' Duckett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amy Garretson rocked her 4-month-old daughter, Sydney. She and  
her husband, who works for the church, hid in a 5-foot-wide cellar 
while the twister destroyed their home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are here to be reminded how lucky we are. We have our  
lives, friends who are helping us and God,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hugs lasted longer and the amens were louder during Sunday's  
two-hour service. A group of church members embraced a man whose 
wife was killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The list of people missing was cut from four to one Sunday when  
two British tourists checked in with relatives and a local 
resident's wife realized her husband was mistakenly listed. 
</P>
<P>
	Still missing is Tram Bui, a 23-year-old woman from Seminole.  
Ms. Bui was blown from underneath a highway overpass where she 
huddled with her family as the tornadoes struck. 
</P>
<P>
	The same powerful system of tornados that ripped across Oklahoma  
also slammed into Haysville, Kan., tearing apart the sanctuary of 
the First Christian Church and scattering hymn books throughout the 
rubble 
</P>
<P>
	About 150 members also gathered there Sunday to sing the very  
songs that the hymnals had been opened to as they fell amid the 
debris. Five people died in the Kansas storms. 
</P>
<P>
	Voices filled the hallways of Rex Elementary School with the  
sounds of the hymn ``Blessed Assurance.'' And near the end of 
services, parishioners gathered together in a large circle, held 
hands and sang ``Standing on the Promises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Oklahoma City suburb of Moore, Pastor Alan Cox of the  
First Baptist Church tried to comfort about 2,000 people gathered 
for a communitywide worship service. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all right to cry,'' he said. ``It's all right to hurt.  
It's all right to be confused. Hope will rebuild landmarks. Hope 
will outlive the broken hearts.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
