<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Records Vital for Disaster Tax Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tax relief, with some strings attached, is  
available to people who suffer financial losses in natural 
disasters like the Midwestern tornadoes. But tax advisers say it's 
crucial to keep adequate records -- and keep them in a safe place. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internal Revenue Service allows federal income tax  
deductions for people whose homes and businesses are damaged or 
destroyed by tornado, hurricane, earthquake or certain floods. 
</P>
<P>
	Insured damage estimates from last week's tornadoes in Oklahoma  
alone have reached $1 billion, but insurance won't cover every 
loss. 
</P>
<P>
	In such cases, proof is essential, and it's smart to plan ahead.  
For instance, the IRS could ask to see records such as receipts or 
canceled checks for household goods such as appliances, furniture 
and art. Even a videotape of a building's interior and contents can 
serve as evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people are not going to go through every room and  
inventory everything in the house,'' IRS spokesman Don Roberts said 
Monday. ``If you have the videotape, you have that as a reminder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, it doesn't do any good to keep these records if the  
home or business they're in is destroyed. One alternative is to 
store them in a safety deposit box or with a friend or relative 
someplace else. 
</P>
<P>
	The law permits tax deductions only for the ``fair market  
value'' of an item, not the full replacement cost or its 
sentimental value. This lands taxpayers without records in a murky 
area of estimating the worth of such things as used furniture or 
old wedding china. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to depend on the facts and circumstances a taxpayer  
presents and how well-documented the loss is,'' Roberts said of the 
IRS position in such cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other cautions: Deductions are permitted only when each  
separate loss is above $100, when the total combined loss for a 
single year exceeds 10 percent of a taxpayer's adjusted gross 
income and when any insurance claims were filed in a timely manner. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Luscombe, tax analyst at CCH Inc. of Riverwoods, Ill., said  
people who meet those thresholds should remember that deductions 
can be taken for property repairs as well as such items as 
destroyed trees and shrubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Examples of costs that aren't deductible are rental cars,  
temporary housing, cleanup costs or personal injuries, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	If the loss happened in a federal disaster area declared by the  
president, the rules are somewhat different. The loss can be 
deducted in the most recent tax year -- even if April 15 has passed 
-- by filing an amended 1040 return, as long as deductions are 
itemized. 
</P>
<P>
	There also are special rules for small businesses in disaster  
areas that allow deferral of a gain on the purchase of replacement 
equipment, which lowers the income tax bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``This provides relief for businesses that are forced to suspend  
operations for a substantial time due to property damage,'' 
Luscombe said. 
</P>
<P>
	IRS Publications 547 and 584 provide more information on  
disasters and taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
