<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 23:32:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert's Preakness Decision Easy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Bob Baffert intends to let the luck determine  
whether he runs fillies Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting in 
the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	If Monday's workout means anything, then Baffert's decision on  
Silverbulletday will be an easy one. 
</P>
<P>
	After the filly covered five furlongs in an impressive 59  
seconds at Churchill Downs, Baffert said, ``I figured after she 
worked they'd have to put water on the track to cool it down. 
That's what you want to see coming into a race like the 
Preakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both fillies are entered in Friday's Black-Eyed Susan, where  
Silverbulletday drew the rail and Excellent Meeting received the 
fourth position. If they get anywhere near that kind of placement 
in Wednesday's Preakness draw, Baffert will saddle both for 
Saturday's middle jewel of the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fate will decide whether we run or not,'' Baffert said.  
``These are two great fillies and I'm not going to waste a (start). 
I want to run to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday has won 10 of 11 career races, including the  
Kentucky Oaks. Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Kentucky Derby, was 
to work out this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In other news, the trainer of First American pulled his horse  
from the Preakness, citing a pair of injuries. The colt, who took 
16th in the Derby, has been bothered by fluid in his lungs and 
developed a bone chip in his ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed. When we decided to make this trip, we  
thought he would be in good shape,'' trainer Eduardo Caramori said. 
``The lung wasn't clear for the Derby and still isn't great, and 
the first sign that the ankle was bothering him came yesterday. 
With that combination, we have to pull out. You can't go into a big 
race at less than 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The departure of First American leaves the stakes barn at  
Pimlico near empty. Although most of the entrants plan to arrive 
Wednesday, trainer Nick Zito shipped his two horses, Stephen Got 
Even and Adonis, last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot easier for a trainer and his staff to stay in one  
place and ship in at the last minute,'' Zito conceded. ``I feel 
that if you come here and get used to the racetrack, it should mean 
something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His strategy worked to perfection in 1996, with upset winner  
Louis Quatorze. Zito is counting on similar results this year, even 
though both of his entrants finished far back in the Kentucky 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were right in '96 and hopefully we'll be right in '99,'' he  
said. ``If they do well Saturday, we'll be vindicated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zito was among the first arrivals at Pimlico three years ago,  
and his judgment appeared justified when Louis Quatorze charged 
past Skip Away and paid $19 to win. 
</P>
<P>
	If Stephen Got Even or Adonis win Saturday, it was also be  
considered a surprise. Stephen Got Even is coming off a 14th-place 
finish at the Derby, and Adonis took 17th place. 
</P>
<P>
	``They deserved the right to be in the Derby. But they had  
traffic problems and didn't have the best of trips,'' Zito said. 
``Hopefully, they'll have better luck here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
