<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:55:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Down Vs. Most Top Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the euro and most other  
major currencies Monday as news of a partial pullout of Yugoslavian 
troops from Kosovo stirred hopes that an end of the conflict may be 
approaching. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0782 in late trading in New York, up  
from $1.0748 late Friday. The dollar slipped to 120.50 Japanese yen 
from 120.85 yen late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro has been buffeted by changing expectations about the  
course of the NATO bombing of the southern Serb province. 
</P>
<P>
	The war has hurt the euro because of the risk of a broader war  
in Europe and the rising financial costs for European countries 
backing it. 
</P>
<P>
	But a settlement of the conflict would relieve some of those  
worries and take pressure off the euro, the currency since January 
of 11 European nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia's army announced Monday a partial withdrawal of  
military and police forces from Kosovo, saying it had completed its 
operations against ethnic Albanian rebels there. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO quickly said a partial withdrawal would not halt its  
bombing campaign, but President Clinton said he was ``encouraged by 
any good word.'' He repeated the alliance's demands for a complete 
Yugoslav withdrawal from Kosovo and deployment of an international 
security force there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clinton seems eager to wrap up this war,'' said Paul Podolsky,  
currency strategist for BankBoston. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said there is still confusion about Yugoslavian President  
Slobodan Milosevic's intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Bryson, an international economist for First Union National  
Bank in Charlotte, N.C., said the euro also got a lift from 
comments by German Finance Minister Hans Eichel who said Monday 
that the euro has potential to rise without any particular measures 
to support it. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to reporters after a meeting of the 11 euro-zone  
finance ministers in Brussels, Eichel said the ministers felt the 
euro's relative weakness against the U.S. dollar was due to 
different growth rates between the U.S. and the euro zone. ``The 
growth gap can be narrowed in time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Monday, the dollar was quoted at 1.4899 Swiss  
francs, down from 1.4965; and 1.4613 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4575. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound fell to $1.6253 from $1.6308.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8139 German  
marks, down from 1.8198; 6.0827 French francs, down from 6.1013; 
and 1,795.33 Italian lire, down from 1,801.80. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
