<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Opens Violence Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying he is not seeking a scapegoat for the  
Colorado high school shootings, President Clinton today convened a 
White House brainstorming session on how to reduce violence among 
youth. ``We are not here to place blame, but to shoulder 
responsibility,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the session began amid complaints from the gun and  
entertainment industries that they've already been targeted 
unfairly for blame. The National Rifle Association, uncompromising 
critic of gun control laws, was not invited. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, along with Vice  
President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, sat down in the White House 
East Room with about 60 participants ranging from America Online's 
chief executive to poet Maya Angelou. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he wants the session to provide the groundwork for  
a national campaign on reducing youth violence, much like similar 
campaigns to curb teen-age pregnancy and to find jobs for former 
welfare recipients. He also directed Surgeon General David Satcher 
to prepare a report on the causes of youth violence, the first in 
more than 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we have asked you to come here to see what we can  
do together to give our children safer childhoods,'' Clinton said. 
``Let's leave here today resolved to be, all of us, part of this 
national campaign. I want us to have a good conversation about 
where we go from here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the main question before the group is determining  
why violence is repeatedly erupting in the nation's schools, most 
recently and most deadly in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	But gun advocates and participants from the entertainment  
industry say they are feeling more pressure than most, because of 
the newly intensified debate over the availability of weapons and 
whether violence among teen-agers is fomented by the images and 
language in movies, video games and song lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of two gun-manufacturing groups -- the National Shooting  
Sports Foundation and the American Shooting Sports Council -- met 
with White House domestic policy adviser Bruce Reed last week and 
planned to attend today's gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said today that the councils had agreed to support five  
administration proposals to keep guns out of the hands of young 
people. One measure would raise the age at which a person can buy a 
handgun from 18 to 21. Another would hold parents criminally 
responsible for making guns accessible to children. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have found common ground on some commonsense measures,''  
Clinton said. ``I commend the gun manufacturers here today for 
taking that kind of responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA, meanwhile, called a news conference to assert that the  
Clinton administration has failed to aggressively prosecute 
juveniles caught with guns and adults accused of providing them. 
Executive vice president Wayne LaPierre decried the conference, 
saying the NRA was left out. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, we wanted to be there because this mirror needs to be  
held up to the administration,'' LaPierre said. ``You can talk 
about the culture of violence for the next 10 years. Unless you 
start prosecution, you're never going to cut to the culture of 
violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of  
America, said the film industry shouldn't be singled out for blame. 
He said he supports having the U.S. surgeon general do an in-depth 
analysis of ``the why of violence'' to better understand all of the 
factors at play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I also believe that church and home and school are the three  
places where children learn what is right and what is wrong, and 
that's where they build a strong moral shield,'' Valenti said. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Valenti, entertainment industry representatives expected  
at today's meeting were the heads of the Recording Industry 
Association of America, the National Association of Broadcasters, 
the National Cable Television Association and the Interactive 
Digital Software Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a survey released today by the Kaiser Family  
Foundation showed 80 percent of parents said they'd heard of the TV 
ratings now in use, but only 39 percent of them said they had seen 
an explanation of them. Seventy-seven percent said they would block 
shows they don't want their children to watch if their television 
sets were equipped with such technology, while 20 percent said they 
would not. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, similar to one conducted last year, was based on  
telephone interviews of 1,001 parents from April 6-26 -- before and 
after the high school shootings in Littleton Colo. It had a margin 
or error of plus or minus 3 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kaiser Family Foundation is a California research group  
interested in entertainment's impact on society. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
