<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wis. Debates Its Ice Cream Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin may be America's Dairyland, but  
for ice cream makers it's not always the sweetest place to be. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin is one of only two states -- Hawaii is the other -- with  
laws governing ice cream container size. Ice cream here only can be 
sold in half-pints, pints, quarts and multiples of quarters, 
including half-gallons and gallons. 
</P>
<P>
	A state representative said Monday he wants to do away with the  
34-year-old restrictions to give packagers -- and consumers -- more 
choices. 
</P>
<P>
	``They felt constricted by this law here, and heck, we're the  
dairy state,'' said Phil Montgomery, R-Ashwaubenon. 
</P>
<P>
	Good Humor-Breyers, the nation's largest ice cream producer,  
sells ``Pints Plus,'' a 1 1/2-pint container, in other states, but 
can't sell that size in Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the state Department of Agriculture, Trace and  
Consumer Protection aren't sure why the law was enacted in the 
first place, but speculated that it was done to make comparison 
shopping easier to consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	If the law is rescinded, the state's retailers are ready to make  
room in their freezers, said Brandon Scholz, president of the 
Wisconsin Grocers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers like variety,'' Scholz said. ``They like to be able  
to pick and choose.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 12:35:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Take Your Shoes Off'' (Rykodisc) -- The Robert Cray Band  
</P>
<P>
	Guitarist Robert Cray takes off his shoes, his socks and his  
blues man label for his debut on Rykodisc. The result is a 
soulfest. Cray assembled his band in a Nashville studio and 
produced a fine rhythm and blues record that showcases his sweet 
voice more than his playing. As if to give the record an extra 
measure of credence, Cray dips into the soul vaults to bring new 
life to Mack Rice's ``24-7 Man'' and ``Won't You Give Him (One More 
Chance),'' a 1964 hit for Soloman Burke. After 13 years with 
Mercury Records, Cray headed to the independent Rykodisc and used 
the occasion to give full voice to the soul roots that have always 
been a part of his music. His six originals are right at home with 
the soul covers. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Rising Son'' (Blind Pig) -- Big Bill Morganfield  

</P>
<P>
	Is blues a matter of heredity or environment? Are blues men born  
or made? 
</P>
<P>
	Such weighty questions are forced upon us by the debut recording  
of Big Bill Morganfield -- yes, THAT Morganfield, the mannish 
boy-child of the incomparable Muddy Waters, born McKinley 
Morganfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Does son sound like dad? Kind of. In style, some tracks have a  
Muddy resemblance. Big Bill's mumbling, good-time voice doesn't ask 
to be taken too seriously. In vocal tempo and guitar sound he does 
not compare to dad, but then no one ever has. 
</P>
<P>
	Big Bill is a self-assured performer, and his pedigree sprinkles  
magic on tracks like ``Screamin' and Crying'' and ``Champagne &AMP; 
Reefer,'' written by dad, now updated by son. 
</P>
<P>
	The best sample is Willie Dixon's ``The Same Thing,'' which Big  
Bill plays with the same melancholy, slapped-string tones his 
father used in his recording 45 years ago. It's also a good sample 
because with nods to his father's influence, Bill still presses his 
own sound and touch. 
</P>
<P>
	Setting back this CD some is the fact that blues is not at this  
stage anymore. Muddy Waters today would not play this way because 
his career was a constant progression. Therefore, the CD at moments 
can be stale. But Big Bill has given us more than a just novelty 
recording. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Ralph Siegel, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Borders'' (Red House Records) -- Cliff Eberhardt  

</P>
<P>
	Songwriter Cliff Eberhardt explores boundaries on his second  
record for Minnesota-based Red House Records. There's a rawness to 
his voice and a sparseness to his guitar playing that sharpens the 
emotion of his well-written lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lines,'' which pretty much defines the theme for the record,  
showcases some of his best writing. ``There's a line in the 
desert/There's a line in the sea/Between man and woman/Between you 
and me/Between hell and heaven/Between love and hurt/The line of 
temptation/The hem of your skirt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eberhardt also offers a haunting Civil War account of the  
ravages of battle on those with no reason to fight in ``The Wrong 
Side of the Line.'' ``I never knew Mason/I never knew Dixon/I never 
hurt no one/I never chose sides. I never dreamt that I'd be walking 
with strangers/Because I was born on the wrong side of the line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are some quirky elements that mar ``Borders,'' such as the  
lyric bridge in ``Lines.'' But it's a heartfelt record sung with 
passion. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``The Green Gate'' (J Seven Records) -- Phil DeGreg  

</P>
<P>
	Pianist and professor Phil DeGreg gets right to the point on  
this recording for Cincinnati-based J. Seven Records. DeGreg is an 
associate professor of jazz studies at the University of Cincinnati 
Conservatory of Music who also has played with the Woody Herman 
Orchestra, Slide Hampton, Stanley Turrentine and Eddie Harris. Here 
he leads a trio for most of the disc, playing straight-up jazz with 
confidence and authority. He has an easy grace and a strong sense 
of tradition. Four DeGreg compositions also showcase his writing. 
Tim Ries offers support on the tenor and soprano saxes as well as 
blowing some sweet solos to spice the mix. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Spirit -- A Journey in Dance, Drums &AMP; Song'' (Hollywood  
Records) -- Peter Buffett 

</P>
<P>
	Quite simply, this is a stunning recording. The compact disc is  
a recording of a live performance of composer/keyboardist Peter 
Buffett's celebration of Native American culture. The live show, 
first done in August, includes more than 80 performers, including 
20 dancers and a children's choir, who use rock music, movement, 
chants and songs to pay homage to Native American culture. 
</P>
<P>
	And while it is a celebration, the overall tone is of a  
civilization lost. Indeed, the third piece, ``Hidden Heritage,'' 
includes a recitation of tribes who have gone before. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Mirabal's flute work is particularly haunting throughout.  
A television presentation of the performance was broadcast by PBS 
nationwide in March and a live touring show is set to kick off in 
Chicago in October. Buffett is known for his score work for such 
films as ``Dances With Wolves'' and ``The Scarlet Letter,'' and 
television shows like CBS' ``500 Nations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 17:14:37 </DATE_TIME>
