<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbian Withdrawal News Brushed Aside  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said NATO  
would press on with its air campaign, despite Yugoslavia's 
announcement today of a partial military withdrawal from Kosovo. 
Cohen said he would consider a pause if Yugoslavia indicated its 
acceptance of all the alliance's demands and made a 
``demonstrable'' start to a troop withdrawal. Meanwhile, NATO 
carried out daylight bombings on several towns in central and 
western Serbia, killing four civilians and smashing a factory in 
one 20-minute bombardment, Yugoslav media reported. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Explains What Went Wrong  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an extraordinary admission of error, the  
CIA today said outdated maps, a lack of communication within the 
U.S. government and educated guesses that went terribly wrong led 
to the NATO air attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. 
Intelligence officials briefed lawmakers behind closed doors, then 
met with reporters to explain how a B-2 stealth bomber came to drop 
a load of satellite-guided bombs on a plainly marked embassy 
compound well-known in Belgrade to diplomats and civilians alike. 

</P>
<P>
	US-China Ties Continue To Break Down  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China broke off military ties and other contacts  
with the United States today and demanded those responsible for 
NATO's bombing of its embassy in Yugoslavia be ``severely'' 
punished. In addition, Chinese U.N. Ambassador Qin Huasun made 
clear this afternoon that Beijing won't discuss any peace plan for 
the Kosovo crisis unless the bombs stop falling in Yugoslavia. 
Meanwhile, thousands protested at the U.S. Embassy in Beijing for a 
third day. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia To Debate Yeltsin Impeachment  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin's foes in  
parliament today reiterated their intention to support an 
impeachment vote expected this week. The leaders of Russia's 
Communist Party, which has led the bid to impeach Yeltsin, met to 
discuss tactics for the impeachment debate scheduled to begin 
Thursday in the lower house of parliament, the State Duma. The 
current impeachment charges are the strongest yet. Still, the 
motion has little chance of success because even if the Duma 
approves it, Yeltsin cannot be ousted unless it also is passed by 
the upper house of parliament and the Supreme and Constitutional 
Courts. 

</P>
<P>
	Khmer Rouge Torturer To Be Witness  
</P>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- An admitted Khmer Rouge torturer who  
is expected to be a star witness in a trial of the group's 
leadership will be questioned soon by a Cambodian court, a 
government official said today. Meanwhile, a top U.N. human rights 
envoy arrived in Cambodia to continue negotiations with the 
government on what role the international community will play in a 
trial of Khmer Rouge leaders. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Discusses Youth Violence  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today convened a White House  
brainstorming session on how to reduce violence among youth. But 
the meeting began amid complaints from the gun and entertainment 
industries that they've already been targeted unfairly for blame. 
The National Rifle Association was not invited. Clinton said he 
wants the session to provide the groundwork for a national 
campaign. ``We are not here to place blame, but to shoulder 
responsibility,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Car Marine Gets 6 Months  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine pilot was sentenced today to  
six months in prison and he was dismissed from the Corps for 
helping hide a videotape shot during a flight in which 20 people 
died when his jet cut a ski gondola cable in Italy. Capt. Richard 
Ashby also was ordered to forfeit all pay and allowance for his 
conviction on charges of obstruction of justice and conspiracy to 
obstruct. 

</P>
<P>
	Kid's Author Shel Silverstein Dies  
</P>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Shel Silverstein, the author of such  
acclaimed children's books as ``A Light in the Attic'' and ``Where 
the Sidewalk Ends,'' was found dead at his home early today. He was 
66. Silverstein was born in Chicago and began his career as a 
writer and cartoonist for Playboy in 1952. He was discovered in his 
bedroom. The cause of death was not immediately known. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 24.34  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed today as the Dow Jones  
industrial average finished down 24.34 at 11,007.25. On the NYSE, 
gainers led losers 1,754-1,277. The Nasdaq Composite Index was up 
22.76 at 2,526.38. 

</P>
<P>
	Florida Charges Strawberry for Drugs  
</P>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry  
was charged by Florida today with possessing cocaine and soliciting 
a prostitute. He was arrested April 14. Police said he offered an 
undercover female officer $50 for sex. Strawberry is scheduled to 
be arraigned May 26. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
