<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> More Than 1,000 Attend Hess Funeral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Jets owner Leon Hess was remembered  
Monday for his wisdom and compassion in a funeral service attended 
by more than 1,000 mourners. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody truly incredible has left us,'' teary-eyed Dennis  
Byrd said after the service at the Park Avenue Synagogue. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess, 85, died Friday of complications from a blood disease.  
</P>
<P>
	Byrd recalled that when he was temporarily paralyzed from a  
football injury in 1992, Hess visited him at the hospital every 
night and was ``like a family member coming by to impart a little 
wisdom. ... He turned the worst time of my life into a blessing for 
me and my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd was joined at the service by Jets coach Bill Parcells and  
former Jets coach Rich Kotite. Also attending were Hall of Fame 
quarterback Joe Namath, former quarterback Boomer Esiason as well 
as other players and NFL owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Sens. Bill Bradley and Alfonse D'Amato, former New York  
Gov. Hugh Carey and hotel queen Leona Helmsley were also there. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess, who stepped down as chairman and chief executive officer  
of Amerada Hess Corp. in 1995, was remembered by his children and 
grandchildren as a hardworking family man who had a passion for 
both the oil business and his beloved Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could always tell how the Jets were doing by the condition  
of his cigar,'' said his son, John, who succeeded him as CEO of 
Amerada Hess. ``If it was short and chewed up, they were losing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hess also was a hard-nosed businessman. Whenever he faced a  
difficult negotiation, he liked to recall an encounter over oil 
prices with Moammar Gadhafi. The Libyan strongman watched as an 
associate in fatigues removed a pistol from a holster and placed it 
the table. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't scare me,'' Hess said.  
</P>
<P>
	Although the Jets won the Super Bowl in 1969, the team struggled  
for years after that. 
</P>
<P>
	If oil was Hess' business, football was his passion. He wanted  
to get the team back to the Super Bowl and hired a procession of 
coaches in the effort. He brought in Kotite in 1995, saying, ``I'm 
80 years old. I want results now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Kotite failed to supply them, Hess went after Parcells, who  
got the Jets back to the AFC championship game last January. After 
they lost to Denver, the owner met the team at the airport in the 
middle of the night to thank the players for their effort. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his son, Hess is survived by his wife, Norma; two  
daughters, Connie Williams, a state representative in Pennsylvania, 
and Marlene Hess; and seven grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Hess was the fourth major New York sports figure to die in the  
last six months. Weeb Ewbank, who coached the 1969 Jets, died in 
November, as did former Knicks coach Red Holzman. Baseball great 
Joe DiMaggio died in March. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
