<HEADLINE> Norsk Hydro Bids on Private Oil Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- State-controlled Norsk Hydro ASA offered  
$2.2 billion in stock on Monday for its smaller rival, Saga 
Petroleum ASA. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga is the country's third largest oil company, after  
state-owned Statoil ASA and Norsk Hydro, in which the government 
has a 51 percent stake. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro, with interests in petroleum, light metals and  
fertilizers, is offering to swap one of its shares for three Saga 
Petroleum shares. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer represented a 35 percent premium over Saga's closing  
price on Friday and its shares soared 31 percent Monday on the Oslo 
Stock Exchange, while Norsk Hydro shares rose 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga reported a pretax loss of $244 million for 1998, and was  
planning austerity measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro is the largest company listed on the Oslo exchange.  
Its offer was contingent on 90 percent of Saga's shareholders 
accepting the deal by the end of June, and on government approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga and Norsk Hydro already have many joint ownership interests  
in fields on the Norwegian continental shelf, and have parallel 
organizations in operations and support activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro employs about 40,000 people worldwide, while Saga  
has a staff of roughly 4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects to cut about 800 jobs if the takeover goes  
through. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga reported a pretax loss of $244 million for 1998, and was  
planning austerity measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
