<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mint Glut Gums Up Wash. '99 Harvest / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- The sweet smell of success seems elusive  
this season for farmers facing a national glut of mint oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers and buyers around the country are holding 3 million to 4  
million pounds of mint oil, nearly the amount Washington produces 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
	In Montana's Flathead Valley alone, growers have half a million  
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Some farmers are still trying to sell mint harvested in 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	``We can't stand a downturn that lasts much longer than this one  
has,'' says Wes Ferguson of Harrah, who has been growing mint for 
34 years. 
</P>
<P>
	A small portion of his crop has been contracted for sale at $9 a  
pound, but he hasn't found buyers for the rest. Two years ago, his 
native spearmint sold for $11 a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Even at $8 a pound, there are few takers. ``You'd have trouble  
selling it. Nobody wants it,'' says Rocky Lunde, director of the 
Mint Industry Research Council in Stevenson. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington is the country's top producer of spearmint oil. It's  
also a major source of peppermint oil, second only to Oregon. The 
oil is used to flavor toothpaste, gum and mouthwash. 
</P>
<P>
	When demand for mint was strong a few years ago, U.S. growers  
began to add acreage. At the same time, countries such as India, 
China and Argentina emerged as major competitors, often selling 
mint oil for half the price. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, the Asian financial crisis caused overseas demand to slow  
and inventories began to build. 
</P>
<P>
	I.P. Callison &AMP; Sons, a Chehalis mint buyer, has been turning  
sales away for two years. Its Sunnyside warehouse is full. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry has ``a huge oversupply, three times bigger than  
anything we've seen before,'' says Les Toews, Callison's vice 
president for purchasing and field operations. ``We're in uncharted 
territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A little mint oil goes a long way and has a long shelf life. One  
55-gallon barrel makes 5.2 million sticks of chewing gum. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Officials at the state Department of  
Agriculture are looking for ways to bring back Connecticut's oyster 
industry after a parasite swept through shoreline shellfish beds, 
wiping out up to 90 percent of some recent crops. 
</P>
<P>
	State biologists have spent the last year canvassing shellfish  
beds to assess the damage and provide insight for the future. Among 
the tactics under consideration is development of a hatchery in 
Groton to spawn resistant seed oysters. 
</P>
<P>
	The nursery approach would mark a departure from centuries of  
Connecticut oystering. Other large, oyster-producing states such as 
Washington employ hatcheries on a broad scale, but Connecticut has 
historically relied solely the open waters of Long Island Sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatcheries can accelerate the oyster's three-year growing cycle.  
</P>
<P>
	The state also has been spawning seed oysters that survived in  
Clinton harbor last year and offering them to oystermen to 
replenish their stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The resistant oysters will spawn resistant seed,'' said Inke  
Sunila, a shellfish pathologist with the aquaculture bureau. 
</P>
<P>
	The parasites, known as dermo and MSX, last created major  
problems in the sound in the mid-1980s, and the industry, with help 
from the state, spent several years rebounding. 
</P>
<P>
	When MSX and dermo reappeared in late 1996, oystermen felt it  
immediately. Overall, the state's oyster harvest dropped from 
525,809 bushels in 1996 to 179,562 bushels in 1998, according to 
the latest figures. The yields are the lowest since 1988, when the 
earlier parasite infection subsided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
