<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC, Xoom.com, Snap.com Join Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC and two online partners are launching a new,  
publicly traded company that will combine most of the network's 
Internet operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, NBC Internet or NBCi, will include the Snap Web  
directory and Xoom.com, a direct marketing service. The deal does 
not include MSNBC news, the network's 50-50 partnership with 
Microsoft Corp., but MSNBC will have prominent placement on the new 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	The three partners are hoping to create a strong,  
general-interest site by combining the entertainment appeal and 
marketing capability of NBC, Web searching from Snap and expertise 
in online commerce from Xoom.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is our broad-based Internet play,'' Tom Rogers, executive  
vice president of NBC, said in an interview. ``This is the one 
we're putting our shoulder and muscle behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The main Web site will continue to operate under the name Snap!,  
but content from NBC and the network's trademark peacock logo will 
be prominently featured. The site will also combine material from 
the network's current Web site, NBC.com, and its Videoseeker.com 
video guide service. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Kitze, the chairman and co-founder of Xoom.com, said the  
companies hope to use the powerful capability of TV networks to 
reach viewers as a way to bolster the online business. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that in the long run what will win in this business  
is an integrated media play, where the network takes viewers, 
drives those people to the Internet, where they'll use sites like 
Snap and commerce facilities like Xoom,'' Kitze said in an 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	NBCi will buy $380 million in TV advertising from the network  
over the next four years, and expects to buy an additional $500 
million over the following six. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC will start off owning 49 percent of the new company, with  
the option to increase its stake to 53 percent later. Xoom.com 
shareholders would own 34 percent and CNET 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's president and CEO Bob Wright will become chairman of the  
new company, and Kitze will become president. 
</P>
<P>
	By rolling most of its Internet assets into one package, NBC is  
hoping to take advantage of the seemingly endless enthusiasm among 
investors for companies whose business lies purely in the Internet. 
Officials said the transaction should be completed by the end of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the deal sent the stocks of NBC's two online partners  
soaring Monday. Shares in Snap's parent company CNET rose $21.75 or 
19 percent to $135.50, while Xoom.com gained $6.75, or 9 percent, 
to $81.87 1/2. Both companies trade on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock of NBC's parent company, General Electric Co., slipped  
$1.18 3/4 or 1 percent to $108.75 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Other major TV networks have also made ventures into the online  
world, but this deal marks the first time that a network's main 
online operation will be a publicly traded company. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has taken stakes in several Internet startup companies,  
including Marketwatch.com, in exchange for promotion on its TV and 
radio networks. ABC's parent Walt Disney Co. has interests in the 
Go Network and the Infoseek Web portal. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
