<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Satellite Still Short of Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- A communication satellite that was  
launched into a useless orbit last week was flying higher Monday, 
but was still far short of its intended orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	The chances of getting the Orion satellite to the desired  
22,300-mile altitude remained slim. 
</P>
<P>
	Another satellite, meanwhile, will remain grounded for at least  
a month because of rain that leaked onto it even though it was in a 
protective room at the launch pad. It was the latest in a series of 
mishaps at Cape Canaveral Air Station and has prompted the Air 
Force to convene a review board. 
</P>
<P>
	The military's Global Positioning System satellite had been  
scheduled for launch aboard a Boeing Delta II rocket as early as 
this weekend. It will be removed from the rocket and inspected for 
damage from Saturday's thunderstorm. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Orion, ground controllers for satellite maker Hughes  
Space and Communications Co. used on-board thrusters Friday night 
to raise the low end of the lopsided orbit from 98 miles to 262 
miles. 
</P>
<P>
	``They accomplished what they wanted to accomplish, which was to  
get it out of the Earth's atmosphere,'' Hughes spokesman Emery 
Wilson said Monday. ``At this time, we're kind of waiting for our 
customer to decide what they would like us to do with the 
satellite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Loral Space and Communications, John McCarthy,  
said the company is looking at all the options. 
</P>
<P>
	The $230 million botched launch on May 4 was the second failure  
in a row for Boeing's new Delta III rocket, a bigger, upgraded 
version of the Delta II. The inaugural flight in August ended in an 
explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the rocket's second stage fired for only one second  
before abruptly shutting down 22 minutes after liftoff. It should 
have fired for nearly three minutes. At the same time, the engine 
experienced a pressure spike and shudder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
