<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Soccer Wins Harassment Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Forward Debbie Keller, who claimed she was  
excluded from the U.S. women's soccer team in retaliation for a 
sexual harassment lawsuit, lost her case against the U.S. Soccer 
Federation on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Arbitrators Mark Crane, Dan Burns, Herbert Channick conveyed the  
decision orally, USSF general counsel John Collins said. A written 
decision may follow. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 10 witnesses testified during a hearing in Chicago  
last week, Collins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a written decision, the exact findings of the  
arbitration panel were unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no finding of retaliation by the federation, or she  
had not proved her allegation, which each means the same,'' Collins 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keller's Washington-based lawyer, Dane Butswinkas, did not  
return a telephone call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this matter behind us, our players, coaches and  
administrative staff can continue to focus on the most important 
task at hand, which is winning the 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup,'' 
USSF secretary general Hank Steinbrecher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keller, a two-time national player of the year, filed the $12  
million suit last Aug. 25 along with former North Carolina teammate 
Melissa Jennings, claiming coach Anson Dorrance made uninvited 
sexual advances and harassed her during and after her college 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	A forward who played for the Tar Heels from 1993-96, Keller also  
named the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, school and 
athletic administrators and women's assistant coaches as defendants 
in the suit, which is awaiting trial. Dorrance, the only women's 
soccer coach North Carolina has ever had, is the former coach of 
the U.S. women's team. 
</P>
<P>
	Keller argued she was bypassed for the 26-player residency camp  
for the U.S. women's team in retaliation for the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 30, U.S. District Judge Ann Claire Williams transferred  
the suit from Illinois to Greensboro, N.C., but denied a dismissal 
motion by university lawyers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
