<HEADLINE> Internet Co. Loses Playboy Logo Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A Miami Beach company must stop using the Playboy  
name and the well-known rabbit head logo on its Internet sites, a 
federal judge ruled Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago-based Playboy Enterprises International Inc. had filed a  
federal complaint against Miami Beach-based Global Site Designs 
Inc., saying Global used the famous name and trademark for its own 
financial gain. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Edward B. Davis issued a temporary  
restraining order against Global and two employees last week. When 
no Global representatives showed up Monday for a hearing on the 
matter, Davis entered an injunction. 
</P>
<P>
	Playboy attorneys said Global's two sites were rip-offs of  
Playboy's own Web site, which prominently displays the trademark 
Playboy Online, and of Playboy's recent search for a Playmate for 
the Year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Global's Web sites announced a ``talent search,'' offering cash  
and prizes to women who sent in videos, photos and personal 
information. Global offered $100,000 and a Stingray Corvette to 
winners. The Web site charged a $20 processing fee to review model 
applications. 
</P>
<P>
	Global's Web sites, www.playboyonline.net and  
www.playmatesearch.net, have apparently been taken offline. 
Attempts to link with them Monday were unsuccessful,and a telephone 
call to Global was not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Playboy is still fighting other companies that use Playboy's  
name to sponsor unauthorized model searches, Francescani said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
