<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $581M Awarded in Alleged Overcharge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A jury awards a jaw-dropping $581  
million to a family that claimed a finance company tried to cheat 
them out of $1,200 for two satellite dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Is the verdict proof of a ``jackpot justice'' system in  
desperate need of repair? Or is it an instance of the only real way 
Alabama consumers can be protected from cheats? 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict -- possibly the largest in state history and almost  
certain to be reduced -- provided fresh ammunition to critics asking 
lawmakers this session to revamp the state legal system. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly highlights the need for reform,'' Kathy Bowden of  
the Alabama Civil Justice Reform Committee said Monday. ``It's a 
BIG highlight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But trial lawyers say deterrence is the only protection for  
customers given Alabama's weak consumer protection laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the system is working now better than it ever has,''  
said plaintiff's attorney Tom Methvin of Montgomery. ``Jury awards 
like this serve a necessary interest in our society. They draw 
attention to a problem that needs attention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As early as today, the Alabama Senate could consider bills that  
would limit punitive damages awards and make it more difficult to 
file ``frivolous'' lawsuits. A committee has approved the bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Don Siegelman said Monday he would sign the bills.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is time to pass reasonable tort reform in Alabama, while at  
the same time protect consumers from unscrupulous conduct,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was an Alabama jury a few years ago that awarded $4 million  
to a doctor who didn't like that the paint had been touched up on 
his new BMW. The Supreme Court struck down the award, and the 
doctor eventually got $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	In the current case, Barbara Carlisle and her parents, George  
and Velma Merriweather of Greensboro, sued Whirlpool Financial 
National Bank and Gulf Coast Electronics, contending the companies 
tried to gouge them for $612 each on the purchase of two $1,100 
satellite dishes sold door-to-door in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	A sales person told the three they would have to pay $34 a month  
for three years, but the contract ran for 4 1/2 years, said Methvin, 
who represented the family. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors heard testimony that the company cheated thousands of  
people out of $8 million by getting them to sign credit card deals 
that required them to pay as much as 300 percent in interest, even 
though the advertised rate was only 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Whirlpool Financial said any wrongdoing was committed by Gulf  
Coast Electronics, a Mobile retailer that financed dish sales 
through Whirlpool Financial. The verdict went against both 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Once it learned of the allegations in the suit, Whirlpool  
Financial waived payment of the amount that was disputed by Ms. 
Carlisle and her parents, said Robert Spotswood, a lawyer for 
Whirlpool Corp., which sold Whirlpool Financial to TransAmerica 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The family lost nothing, Spotswood said, yet jurors in Hale  
County on Friday awarded them $975,000 to for mental anguish and 
$580 million to punish the companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The president of Gulf Coast Electronics, Don Gantt Jr., said his  
company sold the family a good system at a fair price through a 
newspaper advertisement, and then installed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Ms. Carlisle nor the Merriweathers could be located by  
telephone for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Spotswood said the case will be appealed. And Methvin said he  
expects the verdict to be reduced to less than $1 million because 
of the Supreme Court's 1996 ruling in the BMW case. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
