<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Questions Before Buying Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Computers run on software, which is to say they run on money --  
yours. And a few moments of thought in the software store or on the 
net can save you some money. 
</P>
<P>
	Before you open your wallet, ask yourself some questions:  
</P>
<P>
	--1) Do I already own software that can handle this task? An  
example is a $19.99 effort called ``Secret Diary &AMP; More'' from 
Encore Software, Inc., of Los Angeles, Calif. Although it's nice 
enough, the central point of the software is a password-protected 
secret diary for girls age 7 and older, plus a stationery-maker, 
personal calendar and address book. 
</P>
<P>
	If you already own either Corel's WordPerfect, or Microsoft's  
Word, just show your daughter how to password protect her files and 
call it a day. (If she doesn't already know, that is. Mine had it 
figured early, I discovered while accidentally trying to open a 
file named ``josh.'') And the word processors will also handle 
fonts and borders for stationery, addresses and dates. 
</P>
<P>
	--2) Is it really easier to do this task without a computer?  
Intuit's Quicken has been keeping track of my checkbook for years 
and years. Now, with the advent of palm computers, real techies 
with $39.95 to burn can run Pocket Quicken on their Palm machines, 
enter transactions in the real world, and then synchronize them 
with the full version of Quicken on the desktop. 
</P>
<P>
	But those with less money and inclination to digitize everything  
can be just as synchronized by keeping track of checks on a note 
card shoved in a pocket along with credit-card slips and entering 
the data at home. 
</P>
<P>
	--3) Why am I upgrading? Software publishers upgrade constantly  
in an effort to generate revenue from both existing and new 
customers. Think twice before upgrading if you're happy with the 
existing product. Besides enriching the publisher, your rewards are 
likely to be small and may even be irritating if the upgrade 
changed commands and functions significantly. 
</P>
<P>
	--4) Will my machine run this program? Software publishers  
sometimes seem to be in a contest for hiding system requirements in 
tiny type on the bottom of the package. Find them before you buy. 
Also be wary of the mealy-mouthed ``minimum'' and ``recommended'' 
hardware configurations. Sure, the software will run on the 
``minimum'' configuration, but in about the same way as an 
80-year-old running uphill. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Regular readers saw an earlier rant about a DirecTV home  
satellite system that stopped working and the advice from Hughes 
Network Systems to do some tests with a voltage meter -- certainly a 
common bit of household equipment, right? Here's how things worked 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	The meter was less than $20 at Radio Shack. And so, meter in  
hand, I determined that the receiver was indeed producing voltage -- 
but still no picture. Reported that to Hughes, was assigned Trouble 
Number 3154173 and given the number of a nearby service company. 
The service company asked for voltage checks at the ground block, 
the part of the cable outside the house that is grounded to prevent 
lightning strikes from blasting the equipment inside. Good voltage 
in and out. Reluctantly, the company agreed to an on-site visit. 
</P>
<P>
	A technician showed up, spent two hours, confirmed that it  
didn't work, and promised to call back. Never did. Never sent a 
bill, either, which is good -- it wouldn't have been paid. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally opened a phone book and selected a different satellite  
service company that showed up on time, correctly diagnosed a dead 
LNB and corrected the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Time involved: three weeks. Expense involved, including the  
meter, $285. Lesson learned: it would have been cheaper, and 
quicker, to buy a complete new system, now being offered in the New 
York metro area for $199, including installation. Ah, technology! 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
