<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Market Reacts to Chevron-Texaco Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors on Monday began discounting the  
possibility that Chevron Corp. might buy Texaco Inc. . 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Chevron, which fell $2.93 3/4 Friday when reports of  
negotiations over a deal hit the market, bounced back $1.37 1/2 Monday 
to $96.25 on the New York Stock Exchange. Texaco, which rose $5.06 1/4 
Friday, fell $1.37 1/2 Monday to $65.87 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of an acquiring company often fall as investors bet that  
the cost of the purchase will dilute profits. Those shares 
sometimes recover if market sentiment increases that the deal won't 
take place. 
</P>
<P>
	Takeover targets often rise as investors believe shares will be  
worth more in an acquisition than on the open market. Likewise, if 
the market believes the deal isn't imminent, those shares often 
drop. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that the two are  
discussing a $42 billion stock deal that would unite the nation's 
third and fourth biggest energy companies 
</P>
<P>
	But the newspaper, citing unidentified people familar with the  
talks, said the companies aren't near an agreement and said a 
combination faces enormous hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of Chevron, based in San Francisco, and Texaco, based  
in White Plains, N.Y., declined to comment on a deal Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Large oil companies have been rushing to unite because of  
falling oil prices and the need to cut costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., the nation's two  
biggest energy companies, plan to vote later this month on a 
merger. British Petroleum acquired Amoco Corp., then the fifth 
largest U.S. energy concern, last year and the combined company, BP 
Amoco, has agreed to buy Atlantic Richfield Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron chairman Kenneth Derr and Texaco chief executive Peter  
Bijur both have said recently they don't need partners to be 
successful but would consider merging with other companies to 
increase cash flow or efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts say a Chevron-Texaco merger would make less  
sense than other recent oil company mergers because both companies 
have been cutting costs on their own and Texaco last year formed a 
refining partnership with Shell Oil, which would present a 
regulatory stumbling block. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
