<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 24.34 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed Monday in a choppy  
session that saw profit-taking in blue chips amid worries about 
higher interest rates. But traders showed a renewed interest in 
technology stocks, particularly Internet issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 24.34 to 11,007.25 after  
fluctuating between positive and negative territory throughout the 
session. On Friday, the Dow rose 84.77 to close at 11,031.59, its 
second record high close for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators ended mixed Monday. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index declined 4.70 to 1,340.30, but the Nasdaq 
composite rose 22.77 to 2,526.39, largely on the strength of 
Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors sold big-company stocks and growth stocks, which  
depend on lower interest rates, although yields actually declined 
in the bond market. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year Treasury yield fell to 5.78 percent from 5.81  
percent late Friday, but it is still up more than 0.60 percentage 
point since April 20, and investors are concerned that it will 
continue to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury is auctioning $15 billion of 5-year bonds Tuesday  
and another $12 billion in 10-year notes Wednesday. The new supply 
could push yields higher, said Hugh Johnson, market strategist at 
First Albany Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising rates typically prompt some selling in financial services  
stocks and also in stocks trading at high prices relative to their 
earnings projections, Johnson said. Higher rates tend to eat into 
corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Big consumer products stocks closed lower, with Johnson &AMP;  
Johnson dropping 2 3/4 to 93 3/8 and Procter &AMP; Gamble down 11/16 at 90 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	But investors bought the stocks of basic-materials companies,  
believing that those industries will benefit from higher prices. 
Kaiser Aluminum rose 1/2 point to 8 1/2 after Credit Suisse First Boston 
upgraded its stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks were higher on reports USA Networks will abandon  
its bid to acquire Lycos after concluding it can't win approval 
from Lycos shareholders. Lycos stock rose 15 3/4 to 105 1/4, while USA 
Networks eased 1/8 to 35 1/4. Shares of CMGI Inc., a holding company 
that has about a 20 percent stake in Lycos, advanced 16 11/16 to 
237 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, merger news moved other stocks. HSBC Holdings PLC is  
buying Republic National Bank of New York and an affiliated banking 
company for about $10.3 billion in cash. Under the agreement, HSBC 
will pay $72 a share for Republic New York and Safra Republic 
Holdings SA. Republic's stock fell 1 15/16 to 68 1/16 on the news, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	And Chevron Corp. is discussing a purchase of Texaco Inc. for  
about $42 billion in stock, The Wall Street Journal reported. 
Neither company would confirm the talks, and The Journal quoted 
sources close to the deal as saying it faces enormous hurdles. 
Chevron, a Dow stock, rose 1 3/8 to 96 1/4. Texaco fell 1 3/8 to 65 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-8 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where consoliated volume totaled 
940.51 million shares, down from Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 1.90 to 639.34, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.21 to 787.08. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.74 to 441.85.  
</P>
<P>
	In overseas trading, the Nikkei index in Tokyo rose 0.18  
percent. In Europe, the DAX index in Frankfurt fell 1.73 percent, 
the FT-SE 100 index in London eased 0.11 percent, while the CAC in 
Paris added 1.34 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
