<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 'Gonzo' Pushes Streak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The numbers keep adding up for Luis Gonzalez,  
triplets at home and a 23-game hitting streak at work. 
</P>
<P>
	The man his teammates call ``Gonzo'' has been going crazy at the  
plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez kept the streak going Monday night with a soft single  
up the middle in the first inning against the Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he hit a three-run home run on the first pitch he saw  
in the first inning against the New York Mets, then added a double 
and a sacrifice fly. 
</P>
<P>
	He has eight home runs, 24 RBIs and a team-high 16 walks. His  
batting average going into Monday night's game was .388, second 
only to Larry Walker's .395 in majors. He has struck out just five 
times in 98 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can hit,'' said teammate Matt Williams, off to a .354 start  
himself. ``He's got a real good idea about the strike zone. He does 
his homework on pitchers and he's got some real good ability. You 
put those three together, you're a good hitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona got Gonzalez from Detroit for Karim Garcia in what could  
be the most one-sided trade of the offseason. Gonzalez, playing for 
his fourth team in his ninth major league season, said he's loved 
it with the Diamondbacks ``from the get-go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always been a slow starter out of the gate in April,'' he  
said, ``but I just feel good. It's been a fun year for me as far as 
having the triplets, working hard in the offseason, getting traded 
to this team. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of excitement was generated with this team with all the  
moves they made, and I was just excited to come here and be a part 
of it and it seems like everything just kind of snowballed. I'm 
just happy here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oh, yes, those triplets. Last June, Gonzalez's wife, Christine,  
gave birth to Megan, Jacob and Alyssa. They've already made a few 
appearances in their father's arms in the clubhouse, where team 
policy permits players' children the run of the place. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez has become one of the clubhouse's most popular players.  
Because he is bilingual -- his parents were born in Cuba -- he's 
equally comfortable chatting with the Hispanic and the 
non-Hispanics on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a people person,'' he said, ``and this organization has  
been tremendous to me from day one. I think it's just the fact 
there are so many veteran guys who have been on different teams and 
have been through ups and downs in baseball. It's just a relaxed 
feeling here. If you look around, you've got all good guys. You've 
got no bad apples. The coaching staff and management have made me 
feel real comfortable from the first day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez has settled in as the No. 3 hitter in the order, just  
behind Jay Bell and just ahead of Williams, both off to big starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I seem to fit real well between those two guys, and the way  
they've been swinging, it makes my job a lot easier,'' Gonzalez 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Buck Showalter said Gonzalez deserves most of the  
credit, though. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody in this clubhouse would tell you he's the  
one who's doing it,'' Showalter said. ``He's not missing good 
pitches when he gets them and he's hitting some tough pitches, too, 
for base hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez is a career .268 hitter, but he's had streaks before.  
Most notably, he had a 23-game streak for Houston in 1997, a mark 
that tied the Astros' team record and was the longest streak in the 
NL that year. That makes him only the eighth active player with two 
hitting streaks of 20 games or more. 
</P>
<P>
	He nearly saw his streak end Saturday, but singled in the ninth  
inning after Williams, according to Showalter, reminded him, ``Hey, 
Luis, you haven't got a hit yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a little bit more at ease with it now,'' Gonzalez said.  
``In Houston while it was going on, I was a little uneasy about it. 
But as years go by, you learn to deal with things like that. I'm 
kind of having fun with it now because my teammates and everybody 
are pulling for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saturday, I was down to my last at-bat and the fans were  
cheering. You know, it's fun. I know it's going to end sooner or 
later, but it's fun while it lasts.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
