<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Charged in Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry  
finally was charged Monday by Florida with possessing cocaine and 
soliciting a prostitute. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder is scheduled to be arraigned May  
26, Assistant State Attorney Pam Bondi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, who has a home in Tampa, was arrested April 14 a few  
miles from the Yankees' extended spring training camp. Police said 
he offered an undercover female officer $50 for sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Police also said Strawberry had 0.3 grams of cocaine wrapped in  
a $20 bill in his wallet. He was released on $6,000 bond. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry said the cocaine did not belong to him. And while he  
acknowledged discussing sex with the undercover officer, he 
insisted he was joking and did not intend to meet her at a motel. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, 37, has a long history of drug and alcohol problems  
and run-ins with the law, including a conviction on federal tax 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	He was suspended for 60 days in 1995 after testing positive for  
cocaine and another positive test would be cause for another 
suspension, several baseball officials have said since the arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Bud Selig put Strawberry on indefinite  
``administrative leave,'' in April, which isn't defined by 
baseball's rules but carries the same penalties as a suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, who signed a minor league contract while he  
recuperated from colon cancer surgery last October, can't 
participate in workouts or games with the Yankees or their farm 
teams until baseball's inquiry is completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
