<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Destroys Columbine Memorial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- A small fire destroyed a memorial site  
for victims of the Columbine High School shootings set up in nearby 
Clement Park. 
</P>
<P>
	A candle left burning near the shrine sparked the blaze Sunday,  
fire department spokeswoman Susan Brightmire said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was extinguished almost immediately, but not before posters  
and stuffed animals set out to remember those killed and injured 
were destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was more a sentimental loss,'' Brightmire said, adding that  
the blaze was contained to a 400-square-foot area. No one was 
injured and dozens of other memorial sites at the park were left 
intact. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve students and a teacher were killed in the April 20  
rampage by Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17. It ended when 
they committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	For almost three weeks, mourners have brought flowers, teddy  
bears, hand-scribbled notes and blue ribbons to makeshift memorial 
sites at the park, which is adjacent to the Columbine school. 
</P>
<P>
	Brightmire said there was a similar fire at the park a week ago,  
also apparently started by a candle. 
</P>
<P>
	Park personnel say most of the memorials in the park will be  
taken down. A permanent memorial is in the planning stages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
