<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Sets Up Internet Fraud Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- It's hard to fight Internet crime  
when you don't even have a solid idea about how much commerce there 
is -- or how much fraud actually occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement officials will be getting some needed  
assistance. The FBI and several anti-fraud groups announced Monday 
they are establishing an Internet Fraud Complaint Center and 
forming the Internet Fraud Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The center and the council will be modeled after the  
Atlanta-based Centers for Disease Control, which collects health 
data and tracks health trends. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to give law enforcement significant support in  
investigating these cases,'' said Richard Johnston, director of the 
National White Collar Crime Center, which is joining the FBI in 
developing the center in a private-public partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet crime-fighting effort was announced at the Economic  
Crime Summit conference at Walt Disney World. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet crimes range from credit card fraud to pyramid scams to  
securities fraud. Authorities said they have no idea how much 
Internet commerce takes place -- estimates range from $9 billion to 
$108 billion -- and even less of a clue how much Internet fraud 
occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the mission of the Internet Fraud Council will be to  
give law enforcement a picture of how big Internet crime really is. 
The council, supported by the National Fraud Center, the National 
Coalition for the Prevention of Economic Crime and the National 
White Collar Crime Center, will also provide training against 
Internet fraud and create forecasts of fraudulent activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Fraud Center is a Horsham, Pa.-based fraud and risk  
management consulting firm. The National White Collar Crime Center 
is a federally funded research and consulting firm based in 
Richmond, Va. The privately financed National Coalition for the 
Prevention of Economic Crime is a research organization that aims 
to educate the private sector about economic fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint center will take information on its Web site from  
Internet crime victims. The center plans to link its Web site with 
law enforcement sites around the nation so victims can make 
reports. Those reports will allow the FBI to analyze trends and 
notify local law enforcement if action is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	An address for the Web site has yet to be determined. The center  
is scheduled to open in late summer in a yet-to-be-selected 
location in West Virginia and will eventually employ 135 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The popularity of the Internet has changed the face of crime,  
authorities said at the conference. Internet criminals are 
increasingly well-educated and female. 
</P>
<P>
	And they are no longer constrained by borders and boundaries.  
They are as likely to commit crimes over the Internet from Bozeman, 
Mont., as from Manama, Bahrain. 
</P>
<P>
	Because cyber-criminals can move about easily, it is even more  
crucial that law enforcement share information with each other, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyber-criminals don't have the financial limits of law  
enforcement and many upgrade their computer equipment and software 
every six months, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Criminals aren't saddled with taking the lowest bid when  
buying equipment,'' said Florida Department of Law Enforcement 
Commissioner Tim Moore. ``They don't have a lot of albatrosses 
around their neck.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vigra Rival Has Disappointing Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Schering-Plough proved with its top-selling  
antihistamine Claritin that it could overcome competitors that get 
a head start on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The pharmaceutical giant is hoping for the same success in the  
impotence pill market. 
</P>
<P>
	But so far it can't get out of the starting block.  
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough Corp. and partner Zonagen Inc. said Monday they  
will postpone completing the Food and Drug Administration review 
process for their experimental impotence pill Vasomax so they can 
have more time to show it works. As a result Vasomax won't be 
available for at least a year, Zonagen officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The news sent stock in Zonagen, a tiny biotech company based  
outside Houston, plummeting nearly 50 percent Monday. Shares of 
Schering-Plough, a much bigger company whose stock isn't dependent 
on the drug, were flat. 
</P>
<P>
	Viagra, introduced by Pfizer Inc. in April 1998, had $788  
million in U.S. sales last year. The first pill to treat impotence 
became an instant success, and is the fastest selling new drug in 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	But, Viagra, at about $8 a pill, is expensive and competition  
could help drive down the cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Zonagen, which is developing Vasomax, joined with  
Schering-Plough in November 1997. Zonagen, which has no drugs on 
the market, applied for FDA approval in July 1998, and approval was 
expected this summer. The drug is approved for use in Mexico under 
the brand name Z-Max. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we are disappointed with this delay, we believe that  
the additional data from Schering-Plough's studies are important to 
the long-term success of Vasomax,'' said Joseph S. Podolski, 
Zonagen's president and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Zonagen nor Schering-Plough would release the results of  
the tests that prompted the delay in the drug application. 
</P>
<P>
	Neil Sweig, an analyst with Southeast Research Partners, said  
Zonagen's early studies show that Vasomax is not nearly as 
effective in producing an erection as Viagra. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the studies show Vasomax only effective about 40 percent  
of the time compared to about 70 percent for Viagra. ``This 
announcement is without doubt a most unwelcome surprise,'' Sweig 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Podolski acknowledges some data shows Vasomax lacking against  
Viagra. But he contends there are many ways to measure success. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he hopes that after the additional studies are completed  
the company will show that the drugs work similarly. 
</P>
<P>
	Podolski predicted that Vasomax will be proven safer than Viagra  
in men with heart trouble. Viagra is dangerous when taken by those 
who also take certain heart drugs such as nitroglycerin. Also, 
Vasomax works in about 15 to 30 minutes, about twice as quick as 
Viagra, Podolski said. 
</P>
<P>
	The delay in Vasomax will likely put its sponsors behind TAP  
Pharmaceuticals in the race to launch the first Viagra competitor 
</P>
<P>
	TAP, a joint venture between Abbott Laboratories and Japanese  
drugmaker Takeda Chemical Industries, Ltd. expects to seek federal 
approval for its anti-impotence pill Uprima in the next few months. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, TAP presented data at a medical conference showing  
the largest dose of Uprima is 61 percent effective compared to 29 
percent for a dummy pill. 
</P>
<P>
	But Vasomax should not be considered out of the running.  
</P>
<P>
	Schering-Plough has produced come-from-behind winners before.  
Claritin, introduced in the early 1990s, was not the first 
antihistamine on the market. But its fewer side effects and heavy 
promotional campaign helped the drug to quickly become the 
top-selling antihistamine. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
