<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybean Futures End Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures finished higher Monday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade, while wheat ended mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans gained as investors covered positions ahead of  
the late-afternoon release of farmer planting progress reports, 
which were expected to show continued behind-average fieldwork as a 
result of recent rains. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices for corn in particular also gained amid forecasts  
for rain in parts of the Midwest later this week, which could 
further delay plantings as the window of opportunity rapidly 
closes. That could mean fewer acres planted to corn this year, a 
prospect that would help reduce supplies just as world demand is 
expected to show some improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat ended mixed, pressured amid concerns the NATO bombing of  
the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia would dim any hopes for new 
Chinese purchases. Prices were bolstered, however, after the U.S. 
Agriculture Department reported that wheat inspected for export 
totaled 26.23 million bushels, a figure higher than expectations 
and twice that of a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 1/2 cent to $2.64 a bushel; July corn  
rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.21 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 6 1/2 cents to $1.28 3/4 
a bushel; July soybeans rose 1 1/2 cents to $4.79 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and lean hog futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork bellies advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .45 cent to 60.95 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .20 cent to 72.17 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .23 cent to 60.70 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 1.30 
cents to 61.17 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
