<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Informant on Trial in Chicago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- It has all the makings of a courtroom blockbuster  
-- an FBI informant who says he paid a $10,000 bribe to a powerful 
union leader, and a set of secretly made audio tapes. 
</P>
<P>
	The twist is this: The informant, contractor William Russell, is  
the one on trial for fraud, obstruction and perjury, while the 
union leader is a key witness for the prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell, 60, of Schaumburg had served as a confidential  
informant to the FBI on other occasions and was paid by the 
government on a full-time basis to help agents snare corrupt 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Russell had been a reliable informant for nine  
years when he volunteered to help snare Jerry O'Connor, head of the 
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers in the Chicago 
area. 
</P>
<P>
	In September 1991, while his phone was wired with a tape  
recorder, Russell claimed O'Connor demanded a $12,000 payoff ``in 
tens, twenties and fifties'' for steering electrical contracting 
work to Russell. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Russell, 60, faked the tape by enlisting an  
unknown accomplice to pose as O'Connor. Prosecutors said Russell 
was under pressure to provide evidence to back up his claim that 
the union leader wanted a payoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you ask for a payment in tens, twenties and fifties?''  
prosecutor David Buvinger asked O'Connor after playing the tape 
Monday for jurors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did not,'' O'Connor replied. Federal prosecutors believe  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell is heard on the tape telling the man identifying himself  
as O'Connor that he sounds terrible. The man then says he had ``a 
bad cold.'' He also keeps the conversation short, saying he doesn't 
have much time to talk. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell had told agents the payoff amount was to be $10,000.  
When the voice says that he wants $12,000, Russell expresses 
surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deal has changed,'' the man says gruffly.  
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys, who are expected to cross-examine O'Connor  
today, say the voice on the tape is indeed that of O'Connor and 
that Russell delivered the $10,000 to the labor leader in a Chicago 
union hall four days later. 
</P>
<P>
	But union representatives from Eau Claire, Wis., testified for  
the government that records from their meeting that night indicate 
O'Connor was there, speaking about union organizing. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors also presented expense account vouchers, gasoline  
credit-card receipts and union records to suggest that O'Connor was 
not only at the Eau Claire meeting but later spent the night in 
Madison, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the assumption that Russell had passed the $10,000 in cash  
to O'Connor, the FBI launched a $173,000 undercover operation 
deigned to snare other union leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation was shut down without uncovering any corruption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
