<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Stewart Klein    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stewart Klein, a three-time Emmy Award-winner  
and a colorful movie and theater critic for New York's Fox Channel 
5 for more than 30 years, died Monday at age 66. 
</P>
<P>
	Klein, who was battling cancer, suffered a stroke.  
</P>
<P>
	Klein was with the station since 1967, and became part of the  
original on-air team of ``The 10 O'Clock News.'' He also 
contributed theater and movie reviews to ``Good Day New York,'' and 
``Fox Five Live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1978, Klein won his first Emmy for a review of ``Sebastian,''  
a controversial film in Latin about St. Sebastian. Klein panned the 
film in Latin. The second Emmy came for his ``Ode To The Mets,'' in 
1986, to honor the World Series champs. His final Emmy, in 1994, 
was a lifetime achievement award. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1980, The Associated Press cited Klein for the year's best  
coverage of a breaking story, the death of director Gower Champion. 
</P>
<P>
	He made his debut in journalism as a copy boy for The  
Philadelphia Inquirer. He later joined the Daily Intelligencer as a 
reporter, and went on to the Philadelphia Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1959, Klein became news director for WCAU Radio in  
Philadelphia, then joined ABC News as a New York based reporter in 
1961. There he was a featured ``Flair Reports'' reporter along with 
Charles Osgood and Ted Koppel. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1964, Klein joined WNEW Radio in New York, and became a  
regular arts and entertainment critic. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, a son and three other children.  

</P>
<P>
                      *Shirley Dinsdale Layburn    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shirley Dinsdale Layburn, a ventriloquist who  
won an Emmy Award in 1949, the first year the awards were 
presented, died Sunday of cancer. She was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Layburn received her Emmy for Most Outstanding Television  
Personality. 
</P>
<P>
	Her show appeared on Paramount Studio's KTLA in Los Angeles and  
featured her and her puppet ``Judy Splinters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She later had her own children's show on KNBH-NBC, followed by  
several other shows on ABC in New York and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	She later quit her television career and from 1973 to 1985 was  
the head of the Respiratory Therapy Department of John T. Mather 
Memorial Hospital in Port Jefferson, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Layburn, who was born in San Francisco, began her  
ventriloquism career at age 14 with her radio show, ``Judy in 
Wonderland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She later moved to Hollywood, where she and her puppet had  
appearances on radio shows along personalities such as Rudy Vallee, 
Eddie Cantor and Bob Burns. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Layburn made her television debut in 1947 announcing shows  
and giving children birthday greetings on KTLA. Her appearances led 
to the weekly children's show, ``The Judy Splinters Show.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Wynona M. Lipman    	
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Wynona M. Lipman, the first black woman  
elected to the New Jersey Senate and the longest-serving member of 
the upper house, died Sunday of cancer. She never disclosed her 
age; Democrats said she was about 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipman, who joined the state Senate more than 27 years ago, had  
championed the causes of women, minorities, children and small 
businesses. Bills she had proposed that became law included 
measures to increase the penalties for adults who patronize child 
prostitutes, and to expand the state's domestic violence laws to 
protect more victims and provide more services for children. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipman was first elected to the state Senate in 1971.  
</P>
<P>
	In a 1989 forum on women and politics, Lipman recalled that when  
she was first elected, the Senate didn't even have rest room 
facilities for women. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Maurice Scott    	
</P>
<P>
	CLIFTON, N.J. (AP) -- Maurice Scott, a trumpeter and band leader  
whose namesake orchestra headlined concert halls for a 
half-century, died Saturday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maurice Scott Orchestra played in New York hotels and other  
landmark venues in the region. For 20 years, Scott's band 
entertained summer visitors at the Nemerson Resort in the 
Catskills. For another 15 years, the orchestra's home was the 
Metropolitan Hotel in Asbury Park. 
</P>
<P>
	The band's run lasted for more than 50 years, with Scott  
fronting the group and contributing trumpet and vocals. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott, whose real name was Maurice Anzaldi, also played with  
Tommy Dorsey, Jackie Gleason and Sammy Davis, Jr. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Shel Silverstein    	
</P>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Shel Silverstein, the author of such  
acclaimed children's books as ``A Light in the Attic'' and ``Where 
the Sidewalk Ends,'' was found dead Monday morning of a heart 
attack. He was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverstein's books, which he illustrated with his own humorous  
images, are packed with colorful characters like walruses with 
braces and camels in brassieres. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverstein is best known for his children's poetry. His work  
includes ``The Giving Tree'' (1964), ``Falling Up'' (1996) ``Where 
the Sidewalk Ends'' (1974) ``A Light in the Attic'' (1981), ``The 
Missing Piece Meets the Big O'' (1981) and ``The Missing Piece'' 
(1976). 
</P>
<P>
	He won numerous awards for his work including the Michigan Young  
Readers Award for ``Where the Sidewalk Ends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before turning to children's poetry, Silverstein wrote verse for  
adults only. His career began as a writer and cartoonist for 
Playboy magazine in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverstein also was a celebrated lyricist, publishing numerous  
songs including Johnny Cash's ``A Boy named Sue'' and Loretta 
Lynn's ``One's on the Way.'' He also wrote the folk songs 
``Unicorn'' and ``25 Minutes to Go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include son.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 09:25:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skydiving Plane Crash Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CELINA, Ohio (AP) -- A small plane that crashed into a field,  
killing the pilot and all five sky divers aboard, had taken off 10 
times that day, the operator of the skydiving club said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounded good, just like it always did,'' said Robert  
Tangeman, who owns the plane and has operated the Grand Lake 
Skydiving Club for 10 years. Witnesses said the plane's engine 
sputtered and died soon after takeoff Sunday from Lakefield Airport 
in Montezuma. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Transportation Safety Board today was to visit the  
scene of the crash about a mile east of the airport. The Federal 
Aviation Administration also is investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane experienced engine trouble after taking off from the  
airport, the State Highway Patrol said. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident was over in four or five seconds, said dairy farmer  
Charles Schwieterman, who witnessed the crash and was the first 
person to reach the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	``The plane went into half a turn and went straight down head  
first,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Killed were the pilot, Preston E. Parrish II of Tipp City, and  
five skydivers. Tangeman said the sky divers were members of his 
club and jumped every weekend. He said the plane, a Cessna, was 
built in 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwieterman and his son, Chuck, heard the plane overhead early  
Sunday evening about a mile from the runway. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seemed like he was trying to climb but the engine didn't  
sound right,'' Schwieterman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The engine started sputtering, then ``clonked completely out,''  
he said. He saw one sky diver jump out, but that person's chute 
opened only partway. 
</P>
<P>
	Celina is 27 miles southwest of Lima in west-central Ohio.  
</P>
<P>
	The dead skydivers were identified as John Hoover, 43, Michelle  
Korsen, 43, and Arron Schroeder, 30, all of Fort Wayne, Ind.; Jack 
Haenichen, 31, of Ottawa, Ohio; and Keith Edwards, 40, of Marion, 
Ind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:55:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Panel Rejects Steel Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A U.S. panel rejected punitive tariffs Monday  
on some stainless steel from six countries, ruling unanimously that 
foreign pricing practices have not hurt U.S. producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the steel in question, stainless round wire, is a  
relatively small product line, the ruling underscores the U.S. 
International Trade Commission's independence and suggests that it 
will not rubber-stamp cases from the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department determined earlier that Canada, India,  
Japan, South Korea, Spain and Taiwan illegally dumped stainless 
round wire in U.S. markets at prices below production costs. Before 
Commerce could impose tariffs, the commission had to find that the 
dumping has hurt or threatens to harm U.S. producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission ruled, on a 6-0 vote, that no injury or threat to  
U.S. industry resulted from the round-wire pricing. Commissioners 
did not discuss their reasoning during the meeting and refused 
comment afterward. A written opinion is due in a few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed in the negative finding of injury by the  
ITC,'' said George Kurisky, chairman of the U.S. Stainless Wire 
Action Committee, a coalition of domestic producers. ``We continue 
to believe that the data prove injury to a competitive and 
efficient American industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steelworkers have been intensifying pressure on the Senate to  
approve quotas on steel. The House has passed a quota bill, but the 
administration opposes it on the ground that trade cases filed with 
Commerce and the commission are adequate to combat last year's 
surge in low-priced steel imports. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Commerce found that Japan dumped a more common steel  
product, hot-rolled carbon steel. Japanese representatives 
denounced the ruling as politicized and looked to the trade 
commission for what they consider will be a more independent 
review. 
</P>
<P>
	Stainless steel round wire is used to produce springs, wire rope  
and fasteners in construction and other applications. It is a $300 
million-a-year domestic industry, and imports add another $100 
million, industry officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce had proposed tariffs of as much as 36 percent on  
stainless round wire. Industry officials said they would review the 
commission's opinion before deciding whether to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The government already has imposed tariffs on other types of  
stainless steel, a specialty line, and has other cases pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports reached record levels in 1998 in the wake of the Asian  
economic crisis, which lowered demand for steel abroad and forced 
foreign producers to turn to U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade cases were filed by ACS Industries Inc. of Woonsocket,  
R.I.; Al Tech Specialty Steel Corp. of Dunkirk, N.Y.; Branford Wire 
&AMP; Manufacturing Co. of Mountain Home, N.C.; Carpenter Technology 
Corp. of Reading, Pa.; Handy &AMP; Herman Specialty Wire Group of 
Cockeysville, Md.; Industrial Alloys Inc. of Pomona, Calif.; Loos &AMP; 
Co. Inc. of Pomfret, Conn.; Sandvik Steel Co. of Clarks Summit, 
Pa.; Sumiden Wire Products Corp. of Stockton, Calif.; and Techalloy 
Co. Inc. of Mahwah, N.J. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
