<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 11:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Spending Eats at Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A multibillion-dollar package financing the  
Yugoslavia campaign is just one item nibbling away at federal 
surpluses. That's a worry for Republicans, who have promised 
repeatedly to shrink government and leave Social Security funds 
untouched. 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, the Congressional Budget Office thinks the 1999  
surplus will be $111 billion, the biggest ever. All of it comes 
from Social Security, which is collecting more money than it spends 
each year to prepare for the baby boomers' coming retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	While this year's surplus is hardly in danger of vanishing, it  
is about to start shrinking, to the dismay of many conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	``The great danger is there is no more fiscal discipline in  
Washington,'' said Marshall Wittman, congressional affairs director 
for the conservative Heritage Foundation. ``The irony is that when 
we got to a balanced budget, Republicans lost the major brake we 
had on spending, which was the deficit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As early as this week, lawmakers may send President Clinton a  
measure to pay for the battle in the Balkans and other items. Its 
price tag of at least $9 billion is certain to come almost entirely 
from the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers want to add $1 billion to that bill for school  
safety and up to $4.3 billion for farmers. That measure seems 
likely to be attached to another bill bearing help for Central 
America for last autumn's Hurricane Mitch and for U.S. farmers, to 
which senators have added hundreds of millions to aid the oil, 
hard-rock mining and steel industries. 
</P>
<P>
	By year's end, lawmakers and Clinton may dip even deeper into  
surpluses for 1999 and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Both parties say they want to spend more to improve education,  
fortify the military and boost troops' pay. Democrats want to add 
prescription coverage to Medicare, and others want to roll back 
Medicare savings imposed two years ago on hospitals and other 
health-care providers. And Republicans want a tax cut of about $800 
billion over the next decade, although they say none of it would be 
paid for from Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	For many Republicans, using the surplus to pay for such  
proposals could wound their effort to represent themselves as 
protectors of Social Security, a major goal in this pre-election 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politically, the Republican Congress is creating a track  
record that can be used against them,'' warned Ron Utt, a senior 
fellow at Heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the Kosovo spending measure is not even the first chunk  
lawmakers have bitten from the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	When Congress and Clinton enacted a big package of so-called  
``emergency'' spending last fall, it was financed through the 
surplus, which the nonpartisan CBO estimates will trim this year's 
black ink by $17 billion. Without it, the latest projection for the 
1999 surplus would have been $128 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	That spending spree, however, upset many conservative voters,  
which Republicans say stoked their poor showing in last November's 
congressional elections. In reaction, many GOP leaders want to 
sharpen the party's conservative image by holding such raids on the 
surplus to a minimum. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of conservative senators led by Senate Majority Whip Don  
Nickles, R-Okla., have been pushing to keep the Kosovo package 
close to the $6 billion Clinton requested. Their worry is that the 
more money Congress adds to it, the blurrier becomes the Republican 
message of protecting Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	That was underlined when conservative Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla.,  
proposed paying for the Kosovo measure last week by cutting 
domestic programs across the board. He was defeated 322-101, but 
not before highlighting his party's sensitivity to eroding Social 
Security's surpluses just weeks after Congress approved a 
GOP-written budget pledging to leave that money alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is morally right to support our troops'' but not ``to take  
money from the Social Security system, to take money out of the 
very future that we say is our highest priority,'' Coburn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coburn proposal aimed a spotlight on a schism within the  
GOP, as more than half of House Republicans voted against his 
amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	That split illustrated how little taste many Republicans have  
for the domestic spending cuts he proposed, plus their belief that 
since Clinton also proposed paying for the fighting with the 
surplus, there would be scant political price to pay for doing just 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can blame this one on Clinton without blinking hard,'' said  
Rich Galen, executive director of the Republican political action 
committee GOPAC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
