<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Mixed; Corn, Soybeans Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures were mixed early today on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while corn and soybeans moved higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured amid concerns the NATO bombing of  
the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia would dim any hopes for new 
Chinese purchases. Prices were bolstered, however, after the U.S. 
Agriculture Department reported that wheat inspected for export 
totaled 26.23 million bushels, a figure higher than expectations 
and twice that of a week earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans were boosted by some private meteorologists'  
predictions for wet weather this week in parts of the Midwest, 
which could delay planting. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 2 cents to $2.62 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 3/4 cent to $2.19 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1/4 cent to 
$1.22 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans rose 1 1/4 cents to $4.78 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while lean hogs were mostly lower and pork bellies were higher. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .03 cent to 61.37 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .03 cent to 72 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .08 cent to 60.55 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .78 
cent to 60.65 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
