<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 16:53:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veto Threatened on Kosovo Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the first time, the Clinton administration  
threatened Monday to veto a bill providing money for the conflict 
with Yugoslavia, aid for Central America and other items, citing a 
host of objections. Indications were, however, that such a 
confrontation would be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, administration officials had threatened to veto a  
stand-alone aid measure for Central America and U.S. farmers 
because it would cut domestic programs and add environmental and 
other items the White House opposes. They had complained about a 
separate bill in which the House more than doubled President 
Clinton's $6 billion request for the fight over Kosovo, but not 
threatened to veto it. 
</P>
<P>
	But Monday, on the eve of meetings among House and Senate  
negotiators who plan to combine the two bills, White House 
officials warned that the new, blended legislation was in jeopardy 
of being rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a number of very troubling issues ... and the  
president's senior advisors would continue to recommend that he 
veto this legislation unless the objectionable provisions are 
resolved in a satisfactory manner,'' said a letter to House leaders 
by White House budget chief Jacob Lew. 
</P>
<P>
	Before, members of both parties had said privately that they  
don't think Clinton would veto the Kosovo package as long as it was 
kept at roughly the $13 billion range the House approved last week. 
They believe that with American troops in the field and with 
Clinton himself saying the Pentagon needs more money, he would be 
hard-pressed to reject such a measure. 
</P>
<P>
	But in an interview, Lew said of the defense package, ``It's  
important to scale it back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The extra money the House added was for U.S. military operations  
and installations around the world, and for a pay raise for troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Some GOP participants in the negotiations, speaking on condition  
of anonymity, have said they expect Republicans to pare the 
military package to roughly $10 billion. The likeliest item to be 
dropped is $1 billion the House added to modernize U.S. bases 
overseas, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really haven't settled anything yet,'' House Appropriations  
Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 16, Clinton requested nearly $1 billion to help Honduras  
and other Central American nations devastated by last autumn's 
deadly Hurricane Mitch. He later asked for $152 million to help 
U.S. farmers hurt by record-low prices for wheat, corn and other 
farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 23, the Senate approved a $2.5 billion bill for Central  
America and farmers, which included aid they had added for the U.S. 
steel, oil, gas and mining industries. The next day, the House 
approved a $1.3 billion version without the Senate add-ons. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration objections include Senate language that would bar  
the federal government from sharing in the $246 billion settlement 
states have won from the tobacco industry; delay increases in 
royalties oil companies pay for using federal lands; and postpone 
stricter requirements for hardrock mining on government property. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House also objects to GOP plans to pay for the Central  
America aid with cuts in food stamps, along with money the U.S. 
uses to back loans by international lending agencies and other 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration prefers using this year's expected federal  
surplus. Many aides from both parties, however, believe a 
compromise will be reached on spending reductions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
