<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Looking To Even Series  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Round One went to Tim Duncan.  
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Garnett aims to take Round Two when his Minnesota  
Timberwolves face the San Antonio Spurs on Tuesday night in the 
second game of their best-of-5 first-round Western Conference 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``A must win, if that's what you want to call it,'' Garnett  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs won the series opener 99-86 Sunday led by Duncan's 26  
points and 12 rebounds and helped by 21 points from Avery Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Garnett was forceful in the first half, scoring 15 of his  
21 points, he ran out of steam and into foul trouble as Duncan got 
going in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Garnett was scoreless in the final quarter, when the top-seeded  
Spurs opened up a comfortable double-digit lead and the 
eighth-seeded Timberwolves couldn't recover. 
</P>
<P>
	``They kept double-teaming, but I split a couple of them. They  
didn't come as fast,'' Duncan said. ``A lot of things changed and I 
took advantage of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garnett expects some differences Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm probably going to be a lot more aggressive,'' he said.  
``I'll try to stay aggressive for the whole game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garnett, who turns 23 next week, and Duncan, who turned 23 last  
month, guarded each other much of the time Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Early in the game a hot-headed Garnett got in Duncan's face and  
did some intense talking to his fellow 7-footer. Duncan listened, 
then walked away laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just broke out like that, so I responded,'' Garnett said.  
Like Duncan, he didn't repeat the contents of the conversation. 
</P>
<P>
	Garnett insists his duel with Duncan is overblown.  
</P>
<P>
	``You have to understand, I was playing Sean Elliott, I was  
playing David Robinson and I was still being me,'' Garnett said. 
``I think that matchup thing is more of a media thing than 
anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan seemed to agree, saying he makes little out of the  
``hype.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're both good players. We're both going to go out there and  
compete for our teams and do the best we can for our teams, and 
that's where it ends,'' Duncan said. 
</P>
<P>
	But fans and even teammates are intrigued by the competition  
between the two talented players. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great matchup. They can go back and forth and all the  
rest of us can go sit down and watch them sometimes,'' Johnson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the Spurs against the Timberwolves, but those guys are  
the two key components of each team,'' added Spurs guard Mario 
Elie. ``It was a terrific matchup and I thought both of those guys 
played tremendous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan, who gained some support for MVP honors toward the end of  
the regular season, and Robinson led the Spurs in a stretch run in 
which the Spurs captured the Midwest Division title. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs and Timberwolves split their regular season series  
2-2. 
</P>
<P>
	When Minnesota was successful against San Antonio this season,  
it was because the Spurs were forced to rely on shots from players 
besides Robinson and Duncan, said Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders. 
</P>
<P>
	So Johnson's point production Sunday wasn't a surprise. It was  
part of Minnesota's game plan. The tough part for the Timberwolves 
was that Duncan found a way to get the ball and score in the second 
half despite Minnesota's efforts, Saunders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll do some things to change up, because we see some areas  
where we can make some improvement,'' Saunders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs aren't satisfied either. They're vowing to play better  
defense throughout Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy about the win but we know the next one's not going  
to be easy,'' Duncan said. ``We're going to go out there and try to 
play a better game.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
