<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Appleby Returns to Avenel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	POTOMAC, Md. (AP) -- Stuart Appleby, gazing at the 18th hole from  
the clubhouse patio, fidgeted with his wedding ring as he talked 
about his victory last year at the Kemper Open. It was the last 
time his wife would ever see him win. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there was a last tournament that I could win for two or  
three years, this would certainly be the sweetest one, just to have 
the flush of memories again,'' the 28-year-old Australian said 
Monday as he visited the TPC at Avenel course, where he will defend 
his title May 27-30. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be one of the hardest ones to win because of the  
memories, too. But that's what Renay would love for me to do, just 
to do it all again. That's what she's been pushing me to do the 
last nine, 10 months. I just make sure I draw on the resources that 
don't get in my way and go out there and have fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Renay Appleby was 25 when she was killed last July in a freak  
accident. She was crushed by a car while unloading luggage at a 
London train station after the British Open. The news stunned the 
golf world, and Stuart Appleby made a frail and emotional return in 
August at the PGA Championship, where he bravely discussed his 
wife's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he has recovered physically -- he won the Houston  
Open earlier this month for his third career PGA Tour title -- but 
his emotions are far from healed. Golf is his therapy, but so is 
his openness about his feelings. Almost every answer Monday 
contained at least a passing reference to Renay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's like one room, you open the door and close  
the door and go into another. It's not as simple as that,'' Appleby 
said. ``You go into a transition, a slow process. It's like a wine. 
When does a wine become drinkable? Is it 12 months, two days? For 
me, when am I ready? I don't know. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not back at my best. I'm far from that in a lot of ways.  
And I don't know how long it'll take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appleby, taking a few days off to heal a back injury, said golf  
has been therapeutic, something to fill the time, but it doesn't 
consume his life. Asked whether the next step in his promising 
career would be a victory in one of the four majors, he quickly 
reset the conversation back in perspective. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's funny, because the next step for me, in the last eight or  
nine months, hasn't been golf,'' Appleby said. ``Renay was the rest 
of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Appleby said Renay is with him on the course, inspiring him and  
giving him patience because he sometimes finds he doesn't have any. 
His first victory after the accident was in front of her parents at 
the Coolum Classic in Australia in January, and he said he had to 
``try to be Renay, try to talk to myself'' to stay calm during the 
final round at Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than in his immediate natural thoughts following the  
tragedy, Appleby said he never considered giving up golf. He keeps 
on, because Renay wouldn't have it any other way. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to believe there's a future,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
