<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Late Celtic Star's Widow Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Months after Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis  
collapsed and died on a practice court in July 1993, his pregnant 
widow went on television saying she did not blame his sudden death 
on the lead cardiologist. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that Dr. (Gilbert) Mudge is a wonderful person. I  
think that he's a very caring physician. I think that he's a very 
credible and capable physician,'' Donna Harris-Lewis said in an 
interview that aired on Boston's WBZ-TV in November 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis was confronted with those words Monday during her  
second full day of testimony in the malpractice suit she brought in 
1996 against Mudge and two other doctors who treated her husband 
before his death at 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge's attorney, William Dailey Jr., has suggested that it  
wasn't until a 1995 Wall Street Journal article raised the 
possibility of cocaine use by Lewis that Harris-Lewis decided to 
sue. The article said Mudge warned Lewis that if he ``was still 
doing (cocaine), he has to stop, immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such drug use would threaten insurance and contract money  
Harris-Lewis received after her husband died, Dailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis has denied Lewis ever used drugs.  
</P>
<P>
	She sued Mudge, of Brigham and Women's Hospital, and two doctors  
who consulted on the case, Mark Creager and Peter Friedman, 
claiming they misdiagnosed and mistreated Lewis' condition. A third 
consultant settled with Harris-Lewis for an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge, who met Lewis after he collapsed during a playoff game in  
April 1993, initially agreed with a group of doctors who had 
diagnosed Lewis with a potentially fatal cardiac arrhythmia. But 
after further tests, Mudge told Lewis he had a less serious 
neurological condition that causes fainting spells. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months later, Lewis died while practicing jump shots at  
Brandeis University. Mudge has said lies about cocaine use kept him 
from making an accurate diagnosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Under cross-examination Monday, Harris-Lewis denied Dailey's  
suggestion that she had tried to keep Mudge from talking to 
insurance officials after Lewis died. 
</P>
<P>
	``You knew if that (insurance) form had been filled out in a  
manner less than truthful, there could be a problem in recovering 
on the insurance,'' Dailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't worried about it,'' replied Harris-Lewis. She had  
several testy exchanges with the defense attorney, whose patience 
seemed to wear thin at times as Harris-Lewis asked him to repeat 
questions or gave indirect answers. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis scoffed at Dailey's suggestion that Lewis may have  
ignored his doctors' orders about exercise and medication in the 
months before his death. She said she drafted an exercise schedule 
for her husband -- approved by Mudge -- that included only three 
activities: weight lifting, stretching and tai chi. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dailey has said he has a witness who will testify she saw  
Lewis ``glistening with sweat'' while shooting baskets after his 
release from the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Dailey then produced pharmacy records that seemed to indicate  
there was a lapse of more than a week in Lewis' prescription of 
beta blockers, drugs that reduce the heart's workload, which he was 
supposed to take every day. 
</P>
<P>
	Dailey also raised questions about Harris-Lewis' motivations,  
pointing to her request while Lewis was hospitalized for a meeting 
at Brigham and Women's Hospital with Celtics management. 
</P>
<P>
	Dailey asked Harris-Lewis if she had called the meeting to  
discuss a contract extension for her husband. After several 
denials, Harris-Lewis admitted the extension ``was one of the 
subjects'' discussed at the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis is suing to recover money Lewis would have made had  
he lived, estimates of which have ranged from $40 million to more 
than $100 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
