<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Mulls Yugoslav Port Blockade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- As oil continues to arrive in  
Yugoslavia, NATO generals and political leaders are wrestling with 
a plan to blockade its ports. The question is what to do about 
ships that refuse to stop or those that are found to be carrying 
oil. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Atlantic Council, NATO's top policy-making body, is  
hoping to get a look at its military planners' ideas for a naval 
blockade at a meeting today. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the major targets of the allied air operation has been  
Yugoslavia's oil refining and storage capacity. In nearly seven 
weeks of airstrikes, NATO has put the country's two refineries, at 
Novi Sad and Pancevo, out of commission and destroyed one-third of 
Yugoslavia's fuel storage capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme allied commander in Europe, says  
it is unconscionable to risk the lives of pilots to destroy these 
targets and then allow refined petroleum products to enter through 
the back door. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO leaders agreed at their summit last month in Washington on  
an oil blockade, which the alliance euphemistically calls a ``visit 
and search regime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to make it clear that all allies are committed to a  
visit and search regime,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea. ``We are 
all committed to having one, and there will be one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Where the allies differ is on how to enforce it.  
</P>
<P>
	Clark and many of the allies want a blockade with teeth allowing  
allied ships to fire on tankers that refuse to stop for inspection. 
Others, like France and Germany, want it to be voluntary, though 
they don't have an answer for what to do in the case of those 
defying a voluntary embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	Some countries are concerned about the legality of a blockade  
without an official declaration of war. Others, like Greece and 
Italy, worry about the scope, whether it should include the entire 
Adriatic Sea or just the waters around the ports of Bar and Kotor. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States argues that a blockade is justified under an  
existing embargo on war material to Yugoslavia. Others say, 
however, that without a declaration of war, only the United Nations 
could authorize a blockade. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-nation European Union has joined in a voluntary oil  
embargo and accepted that any ships flying member country flags can 
be stopped and inspected. Other countries have also joined in the 
voluntary effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, oil continues to flow in -- at least five ships in  
the past week, diplomats say. Those most likely to eschew an 
embargo include Iran, Iraq, Malta, even Russia. Nobody knows how 
much oil is getting in by sea, but it is estimated to be in the 
hundreds of thousands of barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	Diplomats say they are certain a formula can be found that will  
allow all 19 NATO members to sign on. Just what that will be, 
however, is unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	The big problem is boarding a ship if the captain takes a  
belligerent attitude. A second problem is what to do with a ship 
found with prohibited war material. 
</P>
<P>
	During the Bosnian war, ships attempting to break the U.N.  
blockade were taken to a port and held. A similar practice against 
Yugoslavia could discourage ship owners in it purely for the money. 
</P>
<P>
	An alternative is simply to destroy the ports from the air, but  
the two ports in question are in Montenegro, the smaller of the two 
republics that make up the Yugoslav federation. NATO has been 
treading lightly in Montenegro, which opposes the policies of 
President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	The Montenegrins have been begging NATO not to strike Bar and  
Kotor because if they do, the Montenegrin economy will probably 
collapse. So far they have been spared, even though Yugoslav 
warships moored there fire almost nightly on NATO planes heading 
for targets in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
