<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken To Rejoin Orioles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cal Ripken will rejoin the Baltimore Orioles on  
Thursday or Friday in Texas after a rehabilitation assignment at 
the team's extended spring training camp in Sarasota, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken went on the disabled list for the first time in his  
career on April 18 because of nerve irritation in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's shown plenty of agility and ability already,'' Orioles  
manager Ray Miller said before Monday night's game against the 
Indians. ``It's just a matter of seeing some live pitching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 38-year-old third baseman is in Sarasota, Fla. for workouts  
and practice games until Wednesday, when he will decide on a 
definite date for his return. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken worked out before Sunday's game against the Detroit  
Tigers, which the Orioles won 5-0, and said he felt ready to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Sept. 20, Ripken voluntarily ended his record consecutive  
games streak by sitting out the Orioles' final home game against 
the New York Yankees. It was the first game he missed since 
beginning his record streak of 2,632 games on May 30, 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Willis Otanez started at third base Monday night for  
Baltimore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
