<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Execs Bid for Chip Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) -- A group of present and former Motorola  
Corp. executives has asked the firm's board of directors for 
``immediate'' consideration of its $1.6 billion offer to buy the 
company's semiconductor components unit. 
</P>
<P>
	TFG Acquisition Group said it made an unsolicited offer March 30  
for the unit and recently refined it to profess job security for 
most of the 14,000 workers at plants in nine countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The (semiconductor) unit is certainly a gem in the Motorola  
portfolio and ... will provide a strong operational and financial 
base upon which to build a premier organization to serve existing 
and new customers with the basic products of today and new products 
for the future,'' said Gary Thomas, TFG Acquisition's acting chief 
financial officer and former controller of two Motorola divisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola spokesman David Rudd said the company would not comment  
on the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola is restructuring its chip-making business to make it  
more profitable after a major downturn in the industry last year 
that came partly as a result of the Asian economic crisis. There 
was some speculation in February that the Schaumburg, Ill., 
equipment maker was shopping the chip components unit around for a 
sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid, which remains contingent on approval by Motorola, is  
``genuinely superior to deals currently being considered'' by 
Motorola, TFG Acquisition said. The group has received a letter of 
intent for financing the purchase from a leading international bank 
and an equity investment firm, according to a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
