<DOCNO> APW19990510.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 17:21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres and Bruins Heating Up Series / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- It's only taken two playoff games and one  
rough hit on Ray Bourque to create fury between the Boston Bruins 
and Buffalo Sabres. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things will boil,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff promised Monday.  
``It's going to become an angry series. We were physical in Boston; 
we'd like to take it up one more notch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres will try to do that when the series switches to  
Buffalo for Games 3 and 4 on Wednesday and Friday. Buffalo tied the 
series at a game apiece with a 3-1 victory at Boston on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Matters started really heating between these teams when  
Buffalo's Alexei Zhitnik slammed Bourque into the boards from 
behind during Sunday's game. Defenseman Kyle McLaren took it upon 
himself to inform Zhitnik that the 38-year-old Bourque, the Bruins' 
captain, is not available for Sabres target practice. 
</P>
<P>
	At first, McLaren said he did not know who Zhitnik hit and  
caused to slump to the ice. But after realizing it was Bourque, 
McLaren followed Zhitnick to the penalty box where he pointed his 
finger, hollered some obscenities and, as McLaren said, ``put it in 
his ear and let him know that we're coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McLaren, who had four hits himself in the game, said he knows  
hits are part of the sport. He admitted that sometimes a player 
can't slow down enough to prevent a hit, but added: 
</P>
<P>
	``That hit was uncalled for. It was kind of from behind and you  
just don't do that to guys like Ray.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zhitnik earned a two-minute penalty for boarding.  
</P>
<P>
	Bourque, the 20-year Bruins veteran and sage of the Boston  
locker room, said cheap shots are a part of the game. And they 
should be expected during the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to take it when it comes up and dish it out (when  
opportunity is there),'' Bourque said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Bruins echoed McLaren's warning that Zhitnik had better  
watch his back. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot you can get away with (on the ice),'' Bruins  
forward Tim Taylor said. ``(Zhitnik) just put himself in a really 
tough situation where every time he touches the puck, our guys are 
going to be coming -- and coming hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boston coach Pat Burns thinks his team has to get tougher in  
order to stay competitive in the best-of-7 Eastern Conference 
series. He said his players looked ``soft'' in Sunday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're much hungrier,'' Burns said of the Sabres. ``They know  
what it takes right now to continue and we're going to have to turn 
it around. Are we ready to sacrifice?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the talk of hate between these two teams, the players  
say they love the rivalry -- and the trash talk that comes with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wouldn't be any fun if nobody said anything and both teams  
really liked each other and patted each other after the game,'' 
Sabres forward Dixon Ward said. ``It's a good solid rivalry that's 
been created over the years, and we're picking it up where it left 
off.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 15:15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skater Stojko Breaks Collarbone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRAMPTON, Ontario (AP) -- Three-time world figure skating  
champion Elvis Stojko fractured his right collarbone last week 
while practicing in a rink near his home. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was skating backwards and caught an edge and went down in a  
strange, awkward position,'' Stojko said Monday while conducting a 
clinic for children. 
</P>
<P>
	He had returned to his home in Richmond Hill for a rest after  
performing in 49 shows in the annual post-world championship tour 
of the United States. He was to return to the tour Thursday in 
Florida but now aims to rejoin it in California next month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, it's kind of a blessing in disguise,'' Stojko said  
of the injury which happened last Monday. ``It'll give me a bit of 
time to think about what I want to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What he has to do is decide to either remain on the top  
competitive circuit and go for another world title, or perform 
exclusively as a professional. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's in the middle right now,'' he said when asked which way  
he was leaning. 
</P>
<P>
	Stojko will sit down later this week with his business manager  
``to study all the options on the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When it comes right down to it, when you take away all the  
so-called glamour and glitter and fame, I've got to make sure I'm 
going to be happy with what I'm doing,'' he said. ``Maybe I'd make 
a little more money as a pro, but am I really going to be happy? 
</P>
<P>
	``Am I going to be able to push my potential the way I want to?  
Do I still want to push my potential? I know I still do. So, am I 
going to be able to do it successfully in a pro situation? 
</P>
<P>
	``In the amateur world, I feel comfortable doing that because of  
the whole scene -- the rules setup, the programs, everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he doesn't expect to make an announcement until well  
into the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something I don't want to rush.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 15:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comcast Earns $73M on Cable Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Comcast Corp., the third-largest cable  
operator in the country, earned $73.5 million in the latest 
quarter, bouncing back from a loss a year ago, on strong growth in 
its cable operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings, which worked out to 12 cents per share, were ahead  
of analyst expectations and compared with a loss of $86 million, or 
11 cents per share, for the first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the quarter ending March 31 rose 9.5 percent to  
$1.37 billion from $1.25 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast attributed the good results to expansion into cable  
markets in Broward County, Fla.; Roseville, Calif.; Delaware and 
Maryland, adding over 20,600 basic customers. The results exclude 
the sales of the company's Primestar and British operations, which 
were sold last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes a week after Comcast backed out of the  
bidding war with AT&AMP;T for MediaOne, the nation's fourth-largest 
cable company. 
</P>
<P>
	Under AT&AMP;T's pact with Comcast, the two companies plan to  
exchange 2.7 million customers, giving each company a stronger 
presence in markets they have targeted for growth. Comcast will get 
2 million subscribers in seven markets, including Michigan, New 
Jersey, Pennsylvania and Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth in Comcast's digital cable and high speed Internet access  
businesses helped boost operating cash flow by 38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market, Comcast shares closed up  
$1.37 1/2 at $37.87 1/2. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Calls For Full Serb Pullout  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today he was encouraged  
by a partial Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo but repeated NATO's 
demands for a complete pullout. Yugoslavia's army announced a 
partial withdrawal of military and police forces from Kosovo, 
saying it had completed its operations against ethnic Albanian 
rebels in the southern Serb province. NATO quickly said a partial 
withdrawal would not halt its air campaign. Virtually all foreign 
reporters have left Kosovo under government orders, and it could 
not be determined if any units have actually left. 

</P>
<P>
	China Severs Arms Talks With US  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China broke off talks on arms control with the  
United States today, and allowed waves of demonstrators to hurl 
stones at the U.S. Embassy in Beijing for a third day to protest 
NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. The U.S. 
ambassador hunkered down in the American compound said the 
situation had deteriorated enough that he ordered sensitive papers 
in the embassy destroyed. China suspended diplomatic relations 
regarding human rights, arms control and international security, 
the state-run Xinhua news agency said, which affects U.S. concerns 
that China has provided nuclear weapons or missile technology to 
Pakistan, Iran or other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Marine Gets 6 Months in Gondola Case  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine pilot was sentenced today to  
six months in prison and he was dismissed from the Corps for 
helping hide a videotape shot during a flight in which 20 people 
died when his jet clipped a ski gondola cable in Italy. Capt. 
Richard Ashby also was ordered to forfeit all pay and allowance for 
his conviction last week on charges of obstruction of justice and 
conspiracy to obstruct. Jurors deliberated about two hours today 
before issuing the sentence. 

</P>
<P>
	Crews in Hawaii Search for Survivors  
</P>
<P>
	HAUULA, Hawaii (AP) -- Rescuers using heat-seeking cameras and  
military search dogs did not find any more bodies early today in 
tons of debris left by a weekend landslide that killed at least six 
people and injured dozens of others. Dozens of hikers were sunning 
themselves at a pool beneath one of Hawaii's most scenic waterfalls 
yesterday when the landslide sent tons of boulders crashing down. 
``It looks like the cliff face came away,'' state Department of 
Land and Natural Resources geologist Glenn Bauer said after flying 
over the area. 

</P>
<P>
	Tenn. Jury Sides With Tobacco Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Three of the nation's largest tobacco  
companies were cleared today of liability in the deaths of three 
smokers whose families claimed the companies' cigarettes were 
responsible. The jury returned its verdict during the fourth day of 
deliberations in the case against Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds 
Tobacco Co. and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. The families of 
three smokers who died of lung cancer filed the suit. They claimed 
the companies knowingly sold a dangerous product and tried to cover 
up the risks. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush: I Won't Embarrass You  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush said today that  
Americans can rest assured he wouldn't embarrass them if he's 
elected president next year. Bush is leading most polls for both 
the Republican nomination and overall presidential race for 2000, 
but has not officially announced his candidacy. ``I will not only 
swear to uphold the laws of our country, I will swear to uphold the 
dignity of the office,'' he said. Bush's presidential exploratory 
committee has raised an estimated $11 million so far. 

</P>
<P>
	Jaguars Found To Have Fewest Defects  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- New Jaguar cars had the fewest defects and 1999  
Kia cars the most, according to a private report to automakers by 
J.D. Power and Associates. The company's annual Initial Quality 
Study is a widely followed measure of vehicle quality. The 
Associated Press today obtained results from a confidential 
executive summary of the study which showed Jaguar had the fewest 
defects per 100 new vehicles -- 110. Buick was second at 114, 
followed by Infiniti (118), Acura (124), BMW (125) and Lexus (131). 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 36.08  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow industrials were  
down 36.08 to 10,995.51. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,648-1,350. The Nasdaq was up 13.01 at 
2,516.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Tuinei Reportedly Injected Heroin  
</P>
<P>
	PLANO, Texas (AP) -- Former Dallas Cowboys offensive lineman Mark  
Tuinei injected heroin the night before he died last week, 
according to a broadcast report today. Dallas-Fort Worth television 
station KDFW, citing court documents, said Tuinei, 39, and Cowboys 
running back Nicky Sualua spent Wednesday night at a North Dallas 
apartment. Sualua said Tuinei injected heroin and also used 
Ecstasy, a stimulant, and had a bad reaction, according to the 
documents. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

