<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Holds Cop Brutality Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A day after Mother's Day, Dorothy Elliott came  
to Capitol Hill seeking answers about her dead son. 
</P>
<P>
	Tearfully, she asked why her son, Archie, was shot 14 times by  
police in Prince Georges County, Md., and no one has been held 
accountable four years later. 
</P>
<P>
	Seated next to her was Saiko Diallo, whose son Amadou, a street  
vendor from Guinea, was killed Feb. 4 outside his New York City 
apartment when four white police officers fired 41 shots at the 
unarmed black man, focusing national attention on police treatment 
of minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police officers have been indicted for (second-degree)  
murder,'' Diallo told a hearing on police brutality held Monday by 
the Congressional Black Caucus. ``But they are still working full 
time with a full salary. This is unfair. This is not right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem isn't only excessive use of force but dragnet  
techniques,'' said Hugh B. Price, president of the National Urban 
League. He cited racial profiling of suspects on traffic stops and 
random stopping and frisking policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Lann Lee, acting assistant attorney general for civil  
rights, said that although his office is limited in its ability to 
bring federal prosecutions to local police jurisdictions, it has 
reached settlements with Pittsburgh and Steubenville, Ohio, after 
the Justice Department filed police discrimination complaints 
against the cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said investigations of the Washington, D.C., New York City  
and New Orleans police departments are under way. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen several tragedies in the last few months,'' Lee  
said. ``We have to see how we as a nation as a whole respond. Not 
by pointing fingers but by moving forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Accounts by relatives of those who died in police custody  
brought tears among both spectators and witnesses at the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can call it a tragedy but I call it a murder,'' Elliott  
sobbed. ``My son didn't resist arrest. My son's life had value.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Archie Elliott III, 24, was killed after being stopped by police  
in Prince Georges County in Washington's Maryland suburbs in June 
1995. Police said Elliott pointed a gun at them while sitting in a 
police car with his hands cuffed behind him. He refused to drop the 
gun and was shot 14 times, according to the police account. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he were a congressional aide, the legal system would have  
spared no expense to find the perpetrator,'' Elliott said. ``Isn't 
there a double standard here?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., chairman of the Congressional Black  
Caucus, said additional hearings on police abuse will be held in 
New York, Los Angeles, Houston, Chicago and Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``I promise we won't just file a report and go onto the next  
issue,'' Clyburn said. ``We need to stay focused and achieve some 
meaningful results.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
