<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Denounces Rumor-Starters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush said Monday that he has  
learned from mistakes he may have made 20 or 30 years ago, and he 
denounced those who float rumors and try to destroy a candidate's 
reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, front-runner among early GOP presidential prospects, has  
acknowledged ``youthful indiscretions'' and quitting drinking 
alcohol when he was 40. But beyond that, he has declined to discuss 
his past. 
</P>
<P>
	He repeated that stand Monday, calling it ``a Washington game''  
to get candidates to respond to reputation-tarnishing rumors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I may have made mistakes 20, 30 years ago like a lot of other  
people. But I've learned from my mistakes,'' Bush told the ABC-TV 
program ``Good Morning America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What's important, Bush insisted, is how he would conduct himself  
if elected president. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that's important for America to know about me is  
that if I'm fortunate enough to put my hand on the Bible, I will 
not only swear to uphold the laws of our country, I will swear to 
uphold the dignity of the office,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was my pledge I made to my fellow Texans, that I would  
uphold the dignity of the office, and it's a pledge I've kept.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican governor has formed a presidential exploratory  
committee that's already raised an estimated $11 million. He has 
been the front-runner in several national opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	He is staying in Texas until the Legislature ends its current  
session May 31, then plans to travel to key campaign states before 
making a final decision on whether to seek the White House in late 
summer or early fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``People can float every rumor they want, and people can try to  
destroy the reputations of candidates,'' Bush said. ``But as we 
head into the 21st century, it's necessary to say: `The past is the 
past; judge me for what I am today.''' 
</P>
<P>
	He said it's what an official does in office that counts.  
</P>
<P>
	``What people need to know about me is that I've learned from my  
mistakes and there needs to be a consistent message from people in 
my generation that says, `Drugs will destroy your life, abusing 
alcohol will destroy your life','' Bush said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 06:40:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Albania Sees New Refugee Influx </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- A recent Serb offensive in southwest  
Kosovo has produced a new wave of refugees at the Albanian border 
and again strained the meager resources of this mountain town, a 
U.N. official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 16,000 Kosovo refugees straggled across the border over  
the weekend, relaying tales of Serbs driving them out from the 
towns of Pec and Djakovica. And the influx was expected to 
continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do expect more people today. Those arriving (Sunday) said a  
lot of people were behind them,'' said Ray Wilkinson, spokesman for 
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of refugees arriving daily was shrinking last week to  
a few thousand, or even a few hundred. Aid officials were 
expressing hope that they could start moving large numbers of 
existing refugees further south, away from the unstable region 
around Kukes. The town of 30,000 people has become the temporary 
home for more than 100,000 refugees since the NATO bombing campaign 
began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	With the latest arrivals, the town square is again filled with  
ragged, sunburned refugees, milling around and looking for a tented 
camp that can take them in. 
</P>
<P>
	A large dirt field, which emptied last week as refugees moved  
on, is once again a parking lot filled with the now-familiar red 
tractors and wagons that bring most of the refugees out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The UNHCR and other aid groups are trying to strike a balance  
between providing enough resources for all the new arrivals, and 
strongly encouraging the refugees to move south as soon as 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Kukes is simply not equipped to handle the population it has  
now, aid workers say. The town is also within range of Serb 
artillery, and the Yugoslav security forces have shelled some 
Albanian border regions in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Albanian government does not have full control  
of the remote northeast corner of the country, raising further 
security concerns. Already, there have been a number of problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Albanian boys stand by the side of the road and wave at the  
newly arrived refugees on the tractors, and as they pass, the 
youths snatch clothes, food, and other supplies that may have been 
dangling over the side of the slow-moving vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Aid groups fear such petty theft could increase frictions  
between refugees and Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	The aid organizations plan a tent-to-tent information campaign  
starting Tuesday, when they will hand out leaflets and try to 
persuade refugees to move from the border. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,700 refugees left Kukes on Sunday, roughly the same as  
in recent days, and UNHCR hopes that the exodus will increase 
sharply by the end of the week. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 700,000 refugees have fled Kosovo since the NATO air  
campaign began March 24. More than 400,000 of them have crossed 
into Albania at the Morini border crossing, a narrow, two-lane road 
that hugs the side of a mountain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
