<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:51:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Makers, Anti-Gun Groups Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some of the nation's toughest anti-gun groups  
are joining with their historic enemy, gun manufacturers, to warn 
that the safety locks touted by President Clinton and others to 
fight youth violence can offer a false -- even dangerous -- sense of 
security. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing a tremendous disservice to consumers if we say,  
`Just run out and get a safety lock, and you'll be safe,''' said 
Kristen Rand of the anti-gun Violence Policy Center. She said some 
are made of such flimsy plastic they can easily be crushed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some of the ways the president portrays them, he sends a  
wrong message. They're not childproof,'' agreed Robert Delfay, 
president of the National Shooting Sports Foundation, which 
represents gun and ammunition makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet as the nation seeks ways to keep guns from children after  
the Littleton, Colo., shootings, proposals to make safety locks 
mandatory are gaining new support, even from critics like Delfay 
and Rand, who see them as imperfect. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats in Congress, backed by Clinton, will press in Senate  
debate this week to make locks mandatory. Even some Republicans 
call them acceptable. And a flurry of lawsuits by cities and by 
victims of previous school shootings cite lack of gun locks as 
evidence of manufacturers' negligence. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides generally agree that gun locks address only a  
limited, although serious, problem: The 200 or so children killed 
and more than 1,000 injured each year in gun accidents. Both sides 
believe a gun lock won't deter a determined thief. 
</P>
<P>
	Trigger locks, the most widely used, fasten like a sandwich  
around a trigger to prevent it from being pulled. Cable locks 
thread through the gun's action, preventing it from going off. Some 
work with keys, others with combinations. Guns also can be locked 
in boxes or safes, Delfay notes. 
</P>
<P>
	All have drawbacks.  
</P>
<P>
	Gun groups worry that locks can hamstring a person trying to  
fend off a surprise intruder. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost all manufacturers warn they should be used only on  
unloaded guns -- and in fact, can cause a loaded gun to fire 
accidentally. One company, Saf-T-Lok Inc., has drawn attention by 
insisting its device works on a loaded gun. The Boston police 
department recently bought Saf-T-Loks for its officers to use while 
off-duty, but Beretta USA Corp. says it tested the locks and found 
them unsafe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their purpose is to enable people to leave their guns loaded  
and even accessible to children,'' says Jeff Reh, Beretta's general 
counsel. ``That is a step backward from the conceptual idea of 
making sure guns are unloaded and away from children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, lawyers for the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence  
plan to cite Saf-T-Lok, in lawsuits on behalf of New Orleans, 
Atlanta and other cities, as evidence that gun makers still 
negligently shun expensive state-of-the-art technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The gun industry replies that advocates exaggerate, for  
political purposes, the available technology and the 
as-yet-undeveloped promise of ``smart guns'' that could identify a 
gun's owner through fingerprints, denying anyone else the ability 
to fire it. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite such fights, several gun manufacturers voluntarily have  
begun shipping locks with their firearms. Beretta began after an 
October 1997 meeting at the White House where Clinton, appearing 
with eight top gun-makers, announced voluntary agreement to include 
locks with new guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Police departments nationwide also increasingly provide locks  
both to officers and citizens. Bridgeport, Conn., has given 500 to 
citizens since February. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the city lawsuits, the families of four students  
and a teacher killed in the March 1998 Jonesboro, Ark., school 
shootings have sued two gun makers, saying the weapons used by the 
two youthful attackers, taken from the home of one boy's 
grandfather, were defective because they didn't have locks. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress this week is to debate measures, proposed by Clinton  
and Senate Democrats, to mandate child-safety locks on all guns 
sold, raise the legal age for handgun possession from 18 to 21 and 
impose background checks on buyers at all gun-show sales. A 
proposal to require safety locks failed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	While criticizing Clinton's proposals as ``knee-jerk reaction,''  
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has appeared to leave 
open the door to some restrictions, specifically child locks. Gun 
makers say they can support a proposal, depending on specifics. The 
National Rifle Association, the largest gun-owners' organization, 
opposes mandatory locks. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and most anti-gun groups, including Handgun Control  
Inc., acknowledge locks won't solve all problems but contend they 
can prevent harm if the government sets minimum standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we are trying to focus on are things that can make a  
difference -- and that can pass Congress,'' said Sen. Charles 
Schumer, D-N.Y. ``And trigger locks meet both of those 
conditions.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
