<DOCNO> APW19990510.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Edwin L. Dale Jr. Dies at Age 75 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Edwin L. Dale Jr., a former New York Times  
reporter and spokesman for the White House Office of Management and 
Budget, died of cancer Monday at the Hospice of Washington. He was 
75. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale served as assistant director of public affairs at OMB  
between 1981 and 1987, providing a critical link between reporters 
and the Reagan administration. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent two years after that as a counselor to then-Commerce  
Secretary C. William Verity before returning to the budget office 
as a director of external affairs. He worked in the area of policy 
studies before retiring in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for his mastery of the federal budget, Dale fielded a  
variety of queries from reporters -- once taking as many as 110 
calls in a day during the height of budget season. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale came to Washington in 1951 as a reporter for the New York  
Herald Tribune. Four years later, he began covering economics for 
the Times. He spent several years in Paris, and later returned to 
Washington with assignments at the White House and the State 
Department. In 1977, Dale went to work on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the author of ``Conservatives in Power'' in 1960 and was  
the primary author of ``The People's Budget,'' published in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Philadelphia, Dale graduated from Yale University in  
1944 and served in the Navy during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Meredith, and two stepchildren.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 06:15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday,  
with the key index in Hong Kong rebounding after falling sharply in 
early trading on worries over the NATO bombing of the Chinese 
embassy in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's main indicator of  
blue chips, rose 165.77 points, or 1.3 percent, closing at 
13,163.20. On Friday, the index had slumped 572.81 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices opened sharply lower as investors  
continued to take profits on concerns that Sino-U.S. relations 
would worsen because of the bombing of the Chinese embassy in 
Belgrade last week that triggered massive protests in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices rebounded in the afternoon on bargain-hunting following  
news that banking giant HSBC Holdings is to acquire Republic New 
York Corp. for U.S. $10.3 billion. Trading in shares of HSBC 
Holdings was suspended before news of the acquisition of the U.S. 
banking group. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose  
30.49 points, or 0.18 percent, closing the day's session at 
16,977.01 points. On Friday, the average lost 354.09 points, or 
2.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo share prices were supported by continued hopes that the  
government may come up with additional steps to stimulate the 
economy, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic Planning Agency chief Taichi Sakaiya said Sunday that  
an extra budget to stimulate economic growth was ``one possible 
choice'' the Japanese government is considering. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors, however, remain hesitant to buy stocks ahead of  
earnings announcements in coming weeks from Japanese companies for 
the fiscal year that ended in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 120.86 yen in late  
afternoon trading, up 0.32 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also 
marginally higher than its late Friday New York level of 120.85 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian share prices closed sharply higher on buying by  
foreign investors. The main Composite Index, which tracks 100 key 
stocks, closed at 705.83 points, up 14.15 points, or 2.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in the Philippines also closed higher, propped up by a  
cut in the central bank's overnight rates -- the 13th since the 
start of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank reduced by 0.125 percentage point its overnight  
lending and borrowing rates to 10.125 percent and 12.125 percent, 
respectively. The Philippine Stock Exchange Index of 30 selected 
companies rose 38.07 points, or 1.5 percent, to 2,564.83. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the trend was the Singapore Stock Exchange, where share  
prices closed mostly lower as investors continued to take profits. 
The key Straits Times Index closed 37.07 points, or 2 percent, to 
1,862.63. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed slightly higher for the first time  
in four sessions as investors ventured back to the market for 
bargains. The key Weighted Stock Price Index rose 15.04 points, or 
0.2 percent, to 7,484.37. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed narrowly mixed. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index slipped 0.42 point to 2,226.65. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher, with strong gains  
in the heavily weighted banking and telecommunication sectors 
outweighing sharp falls among resource stocks, particularly gold. 
The All Ordinaries Index rose 9.0 points, or 0.3 percent, to 
2,996.7. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed slightly higher. The Korea Composite  
Stock Price Index rose 3.62 points, or 0.4 percent, to 814.24. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Share prices closed mostly lower on profit-taking. The  
Composite Index slipped 0.763 point, or 0.1 percent, to 574.355. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed slightly higher. The SET index  
rose 2.08 points, or 0.4 percent, to 490.43. 

</P>
</TEXT>
