<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chevron May Buy Texaco </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chevron Corp. is discussing buying Texaco Inc.  
for about $42 billion in stock in a deal that would unite the 
nation's third and fourth biggest energy companies, The Wall Street 
Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	But the newspaper, citing unidentified people familar with the  
talks, said the companies aren't near an agreement and said a 
combination faces enormous hurdles. 
</P>
<P>
	It said officials of Chevron, based in San Francisco, and  
Texaco, based in White Plains, N.Y., declined to comment on a 
possible merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Large oil companies have been rushing to unite because of  
falling oil prices and the need to cut costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., the nation's two  
biggest energy companies, plan to vote later this month on a 
merger. British Petroleum acquired Amoco Corp., then the fifth 
largest U.S. energy concern, last year and the combined company, BP 
Amoco, has agreed to buy Atlantic Richfield Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron chairman Kenneth Derr and Texaco chief executive Peter  
Bijur both have said recently they don't need partners to be 
successful but would consider merging with other companies to 
increase cash flow or efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts say a Chevron-Texaco merger would make less  
sense than other recent oil company mergers because both companies 
have been cutting costs on their own and Texaco last year formed a 
refining partnership with Shell Oil, which would present a 
regulatory stumbling block. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
