<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Answers Sought in NYC 911 Failures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The city's 911 system experienced some delays  
with test calls placed by the New York Police Department over the 
weekend, although police said residents had no trouble getting 
emergency help. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Crotty, group president in New York and Connecticut for  
Bell Atlantic, said NYPD test callers experienced some delays in 
getting an operator over the weekend. A police spokeswoman said 
late Monday night there were no problems after some delays earlier 
in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	On a busy day, 911 in New York City receives some 30,000 calls.  
Police Commissioner Howard Safir said some calls took between five 
to 30 seconds to be answered. 
</P>
<P>
	Breakdowns have shaken peoples' confidence in the system and  
prompted criticism of Bell Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to get to the cause of this, to find out, `What is  
it?''' Bell Atlantic spokesman John Bonomo said before Monday's 
breakdown. ``We want to make sure the system is fail-safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a January service disruption, 41-year-old John Audy of  
Vermont, who was in Queens to celebrate his girlfriend's 40th 
birthday, suffered a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	His girlfriend dialed 911 three times but got busy signals.  
Finally, she ran barefoot in 23-degree weather to a police station 
nearby. Audy died by the time help arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has said the phone company has taken the  
blame, but Bell Atlantic denied having told police the breakdowns 
were its fault. Safir again blamed the phone company on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The police department, which collects a small monthly surcharge  
on phone lines, has received $117 million since 1991 for a new 
back-up 911 facility and to pay for technological upgrades but has 
failed to find an adequate site in the city of 7.4 million people. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
