<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators Adopting Bank Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At the urging of Senate Banking Committee head  
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, federal regulators are taking action to keep 
politics out of bank examinations. 
</P>
<P>
	The four major bank-regulatory agencies are adopting or making  
more formal policies barring bank examiners from discussing 
politics with bankers. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm issued a statement Monday saying the agencies' actions  
will ensure that bank inspections ``are free from political issues 
or considerations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The examination process can be trying enough for a banker  
without injecting the poison of political pressure,'' Gramm said. 
``These new policies should help prevent abuses by making sure that 
both (government) examiners and bankers are aware that exams should 
be above board.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm is a fierce critic of the 1977 Community Reinvestment Act,  
which requires banks to make loans to the poor and minorities in 
the areas in which they operate. As Congress drafts sweeping 
legislation to overhaul the financial services laws, Gramm has 
tried to keep the government's community-lending ratings for banks 
from becoming a standard for allowing them to merge with other 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	His action has put him at odds with the Clinton administration,  
which has threatened to veto a financial services bill passed by 
the Senate last week on grounds it would hurt the community lending 
law. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm said the agencies took the action in response to his  
having recently criticized the Office of the Comptroller of the 
Currency, part of the Treasury Department, for allowing its 
examiners to solicit positive ``political'' statements from bankers 
about the community lending law. 
</P>
<P>
	After the comptroller's office issued a formal directive to its  
employees prohibiting political communications, Gramm said, the 
other three agencies told him they planned to follow suit. They are 
the Federal Reserve Board, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and 
the Office of Thrift Supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Tanoue, the FDIC chairwoman, told Gramm in a letter last  
week that the agency had a long-standing unwritten, informal policy 
of ``carefully avoiding any form of political communications by 
examiners'' with banks or their affiliates. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDIC has had no problems in this area for more than 60  
years, Ms. Tanoue said. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to Gramm's request last month, the agency made the  
policy formal and distributed it to employees, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, the Federal Reserve recently formalized its  
75-year-old policy of avoiding any form of political communications 
with banks, a spokesman for the central bank said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	William Fulwider, a thrift office spokesman, said the agency  
planned to issue such guidelines to employees within the next few 
weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
