<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Potomac Runs Through History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To its earliest explorers, the Potomac was a  
river of possibilities, a broad tidal stream so rich that sailors 
felt justified in trying to catch its teeming fish with the pan 
they used to fry them. 
</P>
<P>
	The Potomac would one day know slavery and see it abolished,  
sprout a national capital on its banks, become the cockpit of a 
civil war and fight to cleanse its once-pristine waters of the 
pollution of human enterprise and waste. 
</P>
<P>
	Centuries after the explorers, it would give its name to Potomac  
Fever, a potent malady that causes perfectly respectable citizens 
to look in the mirror in the morning and see the face of the 
president of the United States staring back. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the beginning, before the Indian tribes were swept aside,  
before the spelling of its name settled down from 20 or more 
variations of ``Patwomeck,'' ``Patomeck,'' ``Pattowmack,'' some 
hoped that the Chesapeake Bay to which the river flows might be a 
sea-road that would lead all the way to China. More practically 
they saw timber, masts for ships, mines, fisheries, farms and 
livestock. 
</P>
<P>
	In the summer of 1608, the Englishmen sailing with Capt. John  
Smith found refuge in the river from a fear-inspiring ocean storm 
and ``an abundance of fish lying so thick with their heads above 
the water ... we attempted to catch them with a frying pan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the sweetest and greatest river I have found, so that  
the Thames is but a little finger to it,'' wrote Father Andrew 
White, a Roman Catholic priest arriving at ``the wished for 
country'' with the first Maryland colonists in 1633. 
</P>
<P>
	The Potomac runs just 380 miles from its source in a spring in  
the Blue Ridge Mountains, near an ancient boundary marker called 
the Fairfax Stone. 
</P>
<P>
	The river was always seen to have possibilities greater than its  
length. 
</P>
<P>
	George Washington, who lived his life near the river, was a  
constant promoter of its commercial potential in opening the West. 
</P>
<P>
	A conference held at Washington's Mount Vernon plantation in  
1785 on a dispute between Virginia and Maryland over taxing Potomac 
cargoes was a beginning link in a tangled chain of events that led 
to the drafting of the Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	That chain also led back to the Potomac when the government  
formed under the Constitution established its capital at a site of 
wavy hills and swamps on the river's banks. It was just about as 
far upstream as an oceangoing ship could sail before encountering a 
crashing wall of violent white water and jagged rocks at Great 
Falls. 
</P>
<P>
	John Adams, the first president to preside in Washington, walked  
down the slope from the White House to swim in the Potomac. John 
Tyler, the 10th president, narrowly escaped injury when a new 
cannon exploded during an 1844 Potomac boating party, killing the 
secretaries of state and the Navy and six others. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking a slave uprising, abolitionist John Brown briefly  
occupied the federal arsenal at Harper's Ferry, the place where the 
Potomac meets the Shenandoah, a place of such natural splendor that 
Thomas Jefferson had said it was worth a voyage across the 
Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	The Civil War started slowly. But the initial reports of ``all  
quiet along the Potomac'' changed soon enough. Union troops, routed 
at Bull Run, flooded back across the Potomac from Virginia. The 
bodies of Union soldiers, repulsed by Confederates at Ball's Bluff 
upriver, floated back to Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert E. Lee twice led invading Confederates across the  
Potomac. After costly, bitterly fought battles at Antietam and 
Gettysburg he led them back again and the cause of the Confederacy 
began to sink. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 20th century the greatest villain lurking on and near the  
river has been pollution that all but turned the stream into an 
open sewer. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton says that when he was a student in the capital  
in the late 1960s the Potomac was so polluted that members of the 
Georgetown University rowing crew were required to get typhoid 
shots before pulling oars through the river's fouled water. 
</P>
<P>
	The Potomac's pollution is easing, due in part to effective  
federal, state and local environmental cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some species of long-absent fish are returning. This spring a  
trio of beavers so approved of the cleaner water that they set up 
housekeeping in the Tidal Basin, gnawing through cherry trees in 
the process. 
</P>
<P>
	The Potomac still has possibilities.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
