<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 10:25:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC, Xoom.com, Snap.com Join Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is joining forces with Web directory service  
Snap.com and Xoom.com, an electronic commerce site, to form a new 
Internet company in an attempt to broaden its online presence. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal announced today, the new company, NBC Internet or  
NBCi, will operate under the Snap name online but will include 
content from NBC and the trademark peacock brand. 
</P>
<P>
	By merging several different kinds of Internet properties under  
one umbrella, the new company is hoping to position itself as a 
full-service site with search capabilities from Snap, the online 
sales expertise of Xoom.com, and entertainment content from NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC will own about half of the new venture and is contributing  
several of its online properties, including NBC.com and 
Videoseeker.com. NBC is also contributing a 10 percent ownership 
stake in CNBC.com, the parent of Snap, to the new venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Xoom.com shareholders will own about a third of the company, and  
CNET will own about 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	MSNBC, a 50-50 news partnership between NBC and Microsoft Corp.,  
was not part of the deal and will continue to operate on its own. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's president and CEO Bob Wright will become chairman of the  
new company, and Xoom.com chairman Chris Kitze will become 
president of NBCi. 
</P>
<P>
	NBCi will buy $380 million in TV advertising from the network  
over the next four years, and expects to buy an additional $500 
million over the following six years. 
</P>
<P>
	The move by NBC resembles a strategy employed successfully by  
competing network CBS, which has taken equity stakes in several 
emerging Internet companies such as Marketwatch.com and promoted 
them across its media outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	NBCi will be a publicly traded company.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
