<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bucks Get Playoff Wakeup Call  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Their postseason debut was disappointing,  
and Milwaukee's Ray Allen and Glenn Robinson are ready to show 
they've learned the difference between the NBA's regular season and 
the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest, it was a little more hype than what I thought it  
was,'' said Robinson, one of four Milwaukee starters in Sunday's 
110-88 loss to Indiana who were playing in their first playoff 
game. ``As a team, we didn't know the intensity level that you have 
to play in a playoff game. ... It was probably a wakeup call for 
us. ... We realize now how much intensity we have to play with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game 2 in the best-of-5 series is Tuesday night before the teams  
move to Milwaukee for Game 3 on Thursday. Both teams practiced 
Monday, with Indiana working out at Market Square Arena and 
Milwaukee practicing at nearby Hinkle Fieldhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, who averaged 29 points and 11 rebounds against Indiana  
in the three regular-season meetings this season, is still bothered 
by a deep knee bruise that kept him out of the last three regular 
season games. He had 16 points and seven rebounds Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're a big, strong team. They like to rebound and bang the  
boards,'' Robinson said. ``I wanted to let the game come to me. I'd 
been out like 10 days, missed three days. It was my first day back. 
... Now we're getting used to things, so everybody is on target.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allen led the Bucks with 22 points on 9-of-16 shooting.  
</P>
<P>
	``This was our first playoff game and now we know what to  
expect. We had the intensity when we started, but we leveled off in 
the second quarter,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson is just one of a lengthy list of Bucks battling  
physical problems. The group added a new name Sunday when rookie 
center Robert Traylor injured his wrist when he landed hard on the 
court after fouling Antonio Davis late in the second quarter. He 
returned in the third quarter and eventually fouled out in the 
fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	``A big thing for us is having Ray off to a good start,''  
Traylor said. ``Tomorrow if we get other guys off into the flow of 
the game, we'll have some fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traylor was icing the wrist down after practice and anticipated  
playing Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not bad at all. I'm just kind of taking it easy, getting  
ready for the next game,'' he said. ``Last night was our first time 
out. They've got all the playoff experience, but I think now that 
we've played one game, the next four games will show that we'll 
play hard and do all the right things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-7 1/2, 284-pound Traylor has the major assignment of  
muscling 7-4 Rik Smits underneath and denying him the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's my job. Once he gets the ball, he's tough to stop,''  
Traylor said. ``I just want to get it out of his hands and make him 
work for everything he gets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smits scored eight points and took eight shots in 17 minutes.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of getting ball into the post,'' Smits said.  
``They do a good job pressuring the low post with fronting and ball 
pressure. We made some adjustments ... and hopefully use it 
tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milwaukee's starters outscored Indiana's starting five, but with  
Jalen Rose scoring a career playoff high 24 points, the Pacers' 
bench outscored Milwaukee's 55-19. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we really have to concentrate more on is their second  
team,'' Milwaukee's Chris Gatling said. ``We can't have any mental 
breakdowns, and I think at times we had those. We have to make a 
conscious effort to shut those guys down and make the other guys 
beat us at the start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana will be going for its ninth consecutive victory over  
Milwaukee and its 10th straight home playoff victory in Game 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
