<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: O.J. Will Keep His Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- O.J. Simpson's lawyer says the ex-football  
star will keep custody of his children under an agreement with the 
parents of his slain ex-wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have formalized a settlement. It just needs to be signed by  
everyone,'' attorney Bernard Leckie said Monday. ``It's in the best 
interest of the children that this not be dragged out through the 
courts any further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If formalized, the agreement would head off a second struggle  
over custody of Simpson's children, a trial which promised to 
revive the argument over whether Simpson killed his ex-wife, Nicole 
Brown Simpson. 
</P>
<P>
	Leckie said he drafted a settlement agreement which is in the  
hands of the Browns' lawyer awaiting signatures and then approval 
by the court commissioner handling the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Reached at home on Monday, Simpson refused to comment on the  
reported agreement. Calls to the Browns were unreturned and their 
lawyer could not be located. The lawyer representing the children 
also did not return calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The children, Justin, 10 and Sydney, 13, live with Simpson and  
often visit their grandparents, Lou and Juditha Brown, who 
previously sued for their custody and lost. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Supreme Court ruled in February that the custody  
case could go back to court for another trial because the original 
family law judge failed to hear evidence about the slayings of Mrs. 
Simpson and her friend, Ronald Goldman. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson was acquitted in criminal court but held liable for the  
deaths in a civil trial and ordered to pay the Browns and Goldman's 
family $33.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson's lawyer said he and the Browns are on good terms and  
the grandparents are taking an active role in the children's 
upbringing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Browns and Simpson are getting along better now,'' the  
attorney said. ``They sit together at the children's athletic 
events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leckie said four mental health experts who were consulted in the  
case agreed it would be best for the children to stay with their 
father. 
</P>
<P>
	``To litigate the matter doesn't make any sense,'' Leckie said.  
``From the standpoint of the children's welfare, it is best for the 
children to believe their father did not kill their mother.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
