<HEADLINE> Hawaii Landslide Kills Six </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAUULA, Hawaii (AP) -- Dozens of people were relaxing and sunning  
themselves at one of Hawaii's most spectacular hiking spots when 
boulders the size of small cars suddenly rained down. 
</P>
<P>
	Six people were killed and dozens injured in the Sunday  
landslide that let loose with all sizes of rocks at Sacred Falls 
State Park. A seventh person is missing and presumed dead, rescue 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were bodies everywhere,'' said David Pahk, 37, a  
volunteer with the Sacred Falls Assistance Program, which hands out 
bottled water and sunscreen to often-unprepared hikers. 
</P>
<P>
	He and a dozen others worked frantically to save the life of a  
young girl, carrying her out the trail on a stretcher and sharing 
CPR efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just died in our hands,'' he said. ``No one gave up hope.  
We fought for her all the way down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue workers used heat-seeking cameras and military search  
dogs Monday, but did not find any more bodies underneath the tons 
of rubble. 
</P>
<P>
	Searchers, who had to dodge falling debris as they looked,  
returned to the scene after one injured hiker said he did not know 
what happened to his girlfriend. The woman's sister and brother, 
who were also hiking, had not seen her either. Officials assumed 
she was buried under rocks or water. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores of hikers were taking in the view and weather at a pool  
beneath the park's 90-foot falls when the landslide began 600 feet 
above them. Hikers and rescuers told harrowing stories about 
bringing victims out of the rubble. Many suffered head injuries and 
some lost limbs. 
</P>
<P>
	After flying over the area, state Department of Land and Natural  
Resources geologist Glenn Bauer said: ``It looks like the cliff 
face came away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four victims were female, and two were male, including Air Force  
Master Sgt. Scott Huling, who was stationed at Hickam Air Force 
Base. His age and hometown was not available. The victims also 
included a young girl from the family of an Air Force staff 
sergeant. Their names were not released. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen of the injured remained hospitalized, including a  
2-year-old boy. 
</P>
<P>
	State geologists said the valley on the northeast coast of the  
island of Oahu remained unstable, forcing the closure of the state 
park. 
</P>
<P>
	The park in the lushly forested Koolau Range is about 30 miles  
north of Honolulu. The falls spill into a pool, reachable by a 
2.2-mile trail, at the base of a 90-foot cliff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is unsafe for our rescue people or anybody to go up  
there,'' Honolulu Fire Chief Attilio Leonardi said Monday. ``When 
we went up this morning, debris was still falling down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our geologist says there are areas in there probably where  
more rubble will fall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The park has long been known as one of Hawaii's most dangerous.  
Since 1970, more than a dozen people have died in flash floods or 
hiking accidents at the park. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
