<DOCNO> APW19990510.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 07:35:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jenny Jones: It Wasn't Our Fault </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Talk show host Jenny Jones said she regrets the  
shooting death of a guest after he appeared on her show but does 
not agree with a jury's decision that held the program responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very regretful. I'm very sorry that Scott (Amedure)  
lost his life,'' Ms. Jones said on ``Dateline NBC'' Sunday. ``I 
think it's an awful, awful tragedy. I really don't think we can be 
held responsible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amedure, 32, was shot to death in 1995, three days after he  
admitted on a taping of ``The Jenny Jones Show,'' that he was 
attracted to Jonathan Schmitz, who had agreed to appear to meet his 
secret admirer. 
</P>
<P>
	An Oakland County jury last week ordered the show and its  
corporate owner, Warner Bros., to pay Amedure's relatives $25 
million. Lawyers for the show have said they will appeal the damage 
award. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones said she did some ``soul searching'' after the  
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course after this happened we went back. I thought back  
about the show and we all, you know, we all talked about it. We 
then and now still feel we did nothing wrong,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones said she might have felt guilty if the two had been  
introduced on the show, but they had met beforehand. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because they knew each other, that's why I keep saying that  
with or without the show, the same relationship could have 
developed,'' she said, adding that the show's content is protected 
by the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	On ABC's ``Good Morning America'' today, Ms. Jones said the  
trial would not prompt any changes in her show. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need a verdict to make us be responsible. We are  
responsible,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the March 6, 1995 taping, Schmitz was kept offstage while  
Amedure declared his attraction to him and described a sexual 
fantasy involving Schmitz. Brought on-stage and told his secret 
admirer was Amedure, Schmitz smiled, covered his face with his 
hands and told Amedure that he wasn't interested. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days later, Schmitz, then 24, bought a shotgun and shells,  
drove to Amedure's mobile home in Orion Township and shot him to 
death. His lawyers admitted he killed Amedure but contended the 
show humiliated Schmitz and he was fighting alcoholism, depression 
and a thyroid condition. 
</P>
<P>
	His 1996 conviction on second-degree murder charges was thrown  
out on a technicality. His retrial is set for this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	In the civil trial, lawyers for Amedure's family argued that the  
show ``lit the fuse'' leading to his death by first deceiving, then 
embarrassing an already disturbed Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones said the show staffers made it clear to Schmitz that  
his secret admirer could be a man or woman, and that it had no way 
of knowing about Schmitz's past suicide attempts or struggles 
against alcoholism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 17:42:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Louisiana Bus Crash Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- There were 43 of them, mostly elderly women  
from swampy small towns west of New Orleans, and they were making 
another of their occasional getaways to a Mississippi casino. 
</P>
<P>
	Few ever won any money, but they liked to get out for a while,  
to socialize and play bingo during the 1 1/2-hour bus ride. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday -- Mother's Day -- their chartered bus picked them up in  
a supermarket parking lot. A half-hour later, just as the bingo 
cards were being passed out, the bus suddenly lurched. It careened 
off Interstate 610, crashed through a guardrail and nose-dived into 
an embankment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It veered to one side and they all hollered, `It's going to  
crash!''' said George Tassin, whose wife and grown daughter were on 
the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash killed 22 people; 15 people were still hospitalized  
Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	A dozen federal investigators were at the scene Monday. The bus  
driver and a witness said a car cut the bus off right before the 
crash, but the investigators said they probably would not determine 
the cause for months. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the victims were in their 70s and 80s. Two were over 90.  
</P>
<P>
	Juanita Marse, 73, and her husband, Arto, 74, made the casino  
trip about once a month from a small town called Reserve, said 
Nancy Desselle, their daughter. They hardly ever won more than $10, 
but they loved getting together with other elderly people. 
</P>
<P>
	``They would play games on the bus,'' Ms. Desselle said.  
``Sometimes it was the same crowd, sometimes it was new people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some friends and relatives of the victims gathered at a hastily  
arranged memorial service in the Place Dubourg retirement home in 
LaPlace, a town of 25,000 about 25 miles west of New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight residents from the home were killed on the bus. Among the  
injured was Barbara Gibson, 62, who had moved into Place Dubourg 
only a month ago and was looking forward to taking a trip with the 
gambling group. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was just getting to know the people in the apartment  
complex,'' said her niece Donna Busby. ``She was so excited about 
it, and couldn't wait to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both of Mrs. Gibson's legs and arms were broken, her pelvis and  
right ankle were crushed, and her face was cut all over. ``But 
she's going to make it,'' said her daughter, Brenda Samrow. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus driver, Frank Bedell, and at least one witness said the  
bus went out of control after a compact car cut it off on a stretch 
of highway that passes through the largest park in New Orleans. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Francis, vice chairman of the National Transportation  
Safety Board, said the NTSB would interview witnesses, examine the 
bus for possible mechanical problems and look into Bedell's medical 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell, who suffered a fractured pelvis and was undergoing  
surgery Monday, drove a municipal bus in New Orleans for 17 years 
before taking a job with Custom Bus Charters about three years ago, 
said his mother, Evelyn Bedell. 
</P>
<P>
	Place Dubourg resident Isabel Dutreix recalled how one of the  
victims, her friend Dorothy Richard, 74, used to bring her pudding 
and a newspaper every day. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dutreix doesn't go on casino trips, but she and Miss  
Richard often played bingo together and would talk about splitting 
their jackpots if either won. Mrs. Dutreix couldn't wait to see 
Miss Richard on Sunday because she had such good news: She had won 
at bingo on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I would see her and I would share it with her,''  
Mrs. Dutreix said, her voice trailing off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:42:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victims Had Passion for Sky Diving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTEZUMA, Ohio (AP) -- They came from all walks of life. There  
were two engineers, a factory worker, a truck driver, and the owner 
of a construction company. But on weekends they pursued the passion 
that brought them together -- sky diving. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday evening, their single-engine Cessna crashed in a  
farmer's field shortly after takeoff in this western Ohio 
community, ending their lives and the life of their pilot. The 
plane apparently had engine trouble but the cause of the crash 
remains under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Killed were pilot Preston Parrish II, of Tipp City and  
passengers Jack Haenichen, 31, of Ottawa, Ohio; John Hoover, 43, 
Michelle Korsen, 43, and Arron Schroeder, 30, of Fort Wayne, Ind.; 
and Keith Edwards, 40, of Marion, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the passengers were sky divers and members of Grand Lake  
Skydiving, a 10-year-old operation with about 35 members. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were here all the time, every weekend,'' club owner  
Robert Tangeman said Monday. ``They were regulars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tangeman said each of the sky divers was well qualified, the  
least experienced of whom had probably jumped 250 times. One was an 
instructor and three were jumpmasters, who helped students jump for 
the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew that if he could have chosen how his life was going to  
end, it would have been sky diving,'' Edwards' wife, Michele, told 
the Fort Wayne News-Sentinel. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoover's passion for sky diving began on his 38th birthday, when  
his wife, Arlene, paid for his first jump. 
</P>
<P>
	``He lived for the weekends so he could sky dive,'' Hoover's  
sister-in-law, Rena Emery, told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Tangeman said he bought the plane five years ago and installed a  
new engine in July. He said he had had no problems with the plane 
and there was no sign of any trouble Sunday. ``It sounded good. 
Just like it always did,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash has had an impact on Tangeman, who has made 3,697  
jumps in the past 37 years. ``I may not go up anymore,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Montezuma is about 25 miles southwest of Lima.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 06:38:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Serbs Ask U.N. To End Airstrikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- As NATO missiles and bombs  
continue to pound Yugoslavia, Belgrade today accused the alliance 
of genocide and appealed to the United Nations' highest court to 
halt the punishing airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	In two days of hearings starting today, Yugoslavia and the 10  
NATO allies involved in the bombing will fight a complex legal 
battle in the World Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``The acts of bombing of the territory of Yugoslavia are not  
just illegal acts,'' Yugoslav representative Rodoljub Etinski told 
the court. ``They constitute a crime against peace and also the 
crime of genocide.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Etinski insisted that Yugoslavia's crackdown in Kosovo was aimed  
at suppressing terrorism and that the allies had no right to 
intervene in an internal conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``The case before you is clear,'' he said, wrapping up the  
Yugoslav case. ``Stop the killing, save lives of all Yugoslav 
citizens, Serbs and Albanians, civilians and soldiers. Save the 
whole nation and all its communities. Don't be late.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The court, formally known as the International Court of Justice,  
is expected to rule within weeks on Yugoslavia's request for an 
order to stop the bombing while the court considers its main case. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia has argued that NATO broke international law when it  
resorted to force in an attempt to end fighting in Kosovo. A ruling 
on the main suit could take years. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia accused the allies of genocide against the Yugoslav  
people, claiming NATO is endangering the entire population with 
pollution caused by attacks on oil refineries and chemical plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Etinski also claimed NATO is using internationally banned  
weapons -- cluster bombs and bombs containing depleted uranium -- and 
is arming and training a terrorist group -- the Kosovo Liberation 
Army. 
</P>
<P>
	``By killing people, by murdering children ... by destroying a  
whole nation, they want to protect a part of that population, one 
of its numerous ethnic minorities,'' Etinski said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the court does tell NATO to stop bombing, there's no  
guarantee the alliance will listen. 
</P>
<P>
	If the alliance ignores a court order to stop, Belgrade can only  
report it to the U.N. Security Council -- a body dominated by NATO 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts do not believe the 15-judge court will go as far as  
explicitly ordering a halt to the NATO bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the court will call upon all the states to abide by  
international law,'' said Andre Nollkaemper, a professor of 
international law at Amsterdam University. ``It's clear that NATO 
is on very difficult legal ground when it comes to justifying its 
airstrikes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States will present its case Tuesday. Yugoslav  
representatives had two hours to present their case today. Each 
NATO member will be given one hour to argue its side. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. Embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said Washington's message would be simple: ``The bottom line is we 
don't think the court should indicate provisional measures (to stop 
the bombing).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other NATO members are expected to say the same.  
</P>
<P>
	When NATO began airstrikes against Yugoslavia on March 24 in an  
effort to stop Belgrade's purge of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, it 
did so without waiting for a Security Council resolution granting 
it the right to use force. That has led many international law 
experts to question the legality of NATO's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given that this is legally very difficult to justify, it is a  
clever move by Belgrade to bring this into the spotlight,'' 
Nollkaemper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 06:39:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  China Breaks Off Arms Talks With US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China broke off talks on human rights and arms  
control with the United States today, and waves of demonstrators 
hurled stones at the U.S. Embassy in Beijing for a third day to 
protest NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also demanded that U.S. officials apologize for  
the NATO bombing, investigate the attack and punish those 
responsible. Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan issued the demands to 
U.S. Ambassador James Sasser, the state-run Xinhua News Agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Sasser and other American officials remained trapped today  
inside the U.S. Embassy compound, which was surrounded by hundreds 
of police in riot helmets and thousands of Chinese demonstrators. 
The protesters shouted, waved banners and threw stones in a repeat 
of Sunday's violent protest. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of halting the violence, police orchestrated the  
protest, directing the demonstrators past the U.S. and British 
embassies. Police also blocked nearby streets and ordered foreign 
reporters away from corners where they could see the embassy. 
</P>
<P>
	Many protesters were students, but others came in busloads of  
organized groups from companies. About 1,000 marched under a banner 
from government-owned China Aerospace Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests were the biggest in Beijing since the Tiananmen  
Square pro-democracy demonstrations 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are essentially hostages of the embassy at the present time  
now. We've been here 48 hours without being able to leave,'' Sasser 
told AP Network News by telephone Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some U.S. diplomats left an office building about three blocks  
away during a lull today and returned to their homes in Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	China suspended diplomatic relations regarding human rights,  
arms control and international security, Xinhua said, citing 
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension affected areas of key interest to the United  
States, including concerns that China has provided nuclear weapons 
or missile technology to Pakistan, Iran or other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In its demands, China called for an ``open and official''  
apology to the Chinese government, its people and the relatives of 
the three reporters killed in the attack in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials, led by President Clinton, have apologized to  
China for the error, and Defense Secretary William Cohen and CIA 
Director George Tenet have said the bombing resulted from faulty 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. State Department issued an advisory today warning  
Americans to postpone travel to China ``until the situation 
stabilizes.'' It said those in the country should avoid crowds and 
stay close to home. 
</P>
<P>
	Official travel by U.S. government employees to China has been  
suspended and those working in the country have been told to stay 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder announced that he will  
shorten his first official visit to China, which begins Wednesday, 
while Russia's top envoy for Kosovo, Viktor Chernomyrdin, was 
flying to Beijing today to discuss the crisis over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Chinese people have flown into furies'' over the attack on  
the Belgrade embassy, said the People's Daily, the main paper of 
the ruling Communist Party. Monday's commentary showed that the 
government has refused to accept the explanation by NATO and the 
United States that the bombing was an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anybody thinks he can intimidate the Chinese through the  
use of force, he will find himself completely wrong,'' the 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three people, all reported to be Chinese journalists, were  
killed in the bombing in Belgrade late Friday. More than 20 were 
injured, six seriously, the Chinese Foreign Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters were furious at what they saw as a deliberate attack  
on China. State-run media have not reported U.S. or NATO claims 
that it was an accident or their expressions of deep regret. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither have Chinese media reported the Serb attacks on ethnic  
Albanians in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo that NATO airstrikes 
were intended to stop. China has accused NATO of creating the 
refugee crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	About 100 students from Politics and Law University in Beijing  
marched past the U.S. embassy Sunday, chanting ``a debt in blood 
must be repaid in blood!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Demonstrators also attacked the British and Albanian embassies  
on Sunday and held protests outside U.S. consulates in Shanghai, 
Hong Kong, Guangzhou, Chengdu and in at least 16 other Chinese 
cities, state media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Consulate in the western city of Chengdu was damaged by  
fire Saturday after a break-in by protesters, U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Shanghai, police acting on a bomb threat evacuated an office  
building today that houses foreign companies. A bomb squad with 
dogs was sent in. The manager of the Dongyi Building said they 
found nothing, and tenants were allowed back in after three hours. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, thousands of people flowed past the main U.S. Embassy  
buildings in Beijing, smashing its windows with rocks and 
splattering its walls with paint. The Chinese government put the 
number of demonstrators at 20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials protested to the Chinese government that embassy  
security was inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao appealed for restraint in a  
nationwide television broadcast Sunday evening. He said the 
government supports ``legal protest activities'' but warned people 
to be vigilant against troublemakers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990510.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 06:39:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
