<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Streamlining Its Distribution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp.'s management team made its  
first major move Monday since a shakeup last month, slimming the 
number of distributors of many of its business-class products to 
four from about 40. 
</P>
<P>
	The change will allow Compaq, the world's largest personal  
computer maker, to reduce costs and improve customer contact by 
streamlining distribution, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that the efficiency gains of this program combined  
with more focused marketing programs will ultimately result in 
higher levels of customer satisfaction and enhance customer 
choice,'' said Peter Blackmore, a Compaq vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq held on to four longtime distribution partners: Omaha,  
Neb.-based Inacom Corp., Santa Ana, Calif.-based Ingram Micro Inc., 
Clearwater, Fla.-based Tech Data Corp. and El Segundo, Calif.-based 
Merisel Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first big change since chairman Ben Rosen and  
Compaq's board ousted president Eckhard Pfeiffer last month after a 
persistent slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts, who heard of the distribution moves Friday afternoon,  
have generally applauded the move. Stock prices for the four 
resellers rose on the news, and Compaq gained $1.50, or 6 percent, 
to close at $26.25. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to cut down their indirect relationships to  
focus more on the direct model,'' said Rob Enderle of the Giga 
Information Group. ``With fewer distributors to carry the load, it 
should result in a further reduction of costs and a potential 
increase in perceived quality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Enderle, who characterized the decision as ``clearly a step in  
the right direction,'' said Compaq's complex distribution system 
had added costs and detracted from customer relations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're proud to be part of Compaq's exciting new strategy, and  
we're confident that resellers will reap the benefits of the new 
distribution model through improved service levels,'' said Jim 
Illson, president of Merisel. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is part of Compaq's effort to forge a closer  
relationship with its larger customers without committing to direct 
sales, like competitors Gateway and Dell. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've leaving all their options open,'' Enderle said.  
``Their view is to provide the buyer with choice. If they want to 
buy from CompUSA (via resellers), OK. If they want to buy direct 
from Compaq, OK. Wherever the buyer goes, they want to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement also might make other PC giants IBM and  
Hewlett-Packard take notice, said analyst Kevin Knox of Gartner 
Group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Are IBM and HP going to follow suit, or does this make them  
stronger with channel players (distributors) who are not part of 
Compaq's program?'' Knox said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
