<HEADLINE> Lucent Chip Combines Phone, Web </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- Lucent Technologies said today it has  
developed a computer chip for phones that will help small- and 
mid-size businesses use their companies' computer networks to 
deliver voice calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The chip will help lower the cost of ``Internet phones'' from  
about $250 to $150 by decreasing the number of chips in a phone 
from five to one, the company said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet telephone systems converge voice and data using a  
single wall outlet jack. Typically, two connections on wall jacks 
are required -- one carrying voice and the other carrying data. 
</P>
<P>
	The market for these Internet telephone sets is expected to  
average annual growth of more than 250 percent for the next three 
years, according to the Murray Hill, N.J.-based company. 

</P>
</TEXT>
