<HEADLINE> Gas Prices Up in East, Down in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- Gas prices rose in most parts of the  
country, while dropping about 5 cents in the West as the effects of 
refinery problems wore off, an industry analyst said. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil price hikes caused pump prices to rise about 1 to 2  
cents per gallon in the East and Midwest, according to the Lundberg 
Survey of 10,000 stations nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The national weighted average, including all grades and taxes,  
was $1.2337 per gallon Friday, a 0.41 cent rise from two weeks 
earlier, analyst Trilby Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fatal explosions and problems in several California refineries  
caused prices to skyrocket in the West recently. However, increased 
supplies of gasoline have stabilized the market and are expected to 
continue knocking down prices in the West, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have risen more than 23 cents per gallon since they  
bottomed out on Feb. 19, but over the past month the increases have 
been very small, she said. ``It looks like they are losing 
momentum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A nationwide gasoline boycott organized for April 30 by consumer  
groups angry about price hikes succeeded in lowering sales on that 
day but may have had little long-term effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prices were down that day, but they were up the day before and  
the day after,'' Ms. Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC and Mexico's decision to cut back on oil production may  
continue to force gas prices slightly higher in other regions, Ms. 
Lundberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average prices at self-service stations was $1.1767 per  
gallon for regular gasoline, $1.2783 for mid-grade and $1.3628 for 
premium. 
</P>
<P>
	Full-service prices were $1.5356 for regular, $1.6220 for  
mid-grade and $1.6954 for premium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
