<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sees Economy Bouncing Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union's economy is  
beginning to bounce back from months of sluggish growth, EU finance 
ministers said Monday, adding that recovery won't be held back by 
the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong consumer confidence in Europe and signs of improvement in  
Asian economies were indications that the European slowdown is 
bottoming out, said Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm. 
</P>
<P>
	``All expectations show that the lowest point has been passed,''  
said Belgian Finance Minister Jean-Jacques Viseur. ``Growth will 
now accelerate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ministers were united in downplaying the potential for the  
Kosovo crisis to hinder European growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Kosovo conflict will have little impact,'' said Spanish  
Economy Minister Rodrigo Rato. ``The prospects of recuperation in 
the European economy are strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Ciampi bucked the optimistic  
trend with a statement warning the ``balance of risks'' for the 
European economy ``remains on the downside.'' However, he also 
predicted a resumption of economic activity in the second half of 
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	German Finance Minister Hans Eichel said the decline of the euro  
against the dollar since the EU single currency was launched by 11 
EU nations Jan. 1 was a natural result of stronger economic growth 
in the United States and ``did not require any particular 
measures'' from the EU. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the European Commission predicted economic growth in  
the 15-nation bloc would slow by 0.8 percentage points to 2.1 
percent this year. However, the mood has improved recently, helped 
by better export potential, lower interest rates and more bullish 
surveys of business sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's meeting was the EU finance ministers' first formal  
gathering since NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia began March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
