<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Wants Bomb Halt Before Talks  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- China is insisting that a halt to NATO's  
bombing of Yugoslavia is a prerequisite for any Security Council 
discussion of a Kosovo peace plan. Last week the seven major 
industrialized nations and Russia agreed to draft a resolution 
calling for the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from Kosovo and the 
deployment of an international security presence. NATO says it will 
continue airstrikes until these conditions are met. Today, at the 
start of a second council meeting called by China to condemn NATO's 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, U.N. Ambassador Qin 
Huasun made clear that Beijing won't discuss peace unless the 
bombing stops. 

</P>
<P>
	China Breaks Military Ties With US  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China broke off military ties with the United  
States today and demanded those responsible for NATO's bombing of 
its embassy in Yugoslavia be ``severely'' punished. President 
Clinton apologized anew, calling the bombing ``an isolated tragic 
mistake.'' U.S. officials blamed it on CIA misinformation. 
Meanwhile, Chinese authorities allowed waves of protesters to 
descend on the paint-spattered, debris-strewn U.S. Embassy in 
Beijing. Some hurled burning objects. Tibetan monks also joined the 
demonstrations. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Pullback Dismissed by NATO  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said NATO  
would continue its air campaign, despite Yugoslavia's announcement 
today of a partial military withdrawal from Kosovo. Cohen said he 
would consider a pause if Yugoslavia indicated its acceptance of 
all the alliance's demands and made a ``demonstrable'' start to a 
troop withdrawal. Meanwhile, NATO carried out daylight bombings on 
several towns in central and western Serbia, killing four civilians 
and smashing a factory in one 20-minute bombardment, Yugoslav media 
reported. 

</P>
<P>
	EU To Create Defense Policy  
</P>
<P>
	BREMEN, Germany (AP) -- European Union defense ministers pledged  
today to work toward a common security policy by December 2000. 
German Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping admitted it was a ``tight 
timetable'' given the persistent shortcomings of Europeans in 
defense matters. EU leaders will debate the issue in more detail at 
a summit next month in Cologne. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Charged in Columbine Attack  
</P>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- A 22-year-old man was formally charged  
today with providing a pistol to students who used it in the 
Columbine High School massacre. Mark Manes, a former Columbine 
student, has admitted selling the semiautomatic TEC DC-9 to Eric 
Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, who used it in the lunchtime 
attack. They killed 12 students and a teacher before killing 
themselves. Defense lawyer Robert Ransome said Manes did not know 
why the students wanted the gun and was horrified when he learned 
of the rampage. 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Car Marine Gets 6 Months  
</P>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine pilot was sentenced today to  
six months in prison and he was dismissed from the Corps for 
helping hide a videotape shot during a flight in which 20 people 
died when his jet cut a ski gondola cable in Italy. Capt. Richard 
Ashby also was ordered to forfeit all pay and allowance for his 
conviction on charges of obstruction of justice and conspiracy to 
obstruct. 

</P>
<P>
	Makah Indians Hunt for Whale  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Seven Makah Indians began hunting for a gray  
whale today -- the tribe's first such expedition since it won the 
right to restore the traditional hunts that had been banned for 70 
years. The whaling crew had intended to go on a practice run, but 
protesters were following their canoe, so the tribe issued a 10-day 
hunting permit that requires other vessels to stay at least 500 
yards away. 

</P>
<P>
	Kid's Author Shel Silverstein Dies  
</P>
<P>
	KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) -- Shel Silverstein, the author of such  
acclaimed children's books as ``A Light in the Attic'' and ``Where 
the Sidewalk Ends,'' was found dead at his home earlier today. He 
was 66. Silverstein won numerous awards for his work including the 
Michigan Young Readers Award for ``Where the Sidewalk Ends.'' The 
cause of death was not known. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Down  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices fell on Tuesday amid caution  
about current high price levels. The Nikkei fell 123.24 points to 
16,853.77 in early trading. In New York, the Dow finished down 
24.34 at 11,007.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra: 3 HRs, 10 RBIs  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra hit a pair of grand slams and a  
two-run homer, driving in 10 RBIs during Boston's game against 
Seattle tonight. Garciaparra hit his second career grand slam in 
the first inning, then hit another in the eighth for 12-3 Red Sox 
lead. The two-run homer came in the third inning. The 10 RBIs tied 
the Red Sox record, a mark accomplished by Fred Lynn in 1975 at 
Detroit. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
