<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Figure in Overthrow Plot Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A federal jury decided today that a  
white supremacist should get a life sentence, sparing him from the 
death penalty for killing a family as part of his plot to set up a 
whites-only nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had asked that Chevie Kehoe be put to death for the  
1996 killings of gun dealer William Mueller, his wife, Nancy, and 
her 8-year-old daughter, Sarah Powell. The three were suffocated 
with plastic bags, weighed down with rocks and tossed into a 
western Arkansas bayou during a robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	Kehoe appeared subdued as the sentence was read and made no  
comment afterward to reporters as U.S. marshals led him away in 
handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer, Mark Hampton, said ``It appears that the jury took a  
solemn approach to their duties, and this was a difficult decision, 
but mercy was shown to Chevie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors had only two choices in recommending sentence on the  
murder conviction, life in prison or the death penalty. When U.S. 
District Judge G. Thomas Eisele formally pronounces sentence, his 
only option will be a life sentence as the jury recommended. 
Besides the formal sentencing on the murder count, Eisele will 
decide the penalties for lesser charges. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a brief delay in announcing the verdict because Eisele  
had to send the mostly black jury back to its deliberating room to 
sign a form declaring the decision was reached without regard for 
Kehoe's race or religious beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kehoe, 26, of Colville, Wash., and codefendant Danny Lee, 26, of  
Yukon, Okla., were found guilty last Tuesday of murder, 
racketeering and conspiracy. They were accused of trying to 
overthrow the government and set up the Aryan Peoples Republic in 
the Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel considered Kehoe's fate first. A hearing on Lee's  
penalty is scheduled to begin Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In deciding Kehoe's sentence, jurors apparently were persuaded  
by the defense argument that Kehoe came from a dysfunctional 
family. They argued that he was influenced by his parents, 
particularly his father, Kirby Kehoe, and other adults who held 
extremist political and social views. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers had argued it was possible that Kehoe's brother,  
Cheyne, who testified against Chevie Kehoe, actually killed the 
Muellers. They said Cheyne was motivated to testify because he 
wants a sentencing reduction in Ohio, where the two brothers were 
convicted in a 1997 videotaped shootout with police. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors would not comment on the sentencing. A gag order  
remains in place for lawyers and parties connected to the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimma Gurel, Mrs. Mueller's sister, said her family would have  
been satisfied with either a death sentence or life without parole. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the weekend, we talked about it, and justified it that  
either way we were winning, because they're not going to be out and 
able to do anything to someone else. Being in prison might be 
worse,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
