<HEADLINE> Astros Coach Sidelined 3-4 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) - Houston Astros first-base coach Jose Cruz will be  
sidelined for 3-4 weeks for treatment of an irregular heartbeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``This condition is not considered serious, but Jose will be  
taking blood thinners which will prevent him from being in uniform 
for three to four weeks,'' Houston general manager Gerry Hunsicker 
said Monday prior to the Astros' game against the Pittsburgh 
Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately Jose will undergo electronic stimulation to try and  
put his heart rate back at a normal rhythm,'' Hunsicker said. 
``This is a common procedure, President Bush underwent the same 
thing a few years ago and so did one of our scouts, Walter 
Matthews.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cruz, 51, was not at Monday's game because of the condition,  
known as arhythmia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to him this afternoon and he's very upbeat as  
usual,'' Houston manager Larry Dierker said. ``He's not letting it 
get him down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 19 seasons, Cruz set Houston career records for at bats  
(6,629), hits (1,937), triples (80), RBIs (942) and total bases 
(2,746). His son, Jose Jr., plays for the Toronto Blue Jays. 
</P>
<P>
	During Cruz' absence, bullpen coach John Tamargo will take over  
first-base coaching duties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
