<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Skeptical About Yugoslav Withdrawal  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- U.S. and NATO officials are  
skeptical about Yugoslavia's announcement that is has withdrawn 
part of its military and police forces from Kosovo. Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright said even if statement is true, it's still 
a ``half measure'' and not enough to halt NATO airstrikes against 
Serb targets. A NATO spokesman said the report must be ``treated 
with caution.'' But he said a withdrawal could be a sign that the 
Serbs are feeling the effects of the bombing campaign, which began 
March 24. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Apologizes for Embassy Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton apologized anew today for  
the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, calling it ``an 
isolated tragic mistake.'' But he said NATO airstrikes will 
continue against Yugoslavia. Clinton said it was important to 
distinguish between the accidental bombing of the embassy and 
Slobodan Milosevic's policy of ``ethnic cleansing'' to drive ethnic 
Albanians from Kosovo. Meanwhile, the White House said protests in 
China were cooling. 

</P>
<P>
	US: 90 Pct. of Kosovars Expelled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 90 percent of all ethnic Albanians  
have been expelled from their homes in Kosovo by Serb forces and 
Serb civilians, the State Department said today. An estimated 
600,000 refugees are still in the Serbian province, struggling to 
survive, the report said. Another 700,000 have gone to Albania, 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Macedonia or Montenegro, the smaller of 
Yugoslav's two republics. Another 130,000 found temporary haven in 
other countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Holds Anti-Violence Conference  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton has opened a meeting with  
entertainment industry leaders and parents and teachers concerning 
youth violence and said, ``we are not here to place blame.'' The 
summit is meant to produce ideas on how to curb violence involving 
children in the wake of a rampage at a Colorado high school. Among 
those invited were executives from the movie and video games 
industry, Internet experts, and gunmakers. 

</P>
<P>
	Bubonic Plague Confirmed in Namibia  
</P>
<P>
	WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) -- Local medical authorities confirmed  
today an outbreak of bubonic plague in Namibia's populous 
north-central region that has killed three of the 73 people with 
the disease. Bubonic plague, also known as the Black Death, killed 
an estimated 25 million people in Europe between 1346 and 1351, 
wiping out nearly one-third of the population. The disease is 
transmitted by fleas infecting rats which in turn infect humans. If 
left untreated, it can kill within three to five days. Today, it is 
easily treatable by powerful modern antibiotics. 

</P>
<P>
	U S West Plans Phone-Computer Hybrid  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U S West plans later this year to become the  
first phone company to sell two new telephone-computer hybrids that 
feature one-button dialing to the Internet and other simplified 
ways to use the Web. The plug-in WebTouch phones made by Alcatel of 
France will be available this fall and U S West will offer wireless 
service for Qualcomm's Thin Phone by the end of the year. The new 
phones operate much the same way as a personal computer uses a 
modem to dial the user's Internet service, but reduces the process 
to one step. The Alcatel phone is expected to sell for several 
hundred dollars. 

</P>
<P>
	NBC, Xoom.com, Snap.com Join Forces  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is joining forces with Web directory service  
Snap.com and Xoom.com, an electronic commerce site, to form a new 
Internet company in an attempt to broaden its online presence. The 
new company, NBC Internet or NBCi, will operate under the Snap name 
online but will include content from NBC and the trademark peacock 
brand. MSNBC, a 50-50 news partnership between NBC and Microsoft, 
was not part of the deal and will continue to operate on its own. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 39  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 39.23 to 11,070.82. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,706-1,192. The Nasdaq was up 25.34 to 
2,528.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Armstrong Wins NBA Sixth Man Award  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darrell Armstrong, the Orlando Magic's spunky  
point guard, easily won the NBA Sixth Man Award today as the 
league's best player off the bench. The 6-foot-1 guard averaged 
career highs in points (13.8), assists (6.7), rebounds (3.6) and 
steals (2.16) this season. He received 85 out of a possible 118 
votes from a panel of sports writers and broadcasters. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

</P>
