<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Playoffs Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	As defending Stanley Cup champions, the Detroit Red Wings have  
been regarded as the team to beat in the playoffs. So far, nobody 
has been able to do that. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings are 6-0 in the postseason, and going home for two  
games following Sunday's 4-0 victory at Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing with lots of energy,'' Colorado coach Bob  
Hartley said. ``They're playing better as a team than we are right 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's victory was a little easier for the Red Wings than the  
opener of their Western Conference semifinal series, a 3-2 overtime 
thriller. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never talked about going home up 2-0,'' Red Wings captain  
Steve Yzerman said. ``By no means can we relax. They could get back 
into this one if we aren't careful. Remember, the Avalanche have a 
great road record (3-0 in the playoffs), better than at home 
(1-4).'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other games Sunday, Buffalo beat Boston 3-1 and Toronto  
defeated Pittsburgh 4-2 to tie each of those Eastern Conference 
series at a game apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	The playoffs continue tonight with Dallas at St. Louis holding a  
2-0 lead in their best-of-7 Western Conference semifinal series. 
</P>
<P>
	Yzerman scored two goals and Bill Ranford gained his fourth  
career playoff shutout to lead the Red Wings, who won their 11th 
straight playoff game dating to last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit, seeking a third consecutive Stanley Cup, gave coach  
Scotty Bowman his 200th career playoff win -- extending his NHL 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Yzerman scored in each of the first two periods, giving him  
eight goals in the playoffs to equal a career high. Nicklas 
Lidstrom and Wendel Clark added power-play goals in the final 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranford, the 1990 NHL playoff MVP with Edmonton, started his  
second straight game in goal in place of the injured Chris Osgood, 
who is out with a sprained right knee. He had 28 saves, preserving 
his shutout with a diving stop on Peter Forsberg late in the first 
period and with back-to-back stops on Theo Fleury and Sylvain 
Lefebvre in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys played unbelievably in front of me,'' Ranford said.  
``There were times when I didn't see the puck, and they were able 
to block it out for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Roy had 33 saves in the Colorado net.  
</P>
<P>
	Games 3 and 4 will be played in Detroit on Tuesday and  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
                         *Sabres 3, Bruins 1    	
</P>
<P>
	Goaltender Dominik Hasek, rebounding from an opening-game loss,  
looked more like the NHL's two-time MVP as the visiting Sabres beat 
the Bruins. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, looking a lot sharper than he did in the Sabres' 4-2 loss  
to Boston on Thursday, stopped 28 of 29 shots this time as Buffalo 
wiped out the Bruins' home-ice advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek seemed headed for his fifth career playoff shutout before  
Don Sweeney scored on a power play with 5:57 left in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Peca, Curtis Brown and Dixon Ward scored for the Sabres,  
who will host the next two games of the series on Wednesday and 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Maple Leafs 4, Penguins 2    	
</P>
<P>
	Mats Sundin broke out of his scoring slump to lead the Maple  
Leafs over the visiting Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	Sundin scored his second and third postseason goals and assisted  
on goals by Steve Thomas and Lonny Bohonos, recently brought up 
from the minors to start on the Maple Leafs' first line. 
</P>
<P>
	Kip Miller and German Titov beat Curtis Joseph, who was  
otherwise at his acrobatic best. 
</P>
<P>
	The series switches to Pittsburgh for Games 3 and 4 on Tuesday  
and Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
