<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Exec Explains Cole Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- An investigation of IOC member Phil  
Coles will focus on possible ``linkage'' between repeated trips to 
Salt Lake City and any services given to Olympic bidders there, a 
committee leader said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevan Gosper, an International Olympic Committee executive board  
member from Australia, said Coles' behavior ``somewhat reflects a 
continuous pattern of misjudgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Gosper denied speculation that he had been sent to Sydney by  
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch to fire Coles or force his 
resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be quite unusual for me to come out here, an  
investigation having been set up, to tell Phil Coles what he should 
do and what he shouldn't do,'' Gosper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has been severely warned by IOC leaders for accepting  
lavish travel and other benefits from Salt Lake bidders, and is now 
under investigation for further allegations of abusing his Olympic 
positions. 
</P>
<P>
	His ex-wife has told the IOC that the couple received jewelry  
valued at $6,000 from a businessman associated with the Athens bid 
for the 1996 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	And news reports last week in the United States and Australia  
said Coles and his current partner, Patricia Rosenbrock, had 
written notes on 400 pages of Australian government reviews of IOC 
members that were conducted for Sydney's successful bid for the 
2000 Games but passed on to Salt Lake's 2002 bid committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has denied any wrongdoing.  
</P>
<P>
	Gosper, in an interview with the Australian Broadcasting Corp.,  
said the three-member IOC panel appointed last week would 
investigate ``whether there was any linkage in any chain of events 
which works backwards from the original investigation into Phil's 
many visits to Salt Lake City after the bid was won by that city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper met with his Australian colleague Monday and said he  
filled in Coles on the latest inquiry. He said there was no plot to 
oust Coles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know of no persons, I know of no information that suggests  
there is a conspiracy against Phil Coles -- and I told him that,'' 
Gosper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has been the target of repeated calls to resign from the  
IOC or from the board of the Sydney Organizing Committee for the 
Olympic Games. The latest came early Monday from Jackie Kelly, 
Australia's sports minister. 
</P>
<P>
	``His time has come,'' Kelly said.  
</P>
<P>
	Coles has stepped aside from SOCOG pending the IOC  
investigations but he expects to be cleared and to return to the 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	``My position has not changed,'' Coles said. ``I have to appear  
before the (IOC) and Mr. Gosper has no role to play in that. The 
(IOC) meeting will take place and I'll present my case and I'll be 
cleared.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
