<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest/KLM, Alitalia To Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Northwest Airlines and KLM Royal Dutch  
Airlines are adding Alitalia Italian Airlines to their partnership 
in flights across the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	The airlines will submit a joint application Tuesday to the U.S.  
Department of Transportation for antitrust clearance, allowing 
Alitalia, KLM and Northwest to coordinate their trans-Atlantic 
route networks. 
</P>
<P>
	The new alliance means the airlines will list each other's  
flights in their computers and coordinate frequent-flyer plans. 
Doug Steenland, a vice president with Northwest, said customers can 
expect lower fares and the convenience of seamless flights. 
</P>
<P>
	Steenland also he expects the alliance to boost profits and  
revenue for all three airlines in the coming years. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Rosso, a vice president with Alitalia, said his company  
studied other partnership possibilities before deciding to join 
Northwest and KLM. 
</P>
<P>
	``We concluded that the joint-venture approach ... used by  
Northwest and KLM was the best example to really enhance a 
corporation with the best results that you can forecast on paper,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the alliance, the airlines would coordinate schedules at  
U.S. and Italian hubs and gateways. It also would include joint 
pricing and inventory management, as well as sharing of facilities 
services, marketing, advertising and sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Alliances are becoming increasingly common in the international  
aviation industry, where travel is booming. Leading airlines 
realized long ago it wouldn't be feasible to get big enough to 
cover the entire globe single-handedly. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest and KLM began code-sharing in 1993. KLM and Alitalia  
entered an alliance in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing a University of Illinois study on the benefits of  
international alliances, Northwest officials said last week their 
alliance with KLM has saved passengers between $110 million and 
$180 million annually because of lower fares. Jon Austin, a 
spokesman for Northwest, said the addition of Alitalia could 
produce even larger savings. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
