<HEADLINE> May Stores Earnings Climb 17 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The May Department Stores Co.'s first-quarter  
earnings climbed more than 17 percent from a year ago, boosted by a 
surge in sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis-based retailer reported Monday that it earned $122  
million, or 34 cents a share, compared with $110 million, or 29 
cents a share in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were $2.94 billion, up from $2.72 billion last year.  
</P>
<P>
	May's results topped Wall Street analysts' estimates, but its  
stock closed down 43 3/4 cents at $44.50 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	May discontinued its consumer electronics business at the  
beginning of fiscal 1999, which depressed its sales figures by 
about 1 percent for the quarter and the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	During the quarter, the board of directors authorized the  
repurchase of up to $500 million of May shares during 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	May opened two new stores in the first quarter, one in Nittany  
Mall in Pennsylvania and a Famous-Barr store in Kentucky. The 
company plans to open 16 additional new stores this year. 
</P>
<P>
	May now operates 394 department stores in 32 states and the  
District of Columbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
