<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta's Crawford Injured in Game 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Hawks forward Chris Crawford separated  
his right shoulder Monday night when he tumbled to the court after 
a tip-in during Game 2 of the first-round playoff series against 
Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawford scored the first six points for the Hawks, the last  
basket coming as he tipped in a missed shot by Mookie Blaylock with 
9:08 remaining in the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-9 forward stretched out to reach the ball and fell to  
the court, landing hard on his right shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Crawford, taken to the locker room for X-rays, returned to the  
bench in the second half wearing street clothes. He was diagnosed 
with a minor separation and listed as day to day. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the injury, Atlanta won 89-69 for a 2-0 lead in the  
best-of-5 series. Game 3 is Wednesday night in Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just had this freak accident happen,'' Crawford said.  
``Hopefully, I'll come back in a little bit and be all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The injury further depleted the Hawks' depth.  
</P>
<P>
	Crawford started the final 30 games of the regular season after  
LaPhonso Ellis was sidelined with a sports hernia. Forward Alan 
Henderson, still suffering double vision caused by a severe 
abrasion to his left eye, did not play Monday after working only 
four minutes in Game 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
