<DOCNO> APW19990510.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:34:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jagr Works To Regain Scoring Touch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The playoffs clearly have hit a critical stage  
for the Pittsburgh Penguins -- even Jaromir Jagr senses the need to 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr did not skate Monday during the Penguins' optional off-day  
practice for Tuesday night's Game 3 against the Toronto Maple 
Leafs, but did put on his practice gear to work on restoring his 
shooting touch. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr has rested on off days since straining a groin muscle  
during the first game of the New Jersey series, and the NHL scoring 
champion said the practice layoff has affected his shooting, 
judgment and confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	His statistics, too: He has no goals and only one assist in two  
games despite taking his regular shifts against Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get the puck in the slot and I don't know whether to shoot  
or pass,'' Jagr said. ``The confidence isn't there. You get 
confidence in practice, but I haven't been practicing. I'm taking 
that extra second to shoot it. I've got to fix it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr realizes the Penguins must be accurate on their scoring  
opportunities because Maple Leafs goaltender Curtis Joseph is 
playing so well, allowing only 12 goals in eight playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph turned aside 25 of 27 shots as Toronto evened the series  
by winning 4-2 Sunday in Toronto. Just as important for the Maple 
Leafs, Mats Sundin came out of a slump with two goals and two 
assists and Lonny Bohonos scored the first goal in his first NHL 
playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	``That gave us our confidence back, especially knowing that Tom  
Barrasso had shut us out (2-0) in Game 1,'' the Maple Leafs' Steve 
Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins need Jagr to do the same, but the groin injury has  
stripped him of his ability to dominate games with his skating, 
stickhandling and shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's tough for me is I can't use my speed,'' he said. ``All  
I can use is my hands. I can't challenge one on one and that's the 
worst thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr needs to take off several days to let the groin injury heal  
properly, but that's not possible while playing every other day. 
Yet the longer the injury persists, the more it affects his play. 
</P>
<P>
	After scoring two goals in the Penguins' momentum-swinging  
victory in Game 6 against New Jersey and setting up two goals in 
Game 7, he is 0-for-6 shooting in this series. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, coach Kevin Constantine said Jagr is capable of helping  
the Penguins even at 60 to 70 percent efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	``He would be a positive to us if he were breathing,'' he said.  
``He's just a talent. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a competitive person who wants to help. He puts aside the  
pain and plays. The possibility of him doing something is strong, 
whether he's injured or not. He feels he will do something along 
the way that will help us win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr plans to keep playing unless he aggravates the injury.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to improve day by day, but I can't pull it  
or make it worse,'' Jagr said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maple Leafs haven't resorted to hooking or whacking Jagr's  
injured right leg, as the Devils did in a seemingly blatant attempt 
to reinjure him after Jagr returned in Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``Toronto hasn't done that yet, but don't tell them that,'' Jagr  
said, laughing. 
</P>
